[SPEAKER_13]: Do we, oh, do you want to do that first?

142
00:12:03,343 --> 00:12:03,903
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, we need to vote.

143
00:12:03,923 --> 00:12:04,504
[SPEAKER_07]: We need to vote on that.

144
00:12:04,524 --> 00:12:04,644
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

145
00:12:04,704 --> 00:12:05,304
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry about that.

146
00:12:05,404 --> 00:12:11,007
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion of Councilor Lazaro to take those papers out of order, seconded by Councilor Callahan.

147
00:12:11,467 --> 00:12:12,348
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

148
00:12:13,848 --> 00:12:14,689
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan.

149
00:12:16,130 --> 00:12:16,850
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming.

150
00:12:17,510 --> 00:12:17,810
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

151
00:12:19,071 --> 00:12:19,711
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Malayne.

152
00:12:19,972 --> 00:12:20,032
Yes.

153
00:12:21,072 --> 00:12:21,853
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scarpelli.

154
00:12:21,873 --> 00:12:21,973
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

155
00:12:23,133 --> 00:12:23,754
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Singh.

156
00:12:23,774 --> 00:12:24,994
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

157
00:12:25,014 --> 00:12:25,935
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro.

158
00:12:26,135 --> 00:12:26,315
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

159
00:12:26,994 --> 00:12:27,714
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Beers.

160
00:12:27,875 --> 00:12:31,897
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, I'm in the affirmative, none in the negative, the motion passes.

161
00:12:31,917 --> 00:12:38,580
[SPEAKER_07]: 26127, communications from city officers and employees submitted by Medford Public Schools, resolution to establish a special education reserve fund for Medford.

162
00:12:39,060 --> 00:12:50,346
[SPEAKER_07]: Whereas the Medford Public Schools district experiences significant and recurring volatility in special education expenditures driven by statutory obligations to provide appropriate services and by student enrollment challenges occurring throughout the year.

163
00:12:50,906 --> 00:13:15,116
[SPEAKER_07]: whereas the number of students requiring special education services in Medford has grown substantially over the past three years with a 2% cumulative increase in students with IEPs and individualized education plans and an 83% increase in students requiring one-on-one paraprofessional support, a 24% increase in students without a district placements, a 7% increase in students requiring specialized transportation, placing increasing pressure on the district's annual budget.

164
00:13:18,610 --> 00:13:30,699
[SPEAKER_07]: This is a long one but it looks like we also have students requiring special education fluctuating significantly during the school year, an influx of move-ins during the year, 73 additional students, a 4% increase.

165
00:13:32,100 --> 00:13:39,025
[SPEAKER_07]: So increase in move-ins with IEPs requiring one-on-one paras, students requiring out-of-district placements or requiring specialized transportation.

166
00:13:39,645 --> 00:13:49,134
[SPEAKER_07]: Whereas special education expenditures in Medford increased 27 percent between fiscal 23 and 25 and the corresponding funding from the city's general funding grants increased only 17 percent.

167
00:13:49,675 --> 00:14:01,447
[SPEAKER_07]: Whereas federal individuals disabilities education act grant faces growing instability from federal budget disputes and policy priorities including an 8 percent reduction in the federal allocation between fiscal 24 and 25.

168
00:14:03,108 --> 00:14:12,771
[SPEAKER_07]: Whereas, Massachusetts General Law authorizes municipal and regional school districts to establish a special education reserve fund that can be used in future years for unanticipated or unbudgeted cost of special education.

169
00:14:13,392 --> 00:14:26,476
[SPEAKER_07]: Whereas, Mass General Law Chapter 40, Section 13E enables the establishment of a special education reserve fund through majority vote of both the school committee and the city council to mitigate these fiscal risks provided that the fund balance does not exceed 2% of annual net school spending amount.

170
00:14:27,578 --> 00:14:35,811
[SPEAKER_07]: Whereas establishment of such a fund provides a proactive and strategic approach planning for unforeseeable special education costs and to provide stability in the delivery of public education.

171
00:14:35,831 --> 00:14:42,782
[SPEAKER_07]: And whereas the school committee has determined that establishing this fund is prudent financial management aligned with the district's responsibility.

172
00:14:43,427 --> 00:14:58,320
[SPEAKER_07]: be resolved by the school committee that we accept the provisions of general law chapter 40 section 13E, directing the superintendent to email a copy of this resolution to the council and the acting city clerk to place this resolution on their June 23rd council agenda for their vote.

173
00:14:58,940 --> 00:15:27,578
[SPEAKER_07]: Establishing a special reserve fund for the Medford public schools to pay without further appropriation for unanticipated or unbudgeted costs of special education services and specifying that the reserve fund shall be funded through transfers of year-end balances and surpluses from the annual school operating budget approved by the school committee, free cash appropriations as determined by the school committee and city council, interest and earnings on the fund balance which shall be automatically credited to the fund and any other permissible revenue sources as approved by a majority vote of the school committee and city council.

174
00:15:28,627 --> 00:15:32,888
[SPEAKER_07]: requiring that any distribution be authorized by a majority vote of the school committee and city council.

175
00:15:33,168 --> 00:15:43,231
[SPEAKER_07]: All distributions shall be approved only by majority vote of both bodies and no distribution will be made without prior written request from the superintendent of schools or designated school administrator.

176
00:15:43,711 --> 00:15:51,313
[SPEAKER_07]: The limiting balance of the reserve fund to 2%, establishing a minimum balance of 200,000 in the interest bearing reserve fund once that level has been achieved.

177
00:15:52,153 --> 00:16:04,697
[SPEAKER_07]: and affirming that the reserve fund is complimentary to and shall not replace other district financial management practices, including the circuit breaker reimbursement program, budgeting for anticipated special education costs and maintaining emergency reserves for general operating contingencies.

178
00:16:04,857 --> 00:16:14,459
[SPEAKER_07]: And finally, directing the school committee to report to the community annually on the status of the special education reserve fund and its role in maintaining fiscal stability and program quality and special education services.

179
00:16:15,119 --> 00:16:17,040
[SPEAKER_07]: I hope you will appreciate my live copy of it.

180
00:16:17,828 --> 00:16:20,269
[SPEAKER_07]: That was about 30% longer than what I just said.

181
00:16:20,609 --> 00:16:26,030
[SPEAKER_07]: So I will turn it over to Superintendent Galussi, School Committee Member Parks, Director Velas.

182
00:16:29,311 --> 00:16:29,491
[SPEAKER_17]: Go ahead.

183
00:16:30,771 --> 00:16:34,532
[SPEAKER_28]: Thank you very much for having us be here and for taking it out of order.

184
00:16:34,552 --> 00:16:36,213
[SPEAKER_28]: We do appreciate that very much.

185
00:16:37,093 --> 00:16:39,634
[SPEAKER_28]: This was a resolution that's near and dear to

186
00:16:41,059 --> 00:16:44,060
[SPEAKER_28]: Member Parks, and the Medford Public Schools.

187
00:16:44,801 --> 00:16:45,861
[SPEAKER_28]: I'm going to have Ms.

188
00:16:45,941 --> 00:16:51,584
[SPEAKER_28]: Parks do the framing, and then we are happy to answer any questions that you may have.

189
00:16:53,577 --> 00:16:54,197
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

190
00:16:54,217 --> 00:16:55,678
[SPEAKER_23]: Welcome.

191
00:16:56,638 --> 00:16:56,898
[SPEAKER_23]: Thanks.

192
00:16:57,278 --> 00:16:58,878
[SPEAKER_23]: So thank you.

193
00:17:00,419 --> 00:17:11,601
[SPEAKER_23]: So this came about from attending the Massachusetts Association of School Committee Members training for new school committee members.

194
00:17:11,961 --> 00:17:21,404
[SPEAKER_23]: And I learned it was probably one of the most impactful financial tools for addressing special education

195
00:17:24,464 --> 00:17:31,846
[SPEAKER_23]: And it kind of immediately struck me as something Medford needed to explore, and it became kind of my mission to bring it back to Medford.

196
00:17:32,626 --> 00:17:38,767
[SPEAKER_23]: As a district, our special education services are a legal and moral obligation, but the costs can be highly unpredictable.

197
00:17:39,507 --> 00:17:50,169
[SPEAKER_23]: A sudden need for an out-of-district placement or specialized transportation can emerge mid-year as students move in and out of the district, creating immediate financial strain.

198
00:17:50,796 --> 00:18:00,601
[SPEAKER_23]: and we are already seeing instability in federal funding, such as the recent 8% reduction in our IDEA grants, which only underscores this vulnerability.

199
00:18:01,382 --> 00:18:13,428
[SPEAKER_23]: So establishing this reserve fund will provide us with a dedicated financial safety net, and it allows us to capture unspent funds and save them in an interest-bearing account.

200
00:18:14,388 --> 00:18:16,970
[SPEAKER_23]: for these unanticipated costs.

201
00:18:17,110 --> 00:18:25,535
[SPEAKER_23]: It protects our general operating budget and ensures we don't have to scramble or make painful cuts elsewhere to provide required services.

202
00:18:26,696 --> 00:18:38,703
[SPEAKER_23]: And I really just want to thank our finance team, our special education leadership, and the superintendent's office, because without them, all of the information to put this together would not have been made possible.

203
00:18:40,757 --> 00:18:52,763
[SPEAKER_23]: We recognize that we're establishing this with a $0 balance, but we want to have it in place should we be able to have funds to put in it at any time.

204
00:18:56,529 --> 00:19:03,453
[SPEAKER_28]: The only thing I would just add to that, especially if there are people listening at home, is that per general law, school committee has approved.

205
00:19:03,733 --> 00:19:05,014
[SPEAKER_28]: You also have to approve.

206
00:19:05,515 --> 00:19:12,899
[SPEAKER_28]: And as, fingers crossed, we hope to grow this so that we have this, as Member Park said, safety net.

207
00:19:13,619 --> 00:19:25,286
[SPEAKER_28]: It does require, so if we feel that there are unforeseen, unanticipated special education costs that we were not, that weren't budgeted for, that happen that we may want to use this fund,

208
00:19:26,413 --> 00:19:34,615
[SPEAKER_28]: I have to make that recommendation to both school committee and this body for approval for use of the funds.

209
00:19:36,936 --> 00:19:39,456
[SPEAKER_28]: So we're here for the first phase of your approval tonight.

210
00:19:40,817 --> 00:19:41,197
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

211
00:19:41,217 --> 00:19:42,997
[SPEAKER_07]: Madam Superintendent, Vice President Lazaro.

212
00:19:45,338 --> 00:19:45,678
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

213
00:19:45,738 --> 00:19:52,419
[SPEAKER_13]: I want to thank school committee member Parks for bringing this forward, bringing this to our attention.

214
00:19:55,538 --> 00:20:23,978
[SPEAKER_13]: One thing I learned when I was working for the school district years ago is that I'm not sure that this is the reason for this particular influx but something that I didn't know before having the job that I had is that private schools and charter schools not all private schools but charter schools don't have the same obligation to educate all students

215
00:20:24,585 --> 00:20:25,486
[SPEAKER_13]: that public schools do.

216
00:20:26,227 --> 00:20:33,457
[SPEAKER_13]: And sometimes a family may not be aware that a student has special needs until they begin at a school.

217
00:20:34,320 --> 00:20:49,208
[SPEAKER_13]: And if they're in a certain charter school, which is a public school, they may learn that their student has special needs that that school is not equipped to tackle.

218
00:20:49,728 --> 00:20:58,213
[SPEAKER_13]: So then the family may decide to change schools, and then the student comes to Medford Public Schools, where we do have an obligation to educate every student.

219
00:20:59,713 --> 00:21:00,814
[SPEAKER_13]: And that costs a lot more money.

220
00:21:01,620 --> 00:21:23,388
[SPEAKER_13]: and it sometimes is reflected in things like school ratings and the expense of transportation and paraprofessionals and all kinds of you know different areas that we we don't we don't encounter a lot of this stuff in city council but I saw a lot of discussions of it in

221
00:21:24,282 --> 00:21:27,344
[SPEAKER_13]: school committee meetings and we have talked a bit about about it.

222
00:21:27,704 --> 00:21:32,727
[SPEAKER_13]: Councilor Scarpelli and Councilor Lemming talking about special education stuff.

223
00:21:32,747 --> 00:21:40,872
[SPEAKER_13]: It just it costs a lot of money and it is our obligation as the city to educate every single student that needs to be educated in Medford.

224
00:21:41,112 --> 00:21:53,740
[SPEAKER_13]: And it makes a lot of sense to me that we would be thoughtful and preventive about having a reserve fund and trying to make sure that we don't

225
00:21:54,830 --> 00:22:04,094
[SPEAKER_13]: play catch up and try to make sure that we're putting money that's available in a fund where we can access it beforehand.

226
00:22:04,855 --> 00:22:13,699
[SPEAKER_13]: The other thing is it takes a long time to establish these things, and then when you funnel money into the fund, you can build it up over time.

227
00:22:14,059 --> 00:22:20,702
[SPEAKER_13]: So much like other, you know, stabilization funds and the Affordable Housing Trust and things that we've established over the last few years,

228
00:22:21,473 --> 00:22:26,596
[SPEAKER_13]: this is just like that, but I didn't know it existed until Member Parks brought it to our attention.

229
00:22:26,636 --> 00:22:31,579
[SPEAKER_13]: So thank you very much, greatly appreciated, and a motion to approve.

230
00:22:33,620 --> 00:22:34,021
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

231
00:22:34,101 --> 00:22:34,701
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Scarpelli.

232
00:22:34,721 --> 00:22:35,341
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

233
00:22:35,522 --> 00:22:38,103
[SPEAKER_21]: Again, thank you, School Board Member Parks.

234
00:22:38,744 --> 00:22:50,931
[SPEAKER_21]: Our team, I think, as a former educator, I think my colleagues bring up good points, and I think that if we can establish a fund that we can jump ahead

235
00:22:51,373 --> 00:22:56,897
[SPEAKER_21]: and take care of situations before they escalate and before it becomes a huge money issue.

236
00:22:57,298 --> 00:23:00,240
[SPEAKER_21]: And then we're sitting at the end of this and saying, what do we cut?

237
00:23:00,280 --> 00:23:00,861
[SPEAKER_21]: What do we lose?

238
00:23:00,901 --> 00:23:02,182
[SPEAKER_21]: Because we didn't prepare ourselves.

239
00:23:02,622 --> 00:23:11,249
[SPEAKER_21]: I think this gives us a unique opportunity to really support the most vulnerable members in our school department, and that's our special needs community.

240
00:23:11,289 --> 00:23:15,312
[SPEAKER_21]: So, you know, it's one thing that I've taken ownership of my personal life.

241
00:23:15,890 --> 00:23:35,431
[SPEAKER_21]: working in recreation we've taken deep passion and extra steps to identify programs for kids with special needs and I think that this is a valuable tool that we'll have in the school department so I think that

242
00:23:37,662 --> 00:23:40,004
[SPEAKER_21]: I appreciate it, the transparency behind it.

243
00:23:40,264 --> 00:23:47,971
[SPEAKER_21]: It's something that's going to be an open process where we can all talk about it, and we know exactly where the money's going to help the most vulnerable.

244
00:23:47,991 --> 00:23:48,431
[SPEAKER_21]: So, thank you.

245
00:23:49,292 --> 00:23:49,732
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

246
00:23:50,633 --> 00:23:50,873
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

247
00:23:50,893 --> 00:23:51,574
[SPEAKER_08]: Councillor Sy.

248
00:23:52,354 --> 00:23:54,456
[SPEAKER_09]: We've got a long agenda, so I'll be brief.

249
00:23:58,040 --> 00:23:59,481
[SPEAKER_09]: Don't worry, I have a 10-minute speech prepared.

250
00:24:01,382 --> 00:24:09,267
[SPEAKER_09]: No, all I want to say is I think we know that for the schools and for the city, opportunity for all is guiding principle.

251
00:24:10,109 --> 00:24:22,113
[SPEAKER_09]: This is an opportunity for us to tell those who've been traditionally overlooked for a long time that we do prioritize them, that we see them, that we want to invest.

252
00:24:23,133 --> 00:24:28,655
[SPEAKER_09]: And I know that public schools has been doing it for a long time, putting that focus on them.

253
00:24:28,735 --> 00:24:36,037
[SPEAKER_09]: But this is, I think, an additional tool for us to be able to serve our residents and our students better.

254
00:24:41,021 --> 00:24:41,701
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Singh.

255
00:24:42,201 --> 00:24:42,601
[SPEAKER_07]: So brief.

256
00:24:46,042 --> 00:24:48,223
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there any further discussion by members of the council?

257
00:24:50,504 --> 00:24:54,185
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, on the motion of Vice President Lazaro to approve, seconded by Councilor Scarpelli.

258
00:24:55,025 --> 00:24:55,905
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

259
00:24:57,706 --> 00:24:58,526
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan?

260
00:24:59,586 --> 00:24:59,786
Yes.

261
00:25:00,426 --> 00:25:01,067
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming?

262
00:25:01,827 --> 00:25:02,147
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

263
00:25:03,527 --> 00:25:04,007
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Maloney?

264
00:25:04,027 --> 00:25:04,087
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

265
00:25:05,448 --> 00:25:06,268
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scarpelli?

266
00:25:06,288 --> 00:25:06,368
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

267
00:25:07,268 --> 00:25:07,868
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Singh?

268
00:25:07,888 --> 00:25:08,969
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

269
00:25:08,989 --> 00:25:09,809
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

270
00:25:11,325 --> 00:25:11,925
[SPEAKER_19]: President Behrs.

271
00:25:12,286 --> 00:25:13,447
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, I'm in the affirmative, none in the negative.

272
00:25:13,467 --> 00:25:14,207
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion passes.

273
00:25:14,247 --> 00:25:14,588
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

274
00:25:15,688 --> 00:25:16,169
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you.

275
00:25:16,469 --> 00:25:17,210
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you very much.

276
00:25:17,230 --> 00:25:20,532
[SPEAKER_07]: We appreciate that.

277
00:25:20,552 --> 00:25:25,396
[SPEAKER_07]: Paper 26120 submitted by Mayor Brianna Lingo-Kern, free cash and retained earnings appropriations.

278
00:25:25,496 --> 00:25:30,400
[SPEAKER_07]: Dear President Behrs and city councilors, I respectfully request and recommend that your honorable body approves the appropriation of

279
00:25:31,063 --> 00:25:32,804
[SPEAKER_07]: One, free cash in the amount of $10,099,270.04 on the following items.

280
00:25:32,824 --> 00:25:38,907
[SPEAKER_07]: $7,447,658.04 to replenish the Capital Stabilization Fund to $13 million would contain $5,552,341.96 if the Capital Stabilization Fund appropriation request on the agenda later is approved.

281
00:25:55,608 --> 00:26:02,835
[SPEAKER_07]: $1,355,311.55 for the snow and ice deficit, $1,281,300.45 for the fiscal 23 and fiscal 24 patrol superior and dispatch union retro, and $15,000 for a feasibility study for the project labor agreement for the construction of a new Medford High School.

282
00:26:16,769 --> 00:26:19,530
[SPEAKER_07]: As of the submission of this request, the balance of free cash is $21,012,459.

283
00:26:19,570 --> 00:26:34,397
[SPEAKER_07]: Retained earnings in the water and sewer, and then two retained earnings from the Water Sewer Enterprise Fund in the amount of $560,000.00 on the following item, $560,000.00 to replenish the Water Sewer Capital Stabilization Fund to $2 million.

284
00:26:34,657 --> 00:26:39,158
[SPEAKER_07]: As of submission of this request, the balance in retained earnings in Water Sewer Enterprise is $5,091,021.00.

285
00:26:39,199 --> 00:26:40,419
[SPEAKER_07]: Respectfully submitted Brianna Lingo-Kern, Mayor.

286
00:26:45,943 --> 00:26:50,785
[SPEAKER_07]: And there are two other items here for free cash that are on our agenda later.

287
00:26:50,805 --> 00:26:58,949
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll just note those, $250,000 for the Affordable Housing Trust and $100,000 for the Medford Family Network.

288
00:26:59,009 --> 00:27:02,250
[SPEAKER_07]: And we will take those up later, but they are free cash papers.

289
00:27:03,030 --> 00:27:05,131
[SPEAKER_07]: I will recognize the administration.

290
00:27:05,171 --> 00:27:11,714
[SPEAKER_07]: Looks like we have Finance Director Dickinson, Chief of Staff Nazarian here if they want to present on this paper.

291
00:27:17,518 --> 00:27:18,238
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you and welcome.

292
00:27:19,059 --> 00:27:19,859
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, President Behrs.

293
00:27:20,420 --> 00:27:25,202
[SPEAKER_25]: Members of the council, I'm happy to answer any questions.

294
00:27:25,222 --> 00:27:30,725
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't have anything further to, I think, state at this stage.

295
00:27:31,866 --> 00:27:43,613
[SPEAKER_25]: You know, I will say that broadly, with the support of this council going back last year, we had identified that there was a significant need to have

296
00:27:44,313 --> 00:27:46,474
[SPEAKER_25]: funding in a stabilization fund.

297
00:27:46,854 --> 00:27:59,377
[SPEAKER_25]: Going back further in time, this council supported and collaborated with the administration, with the mayor, and myself and others to create the stabilization funds that didn't exist previous.

298
00:28:00,337 --> 00:28:12,360
[SPEAKER_25]: And so we have seen the fruits of that labor because unlike free cash, capital stabilization or stabilization funds can be used any time throughout the year.

299
00:28:13,272 --> 00:28:22,441
[SPEAKER_25]: And, you know, in the times where we didn't have stabilization funds, we were somewhat benefiting from the flexibility of ARPA.

300
00:28:22,501 --> 00:28:28,366
[SPEAKER_25]: But that came to a close, and this council agreed and moved swiftly with us ultimately.

301
00:28:28,426 --> 00:28:35,833
[SPEAKER_25]: The prior councils disagreed, but this council agreed, and we ultimately established a capital stabilization fund.

302
00:28:36,153 --> 00:28:43,560
[SPEAKER_25]: a General Stabilization Fund, a Water Sewer Stabilization Fund at that time and funded those things.

303
00:28:44,300 --> 00:28:59,034
[SPEAKER_25]: We spent over the course of fiscal 26, roughly $7.5 million out of the Capital Stabilization Fund demonstrating the significant need of that pocket of funding because free cash, as you all know,

304
00:28:59,454 --> 00:29:03,116
[SPEAKER_25]: as the public generally knows, is only available when it's certified.

305
00:29:03,176 --> 00:29:07,477
[SPEAKER_25]: So that means that the finance department has closed the books on the prior year.

306
00:29:07,938 --> 00:29:25,405
[SPEAKER_25]: It has, you know, submitted all the necessary paperwork to the state to get free cash certified, which can be a lengthy and arduous process that requires a lot more than I'm making it seem, which Auditor and Finance Director Bob Dickinson can expand on as the council wishes.

307
00:29:26,366 --> 00:29:29,218
[SPEAKER_25]: but it really effectively means that free cash is only available

308
00:29:30,504 --> 00:29:32,246
[SPEAKER_25]: at best half of the fiscal year.

309
00:29:33,126 --> 00:29:44,295
[SPEAKER_25]: So having this capital stabilization fund, replenishing this capital stabilization fund to the same level that it was at when we began fiscal 26 is what is being recommended here.

310
00:29:45,056 --> 00:29:48,399
[SPEAKER_25]: The snow and ice deficit is effectively just what it is.

311
00:29:49,880 --> 00:29:57,026
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm happy to answer any questions or our finance director could answer any questions on that who may have more depth and knowledge in that.

312
00:29:57,506 --> 00:30:08,954
[SPEAKER_25]: The next item with the union retroactive payments, we were able to place the fiscal 26 impact in the fiscal 26 budget.

313
00:30:09,275 --> 00:30:17,521
[SPEAKER_25]: The fiscal 25 impact was reserved, but we can't go back prior years once the books are closed.

314
00:30:18,121 --> 00:30:20,643
[SPEAKER_25]: That amount carries for those prior years.

315
00:30:21,460 --> 00:30:28,183
[SPEAKER_25]: And then finally, a feasibility study for a project labor agreement for the construction of the new Bedford High School.

316
00:30:28,203 --> 00:30:31,444
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't really have more comments on that, but happy to answer any questions.

317
00:30:32,145 --> 00:30:43,169
[SPEAKER_25]: And then similarly with retained earnings, replenishing the water and sewer capital stabilization fund back to $2 million because we spent effectively $500,000 out of that over the course of fiscal 26.

318
00:30:44,050 --> 00:30:44,330
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

319
00:30:46,651 --> 00:30:50,653
[SPEAKER_07]: Would it be useful, since we're talking about free cash, I know we didn't take them out of order, but to talk

320
00:30:52,311 --> 00:31:02,354
[SPEAKER_07]: Medford Family, is there like from just a financial perspective, it's another about $350,000 for the Affordable Housing Trust and Medford Family Network if you want to add anything at this point just about the fiscal picture there.

321
00:31:03,118 --> 00:31:03,458
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

322
00:31:05,660 --> 00:31:13,445
[SPEAKER_25]: From the standpoint of available free cash dollars, we have been fortunate as a community.

323
00:31:13,465 --> 00:31:26,334
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we have said to this council and this council has, I think, seen the difference that our fiscal picture is starting to create.

324
00:31:27,270 --> 00:31:44,240
[SPEAKER_25]: And what I mean by that is when we certified free cash for what would effectively have been fiscal 24, and finance director Dickinson can correct me if I'm wrong because these fiscal years start to confuse the brain a little bit, but we had about $28 million at that time.

325
00:31:46,661 --> 00:31:53,685
[SPEAKER_25]: When we closed fiscal 25, we had a free cash balance of $21 million.

326
00:31:54,546 --> 00:31:56,187
[SPEAKER_25]: Both finance director Dickinson and I

327
00:31:57,972 --> 00:32:03,013
[SPEAKER_25]: have stated here before, and we are going to continue to see a narrowing of those dollars.

328
00:32:03,453 --> 00:32:10,115
[SPEAKER_25]: But for the purposes of this picture, I can tell you that we will have somewhere over $10 million.

329
00:32:10,155 --> 00:32:13,156
[SPEAKER_25]: I had the calculation nearby.

330
00:32:13,176 --> 00:32:16,856
[SPEAKER_25]: I could recalculate, because I don't know exactly what would remain off the top of my head.

331
00:32:16,896 --> 00:32:18,497
[SPEAKER_25]: It's on order of magnitude of $10 to $12 million.

332
00:32:19,797 --> 00:32:27,985
[SPEAKER_25]: with the totality of these free cash appropriations that will effectively stay in free cash, but come June 30th, it will become unavailable.

333
00:32:28,526 --> 00:32:30,848
[SPEAKER_25]: We can't touch it, we can't use it, we can't do anything with it.

334
00:32:31,269 --> 00:32:33,871
[SPEAKER_25]: It will fall into essentially

335
00:32:35,023 --> 00:32:38,266
[SPEAKER_25]: this is my wording, this isn't the finance terminology.

336
00:32:39,206 --> 00:32:55,480
[SPEAKER_25]: It will fall into what is effectively 27, fiscal 27, and then whatever gets added to it from fiscal 27, which we don't believe is going to be the same level as we've seen historically, especially considering how much we've tightened outside of our collective comfort zones for fiscal 27.

337
00:32:58,542 --> 00:33:08,010
[SPEAKER_25]: Then when fiscal 27 is closed, we will, sorry, when fiscal 26 is closed, then we will see those numbers come back.

338
00:33:08,070 --> 00:33:12,134
[SPEAKER_25]: So that $10 million-ish will be the base added to whatever is added to.

339
00:33:12,154 --> 00:33:14,116
[SPEAKER_25]: If that made sense.

340
00:33:14,156 --> 00:33:19,560
[SPEAKER_25]: If not, please ask clarifying questions and I will defer to Finance Director Dickinson for a different way to say it.

341
00:33:20,653 --> 00:33:23,114
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, I guess just a really quick clarifying question.

342
00:33:23,134 --> 00:33:24,155
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll go to Councillor Scarpelli.

343
00:33:24,175 --> 00:33:30,638
[SPEAKER_07]: Do we have an estimate of how much we expect to be in surplus at the end of fiscal 26 that would roll to free cash?

344
00:33:31,358 --> 00:33:32,458
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't think either way.

345
00:33:32,699 --> 00:33:32,839
[SPEAKER_25]: No.

346
00:33:33,519 --> 00:33:34,960
[SPEAKER_25]: Neither of us could give you that answer.

347
00:33:34,980 --> 00:33:35,460
[SPEAKER_25]: Okay.

348
00:33:35,540 --> 00:33:44,444
[SPEAKER_25]: It's just it's every financial officer in every city and town is always advised from even the state

349
00:33:45,459 --> 00:33:48,500
[SPEAKER_25]: to not venture a guess on free cash numbers.

350
00:33:49,060 --> 00:33:53,321
[SPEAKER_25]: Because you don't want to be in a situation where you venture a guess and your guess is off.

351
00:33:53,981 --> 00:34:01,943
[SPEAKER_25]: And it's also so dependent on so many factors that are almost impossible to guess on.

352
00:34:05,990 --> 00:34:22,422
[SPEAKER_25]: For instance, we could have a situation where we have building permits pulled for a project that wasn't on the city's radar at all because something changed economically and created a certain opportunity for a developer or whatever the case may be.

353
00:34:22,802 --> 00:34:24,644
[SPEAKER_25]: And that may not even be on the radar.

354
00:34:27,085 --> 00:34:28,887
[SPEAKER_25]: I can't think of other specific examples.

355
00:34:28,927 --> 00:34:29,387
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't know if...

356
00:34:31,365 --> 00:34:36,686
[SPEAKER_25]: You would have any off the top of your mind, but it's just a very, very difficult number to predict.

357
00:34:38,286 --> 00:34:47,628
[SPEAKER_18]: From my point of view, I wouldn't venture a guess until I've closed 2026's books and gone through them and made sure that everything is properly recorded.

358
00:34:49,289 --> 00:34:53,190
[SPEAKER_18]: There's just too much variance to make an estimate.

359
00:34:56,245 --> 00:34:57,706
[SPEAKER_18]: very loathe to make an estimate.

360
00:34:58,106 --> 00:35:02,249
[SPEAKER_18]: Free cash is what the DOR says it is once I've got all the state reporting in.

361
00:35:03,209 --> 00:35:03,930
[SPEAKER_18]: That's what it is.

362
00:35:04,750 --> 00:35:09,473
[SPEAKER_18]: I can make an estimate, but you shouldn't spend it until DOR says it's okay.

363
00:35:12,255 --> 00:35:16,898
[SPEAKER_18]: Replenishing the Capital Stabilization Fund simply uses free cash to

364
00:35:18,605 --> 00:35:26,547
[SPEAKER_18]: fund projects that we would ordinarily fund with available free cash, we just get to do it without having to certify free cash.

365
00:35:26,607 --> 00:35:38,449
[SPEAKER_18]: We have a bucket that we can take money from to fix sidewalks, put HVAC on schools and all that stuff without having to wait for the free cash to be certified.

366
00:35:39,150 --> 00:35:45,131
[SPEAKER_18]: It just increases the city council and the administration's flexibility in doing these projects.

367
00:35:46,240 --> 00:35:46,420
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

368
00:35:46,980 --> 00:36:05,343
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll go to Councilor Squane in just one second, but essentially what we're talking about is the city's reserves, and those fall mostly into two buckets for the general fund, which is stabilization funds, which can be appropriated from year-round, and what the state calls, quote-unquote, free cash, which is really just actually reserves.

369
00:36:06,403 --> 00:36:15,125
[SPEAKER_07]: But because of their calculation, we have to wait for them to say, this is your amount for this year after all of the financial reporting is done.

370
00:36:16,119 --> 00:36:34,184
[SPEAKER_07]: The bulk of this paper is, you know, it's a $10 million request, $7.5 million is making sure that the stabilization fund is at a balance, is at the $13 million balance, basically that we can use our reserves without waiting for the state certification on the upcoming balance for next year.

371
00:36:36,624 --> 00:36:38,065
[SPEAKER_07]: Another million, $1.4 million is

372
00:36:39,764 --> 00:36:47,589
[SPEAKER_07]: What we spent to plow snow and ice last year, which is the only account the state lets us run a deficit on, essentially, by and large.

373
00:36:49,390 --> 00:36:56,534
[SPEAKER_07]: Another 1.3 million for the police union contracts, which were out for many years, all the way back to fiscal year 23.

374
00:36:57,114 --> 00:37:09,241
[SPEAKER_07]: And then 15,000, this is kind of the only looking forward item, I think I would say, which is the 15,000 to do a feasibility study for a project labor agreement for the new Medford High School.

375
00:37:09,977 --> 00:37:19,502
[SPEAKER_07]: And then for retained earnings, it's just to similarly make sure that the flexible stabilization fund that can be used year-round is at $2 million for the water and sewer system.

376
00:37:20,943 --> 00:37:21,183
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

377
00:37:21,923 --> 00:37:24,184
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Scarpelli.

378
00:37:24,204 --> 00:37:39,372
[SPEAKER_21]: Mr. President, before I go on, the $21 million, that's before we ask, just to be clear, ask for the 7.447, 5 million capital stabilization, so on and so forth, correct?

379
00:37:39,752 --> 00:37:40,212
[SPEAKER_25]: Correct.

380
00:37:40,372 --> 00:38:04,999
[SPEAKER_25]: And just to clarify on the parentheses that's contained there, because there is a paper before the council to use the capital stabilization fund, I was identifying the number just to put it in writing so that everyone had it, what the capital stabilization fund balance would be today if this evening the council approved that capital request, which I believe is in the amount of $17,500 if I'm not mistaken.

381
00:38:08,361 --> 00:38:14,304
[SPEAKER_25]: So small, but just wanted to identify the newest number if it was approved for tonight.

382
00:38:14,364 --> 00:38:23,549
[SPEAKER_25]: So the $7 million, the $1.355, the $1.281, and the $15,000 would all reduce the $21 million that's before you.

383
00:38:25,209 --> 00:38:28,931
[SPEAKER_21]: But that's not knowing what the replenished number will be as we move forward.

384
00:38:30,512 --> 00:38:31,713
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm sorry, I didn't hear that.

385
00:38:32,113 --> 00:38:33,714
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry, George, your mic's low.

386
00:38:34,855 --> 00:38:35,075
[SPEAKER_07]: Go ahead.

387
00:38:35,095 --> 00:38:35,515
[SPEAKER_21]: Can you hear me?

388
00:38:37,815 --> 00:38:38,735
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes.

389
00:38:39,096 --> 00:38:46,419
[SPEAKER_21]: So at the end of the, as we subtract, will be minus $21,000 minus the $712, somewhat $14 million in free cash?

390
00:38:46,439 --> 00:38:48,540
[SPEAKER_21]: I would, yes.

391
00:38:48,560 --> 00:38:53,523
[SPEAKER_21]: $21 million minus $10 million, call it $100 if all of those items above are approved.

392
00:38:59,236 --> 00:39:03,497
[SPEAKER_21]: So at the end of this vote, we'll have roughly $10, $11 million left in free cash.

393
00:39:03,577 --> 00:39:03,977
[SPEAKER_21]: That's it.

394
00:39:04,437 --> 00:39:04,717
[SPEAKER_25]: Correct.

395
00:39:04,797 --> 00:39:08,118
[SPEAKER_25]: And then there's two other papers which would deduct from that same number.

396
00:39:08,318 --> 00:39:09,119
[SPEAKER_25]: But yes, that's correct.

397
00:39:09,819 --> 00:39:17,221
[SPEAKER_21]: So I know that the big battle that I had, remember when we came up talking about the override, I said, let's use this.

398
00:39:17,301 --> 00:39:22,502
[SPEAKER_21]: And we said that there is a certain number that we should have in that free cash.

399
00:39:23,182 --> 00:39:24,383
[SPEAKER_21]: Do we fall in that range?

400
00:39:24,983 --> 00:39:26,083
[SPEAKER_21]: Because in the past, it was

401
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:28,361
[SPEAKER_21]: Remember, we wanted it higher.

402
00:39:28,521 --> 00:39:28,941
[SPEAKER_21]: Remember that?

403
00:39:28,961 --> 00:39:35,126
[SPEAKER_21]: Remember the discussions we had when I fought against the override and they said that, well, we have $24 million in the override.

404
00:39:35,586 --> 00:39:42,991
[SPEAKER_21]: Why don't we take the 4.5 for this one time to level fund the school budget so we don't have to look at an override until we do a study?

405
00:39:43,011 --> 00:39:44,412
[SPEAKER_21]: Remember that conversation?

406
00:39:44,912 --> 00:39:52,797
[SPEAKER_21]: And the conversation at that time was, no, we really need to keep that account at a higher number due to many different factors.

407
00:39:53,857 --> 00:39:59,621
[SPEAKER_21]: Things have changed today, so dropping all the way down to $10 million is something that we feel comfortable with.

408
00:40:00,681 --> 00:40:06,885
[SPEAKER_25]: Mr. President, through you, I remember that conversation, Councilor Scarpelli, and we are in that same range.

409
00:40:07,245 --> 00:40:19,393
[SPEAKER_25]: The difference today is when we appropriated funding at the end of the last fiscal year, we appropriated approximately $6 million out of the free cash number into general stabilization.

410
00:40:19,473 --> 00:40:22,715
[SPEAKER_25]: We've been fortunate that we haven't had to draw on that amount.

411
00:40:23,395 --> 00:40:29,382
[SPEAKER_25]: Because as the council knows, as the public knows, that would be our most rainiest days of rainiest funds, right?

412
00:40:29,662 --> 00:40:30,703
[SPEAKER_25]: For a lack of better terms.

413
00:40:30,723 --> 00:40:37,510
[SPEAKER_25]: That's probably a better way to say it, but that's if we have something catastrophic that's really problematic, which we hope to never see.

414
00:40:39,392 --> 00:40:45,074
[SPEAKER_25]: We want to be, because when we're drawing on capital stabilization funds, we're drawing on pre-planned projects.

415
00:40:45,174 --> 00:40:53,699
[SPEAKER_25]: Things that, generally speaking, now it's not going to, it's not to say that we can't draw on capital stabilization if we do have a roof leak that needs to be addressed.

416
00:40:54,199 --> 00:41:02,203
[SPEAKER_25]: It's just to say that we'll probably go to capital stabilization for capital items before we have to draw on general stabilization for any reason.

417
00:41:02,723 --> 00:41:07,804
[SPEAKER_25]: If we're dipping into general stabilization, we have a larger problem on our hands, and we hope to not do that.

418
00:41:08,304 --> 00:41:15,706
[SPEAKER_25]: So getting back to your specific question, Councilor Scarapelli, when we closed the last fiscal year, we were in this range.

419
00:41:15,766 --> 00:41:19,187
[SPEAKER_25]: I think it was $10, $12 million, almost exactly.

420
00:41:19,207 --> 00:41:21,907
[SPEAKER_25]: And to me, that's right there.

421
00:41:21,927 --> 00:41:25,128
[SPEAKER_21]: Okay, and it won't affect that bond rating if we dip?

