00:45:47,850 --> 00:45:49,772
[SPEAKER_18]: Sorry, they'd be talking about all of our reserves.

457
00:45:49,832 --> 00:45:50,252
[SPEAKER_07]: All right, great.

458
00:45:50,272 --> 00:45:55,097
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I think that's just another important thing to really lock in on the terminology here is.

459
00:45:56,375 --> 00:45:59,836
[SPEAKER_07]: not great that the state uses, and I think it gets confusing for folks.

460
00:46:00,137 --> 00:46:03,738
[SPEAKER_07]: So we're talking about our reserves, no matter which account they're in.

461
00:46:05,299 --> 00:46:07,560
[SPEAKER_07]: Any other comments or questions on this paper from members of the council?

462
00:46:09,185 --> 00:46:09,525
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

463
00:46:10,246 --> 00:46:16,891
[SPEAKER_09]: I find most of this very reasonable to be in the course of everyday business of the city.

464
00:46:16,911 --> 00:46:27,159
[SPEAKER_09]: I want to piggyback off of Councillor Scarpelli and President Behrs that I am excited to see the 15,000 for the feasibility study.

465
00:46:28,370 --> 00:46:37,375
[SPEAKER_09]: We've talked a lot on this council about supporting workers, supporting unions, and we've talked about that with the prevailing wage ordinance.

466
00:46:37,896 --> 00:46:41,378
[SPEAKER_09]: We've talked about that with numerous resolutions that come by.

467
00:46:42,636 --> 00:46:54,864
[SPEAKER_09]: And with such a big project coming to the city, I think it's important for us to be exploring, to be supporting workers with good wages, with high work standards.

468
00:46:56,464 --> 00:47:08,652
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think this is putting our rhetoric into practice and preaching, not only just preaching, but practicing what we're saying.

469
00:47:11,943 --> 00:47:12,784
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Sang.

470
00:47:14,185 --> 00:47:17,808
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further comments or questions by members of the City Council on this paper?

471
00:47:18,529 --> 00:47:23,653
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, is there anyone here from the public who'd like to speak on this paper at this time?

472
