700
01:08:53,660 --> 01:08:54,461
[SPEAKER_15]: to get the payments out.

701
01:08:55,081 --> 01:08:57,963
[SPEAKER_15]: But I can obviously, you know, expedite as much as I possibly can.

702
01:08:57,983 --> 01:08:58,504
[SPEAKER_15]: All right.

703
01:08:58,604 --> 01:08:58,804
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah.

704
01:08:59,184 --> 01:08:59,384
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

705
01:08:59,504 --> 01:08:59,844
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

706
01:08:59,884 --> 01:09:00,585
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Callaghan.

707
01:09:01,719 --> 01:09:02,379
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

708
01:09:02,959 --> 01:09:03,459
[SPEAKER_14]: Welcome.

709
01:09:03,679 --> 01:09:07,080
[SPEAKER_14]: It's great to have a new engineer, and I'm going to make some comments.

710
01:09:07,240 --> 01:09:25,624
[SPEAKER_14]: Don't take them in any way personally, but I think both for city councilors as well as for the general public, I think it's really important that when things like this come up, there's enough information for people who are maybe less policy wonky to be able to understand what's being decided.

711
01:09:26,044 --> 01:09:30,305
[SPEAKER_14]: And so, for example, when I read, and I know a lot of this comes from MassDOT, but like,

712
01:09:31,165 --> 01:09:46,095
[SPEAKER_14]: The one descriptive sentence in here says, the project will add traffic signals to three major intersections and include roadway, mill, and overlay, intersection geometry revisions, and improvements to sidewalks, bus lanes, bicycle lanes, crosswalks, signage, and pavement markings.

713
01:09:46,135 --> 01:09:51,859
[SPEAKER_14]: But it doesn't actually, in the words, it doesn't actually describe any of the changes.

714
01:09:51,879 --> 01:09:55,421
[SPEAKER_14]: It just says things will be changed, and as you may understand.

715
01:09:56,902 --> 01:10:00,283
[SPEAKER_14]: improvements to some people are not improvements to other people.

716
01:10:00,563 --> 01:10:03,684
[SPEAKER_14]: People disagree sometimes on whether something is an improvement or not.

717
01:10:04,564 --> 01:10:15,828
[SPEAKER_14]: And when I look at the diagram, I have to admit, and I don't mean to insult anyone, but this looks like I can tell that there are streets.

718
01:10:16,808 --> 01:10:20,113
[SPEAKER_14]: But then there's like 50,000 words, each of which is too small for me to read.

719
01:10:20,674 --> 01:10:26,922
[SPEAKER_14]: And there's no, like, I am, I genuinely have difficulty trying to understand what this is telling me.

720
01:10:26,962 --> 01:10:27,603
[SPEAKER_14]: Yeah.

721
01:10:27,623 --> 01:10:31,268
[SPEAKER_14]: So it would be so incredibly helpful to have

722
01:10:34,078 --> 01:10:42,567
[SPEAKER_14]: even if it were just verbally, but in writing would be excellent, and maybe a diagram of something that actually says what, in fact, is being changed.

723
01:10:43,648 --> 01:10:46,691
[SPEAKER_14]: And even for the public, what is an easement?

724
01:10:47,352 --> 01:10:51,897
[SPEAKER_14]: That kind of thing that would help people to understand what it is that we're actually deciding tonight.

725
01:10:53,277 --> 01:11:21,025
[SPEAKER_14]: So I also tend to feel that it would be really excellent if we could table this and then talk about it a little bit more in depth when hopefully there could also be some supporting documents that were a little bit easier for the general public to understand because when it does involve private property, it really is crucial that people who are a little less sort of wonky can understand what it is that we're voting on.

726
01:11:21,185 --> 01:11:21,905
[SPEAKER_15]: So that would be great.

727
01:11:22,085 --> 01:11:22,605
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, absolutely.

728
01:11:22,625 --> 01:11:42,919
[SPEAKER_15]: The plans, those are specifically like the right-of-way easement plans, but there's also several hundred pages of construction plans, which I think with the help of Todd Blake, our traffic and transportation director, can be better distilled into more readable images and descriptions of all the changes that are proposed.

729
01:11:43,679 --> 01:11:45,581
[SPEAKER_15]: That's definitely something that we can do, for sure.

730
01:11:45,601 --> 01:11:46,541
[SPEAKER_14]: That would be amazing.

731
01:11:46,561 --> 01:11:47,002
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you so much.

732
01:11:47,786 --> 01:11:52,436
[SPEAKER_07]: If you could do it in five slides and have it to us by July 9th, that would be great.

733
01:11:52,476 --> 01:11:54,441
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay, that we can do, yes.

734
01:11:55,403 --> 01:11:55,864
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

735
01:11:56,886 --> 01:11:57,528
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Malayne.

736
01:11:58,150 --> 01:11:58,470
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

737
01:11:58,510 --> 01:12:01,333
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you also for coming here tonight and talking through it.

738
01:12:01,573 --> 01:12:06,517
