847
01:20:55,422 --> 01:20:55,642
[SPEAKER_04]: Sure.

848
01:20:55,662 --> 01:20:59,826
[SPEAKER_04]: My customer for nine on Main Street just instantly.

849
01:20:59,906 --> 01:21:04,571
[SPEAKER_04]: I actually drive up Thomas Street from Maine almost every day because there is a daycare there.

850
01:21:04,671 --> 01:21:05,893
[SPEAKER_04]: It's also like a hospital there.

851
01:21:06,493 --> 01:21:12,680
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm the one comment I want to make is that since you're already doing safety work there like that turn.

852
01:21:14,097 --> 01:21:23,122
[SPEAKER_04]: I have Thomas Street off of Maine, where that gas station is, and the way people use that turn to go against traffic down Thomas to get back onto Maine.

853
01:21:23,645 --> 01:21:33,892
[SPEAKER_04]: is actually wicked dangerous, and Massachusetts drivers on a good day are the worst drivers in the country, and with this particular corner, it gets exponentially worse.

854
01:21:33,932 --> 01:21:45,920
[SPEAKER_04]: So I don't know if there's a way you can actually factor that part into your safety review analysis, but the community and commuters there and people who live there too would benefit a lot from that.

855
01:21:46,360 --> 01:21:50,223
[SPEAKER_04]: Also, for the valuations, it is kind of weird that

856
01:21:51,587 --> 01:22:07,379
[SPEAKER_04]: Global companies, the gas station on the triangle corner, seems to be getting a way higher payout than the rest of the properties here for so-called sliver, but I'm just an observation.

857
01:22:07,759 --> 01:22:08,740
[SPEAKER_04]: But yeah, that's it.

858
01:22:11,021 --> 01:22:11,502
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

859
01:22:11,882 --> 01:22:12,642
[SPEAKER_08]: Is there anyone else?

860
01:22:12,943 --> 01:22:13,123
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

861
01:22:19,182 --> 01:22:25,187
[SPEAKER_06]: My name is Hoang Nguyen, and I own a property in Mr. Gap.

862
01:22:26,188 --> 01:22:32,754
[SPEAKER_06]: So I was informed that there's a wire going above our roof.

863
01:22:33,454 --> 01:22:35,856
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not really above our roof, it's on a sidewalk.

864
01:22:36,337 --> 01:22:39,599
[SPEAKER_06]: And I was informed that it's not in our property.

865
01:22:40,780 --> 01:22:46,325
[SPEAKER_06]: Is there any way I can avoid the temporary easement?

866
01:22:46,937 --> 01:22:56,342
[SPEAKER_06]: Because if it's not involved in our property, then why do we have to abide to a easement?

867
01:22:59,664 --> 01:23:01,325
[SPEAKER_07]: I will recognize the city engineer.

868
01:23:03,846 --> 01:23:04,206
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

869
01:23:07,988 --> 01:23:08,329
[SPEAKER_16]: Hello.

870
01:23:08,429 --> 01:23:16,173
[SPEAKER_16]: So this utility pole that is located next to the gas station is being shifted five feet.

871
01:23:17,181 --> 01:23:23,944
[SPEAKER_16]: and the property owner has the corresponding pole 200 feet away.

872
01:23:24,264 --> 01:23:41,210
[SPEAKER_16]: So this shift of five feet is going to shift those wires to two or three inches closer to his property and MassDOT requires a 10-foot easement along the center line and that's how

873
01:23:42,518 --> 01:23:49,726
[SPEAKER_16]: this, even though the wires are not over his property, there is an easement associated with the wires being shifted over the few inches.

874
01:23:50,186 --> 01:23:52,929
[SPEAKER_16]: And that is why his property is being affected.

875
01:23:52,949 --> 01:23:56,713
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

876
01:23:57,234 --> 01:23:58,475
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Lemming.

877
01:24:00,860 --> 01:24:03,522
[SPEAKER_20]: Through the chair, question for the city engineer.

878
01:24:03,822 --> 01:24:13,168
[SPEAKER_20]: In your opinion, would delaying this until July have any substantial effect on the project?

879
01:24:18,671 --> 01:24:20,292
[SPEAKER_07]: Owen, do you have an answer there?

880
01:24:20,772 --> 01:24:21,893
[SPEAKER_16]: I would say yes.

881
01:24:21,993 --> 01:24:29,217
[SPEAKER_16]: They're going to bid in early August, and this is the time frame that we need to get these

882
01:24:30,458 --> 01:24:33,780
[SPEAKER_16]: temporary easements through city council.

883
01:24:36,502 --> 01:24:39,003
[SPEAKER_07]: So could you just clarify that a little bit more?

884
01:24:39,043 --> 01:24:42,525
[SPEAKER_07]: What happens if we approve it on July 14th instead of today?

885
01:24:43,226 --> 01:24:43,566
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't know.

886
01:24:43,966 --> 01:24:46,428
[SPEAKER_16]: The question is, do you need three readings to approve it?

887
01:24:49,069 --> 01:24:52,031
[SPEAKER_07]: No, we shouldn't need three readings to approve it.

888
01:24:52,331 --> 01:24:53,192
[SPEAKER_16]: It shouldn't matter.

889
01:24:53,212 --> 01:24:55,633
[SPEAKER_16]: We're willing to, again, the city is

890
01:25:00,827 --> 01:25:05,210
[SPEAKER_16]: you know, the liaison for the state in this case.

891
01:25:05,550 --> 01:25:06,911
[SPEAKER_16]: So this is a state project.

892
01:25:07,211 --> 01:25:08,292
[SPEAKER_16]: The state is doing this.

893
01:25:09,433 --> 01:25:19,239
[SPEAKER_16]: We're just going through the, you know, the paperwork, which requires a little bit of line adjustments, property line adjustments and easements for this project.

894
01:25:20,040 --> 01:25:21,561
[SPEAKER_16]: And that's why we're in front of City Council.

895
01:25:23,622 --> 01:25:23,823
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

896
01:25:24,103 --> 01:25:25,864
[SPEAKER_07]: So what I'm hearing is that if we approve it,

897
01:25:27,720 --> 01:25:39,348
[SPEAKER_07]: The order, all three readings, I don't even necessarily think this needs a three-reading approach, but assuming it did, if we chose to approve all readings on July 14th, that would be an acceptable timeline.

898
01:25:39,508 --> 01:25:40,648
[SPEAKER_07]: Just want to confirm that, Owen.

899
01:25:41,429 --> 01:25:41,609
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

900
01:25:41,629 --> 01:25:43,290
[SPEAKER_07]: All right, great.

901
01:25:46,132 --> 01:25:50,835
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further discussion by members of the public on this who haven't already spoken?

