1054
01:40:34,590 --> 01:40:46,157
[SPEAKER_05]: If I had, I heard that you mentioned that the city was essentially offering to allow certain budget items in exchange for taking off certain requests related to like our legal spending.

1055
01:40:48,503 --> 01:40:49,104
[SPEAKER_05]: Is that correct?

1056
01:40:51,527 --> 01:40:57,175
[SPEAKER_21]: Outlining what we asked for in lieu of not cutting the legal line.

1057
01:40:58,340 --> 01:41:05,547
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, just because simply the fact that that is happening I think is just frankly disgraceful.

1058
01:41:06,949 --> 01:41:20,323
[SPEAKER_05]: That currently what our city executive administration is offering to do is essentially swapping what we're funding for just getting basic information from our city about where our money is going.

1059
01:41:20,423 --> 01:41:21,284
[SPEAKER_05]: That should be a concern.

1060
01:41:22,104 --> 01:41:24,027
[SPEAKER_05]: anyone who's a resident of the city.

1061
01:41:24,848 --> 01:41:37,823
[SPEAKER_05]: And I also support this resolution, but I also think that like we should be looking more into just like how this mayoral administration seems to be trying to use this pressure to how they're trying to basically force

1062
01:41:40,012 --> 01:41:54,163
[SPEAKER_05]: concessions in favor of actually getting things that we should be getting as basics from our mayoral administration in exchange for funding what is always going to be important, which is the city services that keep the city going.

1063
01:41:54,183 --> 01:42:00,188
[SPEAKER_05]: So yeah, I very much support Councilman Scarpelli's resolution and very much hope you all will too.

1064
01:42:02,349 --> 01:42:02,770
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1065
01:42:02,790 --> 01:42:04,631
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing no hands on Zoom, we'll stay at the podium.

1066
01:42:04,691 --> 01:42:07,533
[SPEAKER_07]: If you give your name and city for the record, and you'll have three minutes.

1067
01:42:08,214 --> 01:42:09,795
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm Mike Hesselman, 499 Main Street.

1068
01:42:11,133 --> 01:42:21,738
[SPEAKER_04]: First, I actually, Chair, thank you, Councilor Scarpelli for being very aggressive and trying to track this down and actually shed some daylight on this.

1069
01:42:22,079 --> 01:42:23,299
[SPEAKER_04]: This is actually super important.

1070
01:42:23,779 --> 01:42:30,503
[SPEAKER_04]: I am honestly baffled how you're, like this isn't a simple report to generate.

1071
01:42:32,059 --> 01:42:35,583
[SPEAKER_04]: At this point in my career, I've worked in-house longer than I've been in private practice.

1072
01:42:36,183 --> 01:42:49,017
[SPEAKER_04]: And managing outside counsel, if you want to know how much you've spent and what that money's been spent on specifically, the outside counsel provides a report in a spreadsheet that should break it down.

1073
01:42:49,978 --> 01:42:52,139
[SPEAKER_04]: Law firms are in the business of making money.

1074
01:42:52,599 --> 01:42:56,940
[SPEAKER_04]: They track very closely how they are billing you for that money.

1075
01:42:57,380 --> 01:42:59,961
[SPEAKER_04]: It's very easy to get this information.

1076
01:43:00,401 --> 01:43:05,403
[SPEAKER_04]: It's shocking to me that this is like this crazy, fakaka nonsense headache.

1077
01:43:05,903 --> 01:43:06,603
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't understand.

1078
01:43:06,643 --> 01:43:08,584
[SPEAKER_04]: This is so incompetent.

1079
01:43:09,936 --> 01:43:10,696
[SPEAKER_04]: It's wild.

1080
01:43:11,477 --> 01:43:17,218
[SPEAKER_04]: So, and I'll also add that, like, I'd reached out to Counselor Ciapelli earlier about this, too.

1081
01:43:17,618 --> 01:43:28,041
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, what is the, like, you should at least have access to the engagement letters and the engagements with these law firms so that you know the meets and bounds and scopes of representation that the firms are being contracted to do for you.

1082
01:43:28,485 --> 01:43:30,746
[SPEAKER_04]: That's crazy that you don't have that as well.

1083
01:43:31,047 --> 01:43:36,070
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, this is literally a one-day operation for each of these firms.

1084
01:43:36,230 --> 01:43:36,970
[SPEAKER_04]: Less than a day.

1085
01:43:37,250 --> 01:43:40,212
[SPEAKER_04]: You put a couple of paralegals on it and they'll get it done.

1086
01:43:40,773 --> 01:43:41,873
[SPEAKER_04]: How is this not done?

1087
01:43:42,434 --> 01:43:43,574
[SPEAKER_04]: This is crazy.

1088
01:43:44,395 --> 01:43:45,816
[SPEAKER_04]: It's so infuriating.

1089
01:43:46,336 --> 01:43:47,777
[SPEAKER_04]: Because it's so incompetent.

1090
01:43:48,197 --> 01:43:48,898
[SPEAKER_04]: It's pathetic.

1091
01:43:49,963 --> 01:44:02,933
[SPEAKER_04]: And I really, really hope that you're able to move this forward, because it should not be this hard for basic, minimal accountability from outside contractors to the city.

1092
01:44:04,714 --> 01:44:04,974
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

1093
01:44:04,994 --> 01:44:05,335
[SPEAKER_04]: That's it.

1094
01:44:07,676 --> 01:44:08,037
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1095
01:44:10,659 --> 01:44:11,860
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll go to Zoom.

1096
01:44:12,500 --> 01:44:13,541
[SPEAKER_07]: Lori Krieger on Zoom.

1097
01:44:14,101 --> 01:44:16,343
[SPEAKER_07]: If you give your name and city for the record, you'll have three minutes.

1098
01:44:17,144 --> 01:44:17,664
[SPEAKER_26]: Hey, y'all.

1099
01:44:18,720 --> 01:44:21,181
[SPEAKER_26]: Hi, Lori Krieger, Medford Mass.

1100
01:44:21,861 --> 01:44:24,661
[SPEAKER_26]: I thank you for bringing this up.

1101
01:44:25,001 --> 01:44:26,481
[SPEAKER_26]: I support the resolution.

1102
01:44:27,882 --> 01:44:37,683
[SPEAKER_26]: Anything to do with the budget should be a matter of standard reporting and the full city council and the community should have complete access to it at any time.

1103
01:44:38,344 --> 01:44:43,725
[SPEAKER_26]: And anti-democratic behaviors by the mayor cannot be tolerated by any means at all.

1104
01:44:43,885 --> 01:44:45,065
[SPEAKER_26]: So I support you 100%.

1105
01:44:45,105 --> 01:44:45,285
[SPEAKER_26]: Thank you.

1106
01:44:47,696 --> 01:44:48,017
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1107
01:44:56,942 --> 01:44:59,864
[SPEAKER_24]: Stephen South, 106 Damon Road, Medford.

1108
01:45:00,564 --> 01:45:12,210
[SPEAKER_24]: First of all, I want to thank Councilor Scarpelli and all of you for standing up to make sure that city residents' tax dollars are spent appropriately and responsibly.

1109
01:45:12,730 --> 01:45:18,073
[SPEAKER_24]: I believe that since January of 2020, that has not necessarily been the case.

1110
01:45:18,953 --> 01:45:25,357
[SPEAKER_24]: I just have a list of just some of the lawsuits that city employees have filed in the last few years.

1111
01:45:27,066 --> 01:45:28,007
[SPEAKER_24]: Howard et al.

1112
01:45:28,527 --> 01:45:31,510
[SPEAKER_24]: versus City of Medford, Connors et al.

1113
01:45:31,570 --> 01:45:33,932
[SPEAKER_24]: versus City of Medford, Ayala et al.

1114
01:45:33,993 --> 01:45:38,137
[SPEAKER_24]: versus City of Medford, Conboy versus City of Medford, Fargo et al.

1115
01:45:38,197 --> 01:45:43,121
[SPEAKER_24]: versus City of Medford, Gill versus City of Medford, Nunley versus City of Medford.

1116
01:45:43,542 --> 01:45:48,887
[SPEAKER_24]: There's also a class action lawsuit that was filed within the last, you know, year or so.

1117
01:45:48,907 --> 01:45:50,448
[SPEAKER_24]: I don't have the exact date.

1118
01:45:51,209 --> 01:46:03,764
[SPEAKER_24]: in which the city administration chose to drug test the entire DPW and alcohol test on the same day because an unused needle was found allegedly at the DPW.

1119
01:46:04,730 --> 01:46:09,152
[SPEAKER_24]: Now, all these cases have been represented by current counsel for the city.

1120
01:46:09,893 --> 01:46:16,036
[SPEAKER_24]: I'm actually curious, as a resident and a taxpayer, number one, how much money are we spending?

1121
01:46:16,476 --> 01:46:19,257
[SPEAKER_24]: Number two, where's this money coming from?

1122
01:46:19,678 --> 01:46:23,340
[SPEAKER_24]: And number three, how could this money be spent more appropriately?

1123
01:46:23,720 --> 01:46:25,601
[SPEAKER_24]: I mean, these are not monopoly dollars.

1124
01:46:25,641 --> 01:46:27,262
[SPEAKER_24]: These are our tax dollars.

1125
01:46:27,382 --> 01:46:30,383
[SPEAKER_24]: And again, I really appreciate you all stepping up.

1126
01:46:30,823 --> 01:46:33,385
[SPEAKER_24]: And I believe that my last point I'd like to make is,

1127
01:46:34,025 --> 01:46:39,167
[SPEAKER_24]: The city of Medford is very unique, and I don't think for a positive reason.

1128
01:46:39,888 --> 01:46:48,892
[SPEAKER_24]: If you look at the city of Malden, which is comparable, I believe a little smaller, Malden has four city solicitors.

1129
01:46:48,952 --> 01:46:51,753
[SPEAKER_24]: I believe it's one solicitor and three assistant solicitors.

1130
01:46:52,133 --> 01:46:52,933
[SPEAKER_24]: You look at Everett.

1131
01:46:53,394 --> 01:46:55,975
[SPEAKER_24]: Everett has three city solicitors.

1132
01:46:56,978 --> 01:47:03,883
[SPEAKER_24]: And you look at larger communities like Newton and Cambridge and others that have many city solicitors.

1133
01:47:04,364 --> 01:47:08,387
[SPEAKER_24]: I just don't understand how a community of our size has zero.

1134
01:47:08,827 --> 01:47:11,650
[SPEAKER_24]: And I know you all know the story.

1135
01:47:11,710 --> 01:47:14,412
[SPEAKER_24]: We had one, I don't know, five years ago.

1136
01:47:14,492 --> 01:47:16,613
[SPEAKER_24]: Then we didn't have one for many years.

1137
01:47:16,693 --> 01:47:23,919
[SPEAKER_24]: Then we had one for, I believe, what, five months and 29 days or something, whatever the probationary period was.

1138
01:47:24,279 --> 01:47:25,640
[SPEAKER_24]: But it seems like it is.

1139
01:47:26,761 --> 01:47:46,889
[SPEAKER_24]: part of this administration's strategy to not have a solicitor, because a solicitor answers to the entire community, the council, all the employees, and is responsible for the upkeep of the laws, whether municipal, federal, and making sure the city's doing the right thing.

1140
01:47:46,949 --> 01:47:55,873
[SPEAKER_24]: And for whatever reason, this administration wants to have their own private hired guns through KP Law and now other, I believe another firm,

1141
01:47:56,767 --> 01:48:02,410
[SPEAKER_24]: and then won't let anybody know what the, is that my three minutes?

1142
01:48:02,770 --> 01:48:16,596
[SPEAKER_24]: So I'll just close out with saying, again, President Behrs, Councilor Scarpelli, and all of you, I appreciate your fortitude in making sure that the community and the taxpayer dollars are taken care of.

1143
01:48:16,936 --> 01:48:17,817
[SPEAKER_24]: I appreciate your time.

1144
01:48:18,497 --> 01:48:18,797
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1145
01:48:21,325 --> 01:48:25,867
[SPEAKER_07]: And the default sound changes every time, so I'm sorry it was like playing you off at the Oscars.

1146
01:48:25,928 --> 01:48:27,128
[SPEAKER_07]: It's usually just a beep.

1147
01:48:28,989 --> 01:48:30,210
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further public comment?

1148
01:48:32,711 --> 01:48:34,692
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, I'll recognize Councilor Scarpa.

1149
01:48:34,832 --> 01:48:43,656
[SPEAKER_21]: If I can, to that point that Mr. South brought forward about the city solicitor, we're also giving a breakdown for each department and what they're using for legal, the legal line.

1150
01:48:45,217 --> 01:48:46,837
[SPEAKER_21]: Not only did I share it with fellow,

1151
01:48:49,322 --> 01:49:11,046
[SPEAKER_21]: friends that are city solicitors, it's great because people that aren't as gifted like myself, you take that information, you add it into chat, and AI tells you exactly what the city of Medford and our departments are using, and then asking it, what is the role of a city solicitor?

1152
01:49:11,706 --> 01:49:18,027
[SPEAKER_21]: And if not most, all those requirements that were being fed out to outside law firms.

1153
01:49:18,974 --> 01:49:21,615
[SPEAKER_21]: Most of them are done by a city solicitor.

1154
01:49:22,036 --> 01:49:25,077
[SPEAKER_21]: So I think that's an interesting point that you brought forward and wanted to share.

1155
01:49:25,417 --> 01:49:26,718
[SPEAKER_21]: I forgot to mention that earlier.

1156
01:49:26,758 --> 01:49:27,719
[SPEAKER_21]: But thank you, Mr. President.

1157
01:49:28,619 --> 01:49:29,579
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Scarpelli.

1158
01:49:31,540 --> 01:49:35,362
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing no further discussion by members of the council or the public on this item, is there a motion?

1159
01:49:35,382 --> 01:49:37,984
[SPEAKER_07]: Motion to approve.

1160
01:49:38,004 --> 01:49:40,545
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion to approve by Councilor Sang, seconded by?

1161
01:49:42,086 --> 01:49:46,548
[SPEAKER_07]: Seconded by Vice President Lazaro.

1162
01:49:46,968 --> 01:49:47,889
[SPEAKER_07]: Chief of Staff Nazarian.

1163
01:49:53,062 --> 01:49:55,324
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not sure what would be helpful in this discussion.

1164
01:49:55,384 --> 01:49:58,727
[SPEAKER_25]: If there's anything that can be said that would be helpful in this discussion at this point.

1165
01:49:58,807 --> 01:50:02,330
[SPEAKER_25]: But, you know, I just want to.

1166
01:50:07,891 --> 01:50:15,758
[SPEAKER_25]: I think it's important for us to have a discussion about what we can do.

1167
01:50:16,979 --> 01:50:21,403
[SPEAKER_25]: I think there's a number of other discussion items here before the council.

1168
01:50:21,644 --> 01:50:28,810
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't have an issue with an appeal being filed by the council on the public records request or whatever.

1169
01:50:31,012 --> 01:50:32,433
[SPEAKER_25]: steps that the council wishes to take.

1170
01:50:32,754 --> 01:50:53,227
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not here to oppose that, but I just want to remind the council that we're happy to have a discussion so that we can go through the records in a manner that's systematic and actually can provide some guidance because of the cumbersome nature of the records request.

1171
01:50:53,788 --> 01:50:56,910
[SPEAKER_25]: So, you know, just to throw a thought out there, if the council

1172
01:50:58,530 --> 01:51:05,475
[SPEAKER_25]: were to potentially designate a member or two of the council to have discussions that would be helpful in our process.

1173
01:51:06,195 --> 01:51:15,762
[SPEAKER_25]: But, you know, not standing in the way of any appeals being filed, just stating that to assist the process, if that's helpful.

1174
01:51:17,023 --> 01:51:17,764
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Madam Chief.

1175
01:51:17,784 --> 01:51:22,207
[SPEAKER_07]: I think, and I see Councilor Scarpelli, for me, what would be helpful is understanding

1176
01:51:23,447 --> 01:51:32,533
[SPEAKER_07]: what clarifying questions you and the administration may have to the February request or the April request or the subsequent budget meeting requests.

1177
01:51:33,093 --> 01:51:38,236
[SPEAKER_07]: Like, I think we've obviously presented a number of questions.

1178
01:51:38,436 --> 01:51:47,442
[SPEAKER_07]: I think at least I and my communications with you and the mayor have asked some maybe more narrow questions that I think get to the heart of some of this.

1179
01:51:47,542 --> 01:51:52,325
[SPEAKER_07]: But I think, I mean, I think we're really talking about a spreadsheet, a table, a chart,

1180
01:51:53,000 --> 01:51:58,819
[SPEAKER_07]: that talks about the aggregate cost to the city of legal matters over the last six years.

1181
01:52:00,469 --> 01:52:11,871
[SPEAKER_07]: you know, some sort of data-driven approach so that we can know how much have we spent, on what things, and then also, I think, going forward, how much we expect to spend.

1182
01:52:11,891 --> 01:52:23,893
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, I appreciate that we got the answer today about the fire department budget, but the answer today was we spent $150,000 on KP law out of the fire department budget last year, and, you know, that's a significant number, right?

1183
01:52:24,033 --> 01:52:26,574
[SPEAKER_07]: Like, even from the communications that

1184
01:52:27,509 --> 01:52:28,950
[SPEAKER_07]: you have sent to the past, right?

1185
01:52:29,210 --> 01:52:30,151
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, well, we only spent 450,000.

1186
01:52:30,411 --> 01:52:32,573
[SPEAKER_07]: This is 2022, right?

1187
01:52:32,653 --> 01:52:39,018
[SPEAKER_07]: But that's 25% of, you know, that's another 25%, right, if there's another 150,000 on that.

1188
01:52:39,099 --> 01:52:49,567
[SPEAKER_07]: So I don't have a clear understanding of what we're spending on legal services across all the departmental budgets.

1189
01:52:50,968 --> 01:52:56,393
[SPEAKER_07]: I can maybe understand the principle of what you noted in your email earlier of putting those out to,

1190
01:52:58,380 --> 01:53:01,901
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, if there's a service for a specific department, that that department's budget pays for it.

1191
01:53:01,941 --> 01:53:06,242
[SPEAKER_07]: But I think that also obscures the cost of legal services since we also have a law department budget.

1192
01:53:08,602 --> 01:53:24,585
[SPEAKER_07]: So if there are clarifying questions to especially, I think, the February resolution, which I think was maybe the most comprehensive but also not necessarily requiring the public records law standards that the April request has, that would be helpful for me.

1193
01:53:26,718 --> 01:53:38,867
[SPEAKER_07]: I have any answers to those clarifying questions that might get us to the point of getting the information we're looking for, but I just think the bit one-offs and like are not answering the question.

1194
01:53:38,887 --> 01:53:46,472
[SPEAKER_07]: And I personally feel like we've communicated many times what our questions are, so that's like where I'm running into a struggle is.

1195
01:53:47,955 --> 01:53:57,062
[SPEAKER_07]: I feel like we've articulated the questions, re-articulated the questions, several different ways and approaches, but the answers are not forthcoming.

1196
01:53:58,883 --> 01:53:59,684
[SPEAKER_07]: That's my two cents.

1197
01:54:00,684 --> 01:54:05,228
[SPEAKER_07]: And if you want to respond to that now or if you want to wait, I can recognize Councilor Scarpelli.

1198
01:54:05,448 --> 01:54:05,688
[SPEAKER_25]: It's fine.

1199
01:54:05,708 --> 01:54:06,429
[SPEAKER_07]: All right, great.

1200
01:54:06,929 --> 01:54:07,570
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Scarpelli.

1201
01:54:07,590 --> 01:54:09,691
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you, Mr. President.

1202
01:54:10,111 --> 01:54:14,615
[SPEAKER_21]: To the podium, I don't know what else we can do to simplify this.

1203
01:54:15,635 --> 01:54:17,537
[SPEAKER_21]: I've asked these questions years ago.

1204
01:54:18,405 --> 01:54:29,337
[SPEAKER_21]: We brought it forth as a team to understand that we want to know what we're spending so we can also understand the motives behind what we're spending.

1205
01:54:29,977 --> 01:54:35,103
[SPEAKER_21]: Because it's not a secret that it seems like the question you're asking, it's new to you.

1206
01:54:36,090 --> 01:54:47,313
[SPEAKER_21]: The increase in lawsuits from just our city employees coming from this administration over the last six years have been an increase of over 590%.

1207
01:54:48,053 --> 01:54:49,454
[SPEAKER_21]: That's not a secret.

1208
01:54:50,234 --> 01:54:58,896
[SPEAKER_21]: So with those numbers and understanding what we've been asking for and not getting any answer at all, so the public can understand.

1209
01:54:58,976 --> 01:55:04,078
[SPEAKER_21]: So because it seems like for the people that are tuning in right now might be a little befuddled as well.

1210
01:55:05,990 --> 01:55:08,894
[SPEAKER_21]: Apologize for the time constraint, but I'm going to explain something.

1211
01:55:10,135 --> 01:55:14,501
[SPEAKER_21]: On the 28th, we legally asked and implemented the FOIA request.

1212
01:55:14,982 --> 01:55:19,367
[SPEAKER_21]: It's a public record request that spelt out exactly what we wanted.

1213
01:55:20,489 --> 01:55:24,214
[SPEAKER_21]: Pursuant to mass general law, we went through that, the request

1214
01:55:27,318 --> 01:55:42,105
[SPEAKER_21]: all public records that contain any reference to lawsuits, claims, administrative proceedings, arbitrations, and or other legal actions in which the city of Medford and or Brianna Lungo Cone is her capacity as mayor.

1215
01:55:42,585 --> 01:55:57,789
[SPEAKER_21]: of the City of Medford is or was named party, whether it's as plaintiff, defendant, respondent, or intervener in any court, tribunal, or administrative body, including but not limited to United States District Court, Mass.

1216
01:55:57,829 --> 01:56:12,052
[SPEAKER_21]: Superior Court, Land Court, Massachusetts Appeals Court, Supreme Judicial Court, Civil Service Commission, the Department of Labor Relations, the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination, House Appeals Committee, the State Ethics Commission,

1217
01:56:12,832 --> 01:56:17,593
[SPEAKER_21]: the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, and any other federal, state, or local forum.

1218
01:56:18,394 --> 01:56:41,280
[SPEAKER_21]: For each lawsuit, claim, administrative proceedings, arbitrations, or other legal actions that included in any response to subsection of this request, please provide all public records that contain any reference to each matter, including the full case name, the docketed case number, the forum, the date filed, nature of the claim,

1219
01:56:42,553 --> 01:56:52,862
[SPEAKER_21]: and present status, for example, whether it is presently pending or has been settled, dismissed, adjudicated, or resolved in any fashion.

1220
01:56:54,687 --> 01:57:13,337
[SPEAKER_21]: C. All public records that contain any indication of the costs of representation and related litigation costs paid by the City of Medford regarding each lawsuit, claim, administrative proceedings, arbitration, or other legal action that is included in the response to subsection A of this request.

1221
01:57:14,838 --> 01:57:30,264
[SPEAKER_21]: including all records indicating fee paid to outside counsel, identified by firm name and total amount per firm, expert witness fees, court costs, mediation, and arbitration fees, and any other litigation-related expenditures.

1222
01:57:31,073 --> 01:57:54,928
[SPEAKER_21]: D, all public records that contain any indication of costs of representation and or related litigation costs paid by the city of Method using the funds received by the city pursuant to the American Rescue Plan Act 2021 ARPA for each lawsuit claim, administrative proceedings, arbitrations, or other legal actions that included in the response to subsection A of this request.

1223
01:57:55,288 --> 01:57:58,150
[SPEAKER_21]: This request includes all records

1224
01:57:58,650 --> 01:58:10,415
[SPEAKER_21]: related to fees paid to outside counsel identified by firm name, total amount per firm, expert witness fees, court costs, mediations, arbitrations, fees, other litigation-related expenditures.

1225
01:58:11,420 --> 01:58:36,856
[SPEAKER_21]: E, all public records containing any indication of settlement payments, judgments, awards, and other monetary considerations paid by the city for each lawsuit, claim, administrative proceeding, arbitration, or other legal action that is included in the response to subsection A of the request, including all payments made by insurance carriers pursuant to policies insurance that provided coverage to the city of Medford or its employees.

1226
01:58:37,557 --> 01:58:37,577
[SPEAKER_21]: F,

1227
01:58:38,434 --> 01:58:53,241
[SPEAKER_21]: all public records that contain any indication of any payment or cost reimbursements or other considerations paid by the city to any private investigative services, detective services or surveillance services of any kind or for any purpose since January 2020.

1228
01:58:53,621 --> 01:59:03,045
[SPEAKER_21]: This includes any payments or costs reimbursed or other considerations paid to any person or entity who on behalf of the city of method then hired

1229
01:59:03,405 --> 01:59:10,559
[SPEAKER_21]: maintained or employed any private investigative service, detective service, or surveillance service of any kind since January 2020.

1230
01:59:12,778 --> 01:59:36,950
[SPEAKER_21]: All public records, including but not limited to emails, memoranda, reports, meeting minutes, internal communications that refer to relate to the deletion, destruction, removal, alteration, or any other dispositions of records that relate to each lawsuit, claim, administrative proceedings, arbitration, or other legal actions that included in response to subsection A in this request.

1231
01:59:38,005 --> 01:59:55,120
[SPEAKER_21]: H, all logs, reports, memorandums, systems generated, or other records that track or document the deletion of destruction of records that relate to each lawsuit, claims, administrative proceedings, arbitrations, or other legal actions, including the response of subsection A in request.

1232
01:59:56,000 --> 02:00:05,684
[SPEAKER_21]: I, copies of non-disclosure disagreements that are currently in effect or were entered into the City of MEF in January 1, 2020, to the date of this request.

1233
02:00:06,144 --> 02:00:20,470
[SPEAKER_21]: This includes, but not limited to, the confidentiality agreement settlements, agreements containing non-disclosure provisions, and limited to confidentiality agreements, settlements agreements, non-disclosure provisions, and any other agreements that contain confidential

1234
02:00:20,990 --> 02:00:35,842
[SPEAKER_21]: confidentiality and non-disclosure clauses to which the City of Medford and or Brianna Lungo Kern, in her capacity as Mayor of the City of Medford, is or was named party, whether plaintiff, defendant, respondent, intervener or any other capacity.

1235
02:00:36,403 --> 02:00:42,868
[SPEAKER_21]: If there is any fee searching or copying these records, please inform the Council of the cost.

1236
02:00:43,476 --> 02:00:44,257
[SPEAKER_21]: that it exceeds $100.

1237
02:00:45,397 --> 02:01:01,448
[SPEAKER_21]: Please note, the council is requesting a waiver for the fee for the disclosure request informing information that is of public record interest and will contribute significantly to the public understanding of the administration litigation history and expenditures since 2020.

1238
02:01:02,289 --> 02:01:09,194
[SPEAKER_21]: The public understands that the history of expenditures is especially important in the light that the administration's failure to respond to

1239
02:01:09,714 --> 02:01:18,879
[SPEAKER_21]: the City Council Resolution 26043 that was passed February 24th, 2026, in which a council essentially requested similar records.

1240
02:01:19,360 --> 02:01:33,688
[SPEAKER_21]: The request for the council for non-disclosure agreement anticipated the need of possible redactions, but as of Justice Botsford said, for the court in Champa v. Weston Public Schools 473 Mass 86,

1241
02:01:37,777 --> 02:01:48,410
[SPEAKER_21]: case involving student records, the inclusion of contractual confidential clause does not, does not apply.

1242
02:01:48,530 --> 02:01:51,694
[SPEAKER_21]: So this information request is not being sought for commercial purposes.

1243
02:01:54,718 --> 02:01:55,900
[SPEAKER_21]: Onward and onward.

1244
02:01:57,007 --> 02:01:57,868
[SPEAKER_21]: This is spelled out.

1245
02:01:58,529 --> 02:02:01,413
[SPEAKER_21]: And the reason why, because these questions were asked very simple.

1246
02:02:01,433 --> 02:02:10,305
[SPEAKER_21]: And the simple question was just a simple breakdown of what we're paying our legal teams for all of these lawsuits.

1247
02:02:11,749 --> 02:02:13,692
[SPEAKER_21]: But nothing was responded.

1248
02:02:14,653 --> 02:02:15,735
[SPEAKER_21]: To your credit, you were right.

1249
02:02:15,775 --> 02:02:20,021
[SPEAKER_21]: The mayor stood at this podium a few weeks ago and said, we're in compliance.

1250
02:02:20,822 --> 02:02:24,768
[SPEAKER_21]: We spend $110,000 in the legal line or whatever it was, and we're spending under that.

1251
02:02:24,808 --> 02:02:27,472
[SPEAKER_21]: She wasn't wrong, but she's not listening to us.

1252
02:02:28,388 --> 02:02:31,990
[SPEAKER_21]: We've been asking year after year, month after month, for this breakdown.

1253
02:02:32,470 --> 02:02:40,853
[SPEAKER_21]: This is legally in process, so I appreciate my council president saying that he maybe would accept something lighter.

1254
02:02:41,293 --> 02:02:42,174
[SPEAKER_21]: I personally do not.

1255
02:02:42,734 --> 02:02:49,257
[SPEAKER_21]: I want what we're asking for now, because what I'm seeing so far in communications with your office, it seems like

1256
02:02:50,663 --> 02:02:51,684
[SPEAKER_21]: It makes no sense.

1257
02:02:52,424 --> 02:02:55,646
[SPEAKER_21]: The breakdown that we're getting is total opposite of what I just read.

1258
02:02:56,227 --> 02:02:59,849
[SPEAKER_21]: It seems like it's deflection, deflection, deflection.

1259
02:03:00,789 --> 02:03:01,550
[SPEAKER_21]: And I don't know why.

1260
02:03:02,571 --> 02:03:08,895
[SPEAKER_21]: So until we see these documents legally, then I will not vote for any budget.

1261
02:03:09,015 --> 02:03:16,419
[SPEAKER_21]: I will not move forward with anything until we know that our money being spent in our city is being spent correctly.

1262
02:03:17,920 --> 02:03:18,721
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you, Mr. President.

1263
02:03:20,008 --> 02:03:21,049
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councillor Scarpelli.

1264
02:03:21,290 --> 02:03:26,597
[SPEAKER_07]: And yeah, I mean, just to clarify too, I wasn't necessarily saying accept something less, but like.

1265
02:03:28,748 --> 02:03:35,191
[SPEAKER_07]: some sort of document that at least it shows we're making progress, because I don't think what we've received really shows that to me.

1266
02:03:35,611 --> 02:03:37,012
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's more what I was trying to say.

1267
02:03:37,252 --> 02:03:37,592
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1268
02:03:38,092 --> 02:03:40,453
[SPEAKER_07]: Madam Chief of Staff.

1269
02:03:40,533 --> 02:03:40,853
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

1270
02:03:40,873 --> 02:03:41,834
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't want to belabor the point.

1271
02:03:42,474 --> 02:03:50,778
[SPEAKER_25]: I'll just say that, as I have said at a prior city council meeting, this public records request and even the resolution is incredibly voluminous.

1272
02:03:51,538 --> 02:03:58,040
[SPEAKER_25]: We have made good faith attempts to send the council information with regard to settlement agreements that exist.

1273
02:03:58,660 --> 02:04:04,242
[SPEAKER_25]: And we've also sent the breakdown for the fire department that was requested.

1274
02:04:05,362 --> 02:04:15,485
[SPEAKER_25]: As the mayor has said before, as I've said this evening, I've just wanted to let the council know that we are happy to continue the discussion on this to make sure that the council gets the records that it's requesting.

1275
02:04:15,705 --> 02:04:16,885
[SPEAKER_25]: That was my only intention.

1276
02:04:17,445 --> 02:04:17,705
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

1277
02:04:18,905 --> 02:04:19,206
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1278
02:04:19,646 --> 02:04:20,606
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Scarpelli.

1279
02:04:22,365 --> 02:04:23,806
[SPEAKER_21]: Well, while the Chief of Staff is here.

1280
02:04:26,968 --> 02:04:27,769
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, Councilor Scrivelly.

1281
02:04:27,889 --> 02:04:28,429
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

1282
02:04:28,669 --> 02:04:32,472
[SPEAKER_21]: So maybe the public can understand where the frustration comes in.

1283
02:04:32,932 --> 02:04:37,175
[SPEAKER_21]: The mayor stood at this podium and said, we never have never done non-disclosure agreements.

1284
02:04:38,456 --> 02:04:45,961
[SPEAKER_21]: But the first two lawsuits you sent us, the settlements, distinctly said that was in place.

1285
02:04:47,282 --> 02:04:50,404
[SPEAKER_21]: So right off the bat, the trust and understanding

1286
02:04:51,042 --> 02:04:54,543
[SPEAKER_21]: that maybe we're not getting the information we want is out the window.

1287
02:04:55,944 --> 02:04:58,765
[SPEAKER_21]: Because we have those in place for many, many years.

1288
02:04:59,785 --> 02:05:02,526
[SPEAKER_21]: And you proved it by sending those documents to us.

1289
02:05:03,507 --> 02:05:12,330
[SPEAKER_21]: So just that alone, it just spells out the questioning behind whether we're really going to get this information or not correctly.

1290
02:05:12,890 --> 02:05:16,912
[SPEAKER_21]: Now, the answer was a few weeks ago was this is just too much work.

1291
02:05:17,650 --> 02:05:18,751
[SPEAKER_21]: This was just too much work.

1292
02:05:19,151 --> 02:05:24,116
[SPEAKER_21]: You spent more time sending us information that has nothing to do what we asked for.

1293
02:05:25,698 --> 02:05:26,258
[SPEAKER_21]: It really doesn't.

1294
02:05:26,739 --> 02:05:28,560
[SPEAKER_21]: We asked for the FOIA request.

1295
02:05:28,961 --> 02:05:29,842
[SPEAKER_21]: That's what we asked you to do.

1296
02:05:30,722 --> 02:05:35,927
[SPEAKER_21]: So now we're moving on to the Secretary of State's office, and hopefully they can expedite this process, Mr. President.

1297
02:05:35,987 --> 02:05:36,328
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

1298
02:05:37,148 --> 02:05:37,509
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

1299
02:05:39,398 --> 02:05:42,279
[SPEAKER_25]: One minor piece of clarification.

1300
02:05:42,699 --> 02:05:56,424
[SPEAKER_25]: When a settlement agreement states that it is confidential to the extent permissible by law, that means essentially and effectively that if we receive a public records request, we are obligated to release it.

1301
02:05:58,024 --> 02:06:00,946
[SPEAKER_25]: So those agreements contain that language.

1302
02:06:01,006 --> 02:06:03,066
[SPEAKER_25]: So I think that's an important clarification to make.

1303
02:06:04,387 --> 02:06:05,227
[SPEAKER_25]: So that's it.

1304
02:06:05,367 --> 02:06:07,748
[SPEAKER_25]: I've said everything I need to say.

1305
02:06:07,788 --> 02:06:08,048
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

1306
02:06:08,753 --> 02:06:18,521
[SPEAKER_07]: I just wanted to clarify though, those also contain some agreements that say we aren't going to basically speak publicly, right, about these matters?

1307
02:06:20,142 --> 02:06:22,264
[SPEAKER_07]: And those are like essentially nondisclosure?

1308
02:06:24,486 --> 02:06:26,848
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not an attorney, as you know, President Bares.

1309
02:06:27,688 --> 02:06:32,512
[SPEAKER_25]: But to answer your question, it's my understanding that that would not qualify as a nondisclosure agreement.

1310
02:06:33,133 --> 02:06:33,373
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

1311
02:06:37,658 --> 02:06:59,786
[SPEAKER_07]: I will just say this to belabor the point we've been belaboring, but, like, is there a spreadsheet in the law department of all of the legal cases against the city, whether that's lawsuits or formal complaints to state and federal bodies,

1312
02:07:02,711 --> 02:07:06,873
[SPEAKER_07]: arbitrations, like, is there a spreadsheet of all of the things that we're facing?

1313
02:07:07,513 --> 02:07:26,301
[SPEAKER_07]: And then is there a SharePoint folder with all the documents for that case, and a column in the spreadsheet that says this is how much we spent on this, and a column that says this is the status, it's closed, it's open, it's, like, that's really what I'm just wondering, like, I mean, essentially, what Councilor Scarpelli read is that, right?

1314
02:07:26,862 --> 02:07:29,363
[SPEAKER_07]: It's what, is there a document somewhere that has,

1315
02:07:30,426 --> 02:07:34,810
[SPEAKER_07]: all of the information relevant to legal proceedings that the city is involved in?

1316
02:07:35,330 --> 02:07:36,571
[SPEAKER_25]: President Behr is not to my knowledge.

1317
02:07:36,911 --> 02:07:37,192
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

1318
02:07:37,412 --> 02:07:39,333
[SPEAKER_07]: And like that's, yeah.

1319
02:07:39,654 --> 02:07:39,934
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

1320
02:07:41,996 --> 02:07:42,316
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1321
02:07:42,776 --> 02:07:46,199
[SPEAKER_25]: Not to my knowledge for the last 30, 40, however many years.

1322
02:07:46,359 --> 02:07:46,659
[SPEAKER_25]: Sure.

1323
02:07:47,860 --> 02:07:48,141
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

1324
02:07:52,124 --> 02:07:55,707
[SPEAKER_07]: There is a hand on Zoom.

1325
02:07:58,158 --> 02:08:00,639
[SPEAKER_07]: We do have a motion on the floor, but I'll just do it.

1326
02:08:03,661 --> 02:08:07,042
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Castaneda, if you give your name and city for the record, please, you have three minutes.

1327
02:08:12,445 --> 02:08:13,865
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, Councilor Beers.

1328
02:08:15,126 --> 02:08:15,686
[SPEAKER_00]: Can you hear me?

1329
02:08:16,447 --> 02:08:17,127
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes, we can hear you.

1330
02:08:17,787 --> 02:08:18,528
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, thank you.

1331
02:08:18,668 --> 02:08:19,748
[SPEAKER_00]: Appreciate the time.

1332
02:08:21,669 --> 02:08:23,650
[SPEAKER_00]: You people are talking a lot better than me.

1333
02:08:24,705 --> 02:08:33,430
[SPEAKER_00]: I simply want to say we the people deserve a comprehensive accountant of all lawsuits versus the city for the last five years.

1334
02:08:34,591 --> 02:08:36,532
[SPEAKER_00]: After all, this is our money.

1335
02:08:37,272 --> 02:08:38,633
[SPEAKER_00]: Taxpayers' money.

1336
02:08:39,413 --> 02:08:39,914
[SPEAKER_00]: Period.

1337
02:08:40,314 --> 02:08:40,734
[SPEAKER_00]: Good night.

1338
02:08:42,455 --> 02:08:42,915
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1339
02:08:42,935 --> 02:08:47,778
[SPEAKER_07]: We got one minute.

1340
02:08:54,249 --> 02:09:08,780
[SPEAKER_04]: So okay there's no record of that like the cases and and the legal matters that the city has been involved in that's crazy but whatever you still know what.

1341
02:09:10,300 --> 02:09:18,682
[SPEAKER_04]: Firms you have worked with, ask them to report out the matters that they have billed you.

1342
02:09:19,302 --> 02:09:21,502
[SPEAKER_04]: Like that's, they will provide that information.

1343
02:09:21,722 --> 02:09:23,002
[SPEAKER_04]: They do have a spreadsheet.

1344
02:09:23,103 --> 02:09:24,963
[SPEAKER_04]: You're not hiring better call Saul.

1345
02:09:25,223 --> 02:09:26,883
[SPEAKER_04]: Like you're hiring real law firms.

1346
02:09:27,423 --> 02:09:28,544
[SPEAKER_04]: They will have that spreadsheet.

1347
02:09:29,004 --> 02:09:30,904
[SPEAKER_04]: You can just get that information from them.

1348
02:09:31,344 --> 02:09:33,365
[SPEAKER_04]: And then you can redact whatever needs to be redacted.

1349
02:09:33,705 --> 02:09:35,025
[SPEAKER_04]: And I want to be clear about something too.

1350
02:09:36,881 --> 02:09:52,527
[SPEAKER_04]: Talking about the billing of a case does not necessitate talking about the substantive matter of the case, which might put you in violation of any confidentiality or NDA that came out of the case.

1351
02:09:52,687 --> 02:09:59,810
[SPEAKER_04]: So this still, even without that spreadsheet here, which that makes me very angry for a different reason.

1352
02:09:59,830 --> 02:10:02,931
[SPEAKER_04]: I would count to four inside and take a deep breath.

1353
02:10:06,268 --> 02:10:09,971
[SPEAKER_04]: you still have very easy ways to get this information.

1354
02:10:10,251 --> 02:10:16,296
[SPEAKER_04]: And it should be, it should have been gotten, received already, retrieved.

1355
02:10:16,516 --> 02:10:16,937
[SPEAKER_04]: It's easy.

1356
02:10:16,957 --> 02:10:18,038
[SPEAKER_04]: All right, that's it.

1357
02:10:18,198 --> 02:10:18,438
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks.

1358
02:10:19,759 --> 02:10:20,259
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

1359
02:10:30,127 --> 02:10:34,651
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion by Councilor Sang, seconded by Vice President Lazaro to approve, Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

1360
02:10:37,350 --> 02:10:38,090
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan?

1361
02:10:38,110 --> 02:10:38,170
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1362
02:10:39,910 --> 02:10:40,591
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming?

1363
02:10:41,391 --> 02:10:41,691
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1364
02:10:43,031 --> 02:10:43,511
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Mullane?

1365
02:10:43,531 --> 02:10:43,591
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1366
02:10:44,891 --> 02:10:45,712
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scarpelli?

1367
02:10:45,732 --> 02:10:45,832
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1368
02:10:46,992 --> 02:10:47,592
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Singh?

1369
02:10:48,432 --> 02:10:48,512
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1370
02:10:48,532 --> 02:10:49,332
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

1371
02:10:49,352 --> 02:10:49,452
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1372
02:10:50,932 --> 02:10:51,533
[SPEAKER_19]: President Pierce?

1373
02:10:52,073 --> 02:10:52,273
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

1374
02:10:52,313 --> 02:10:53,633
[SPEAKER_07]: Seven in the affirmative, none in the negative.

1375
02:10:53,653 --> 02:10:55,893
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion passes.

1376
02:10:55,913 --> 02:11:01,054
[SPEAKER_07]: 26-119 offered by Councilor Scarpelli, resolution to prepare 112th budget due to missing financial information.

1377
02:11:01,074 --> 02:11:04,395
[SPEAKER_07]: We resolve that in light of the administration's repeated failure,

1378
02:11:04,955 --> 02:11:27,629
[SPEAKER_07]: to provide the council with information regarding lawsuits, claims, costs, and other financial impacts of lawsuits, claims, administrative proceedings, arbitrations, and other legal actions, which would allow to properly discern whether to approve the budget submitted by the mayor, that the council vote to reject the budget submitted by the mayor, and instead vote that the mayor submit a 112th budget, which is a continuing appropriation budget on a month-to-month basis for a period not to exceed three months, pursuant to general law chapter 44, section 32.

1379
02:11:28,189 --> 02:11:28,969
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Scarpelli.

1380
02:11:28,989 --> 02:11:30,550
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you, Mr. President.

1381
02:11:32,331 --> 02:11:33,132
[SPEAKER_21]: I just want to

1382
02:11:33,912 --> 02:11:43,248
[SPEAKER_21]: remind my fellow counselors we sat at this budget meeting last year we were promised a bunch of things and when we

1383
02:11:44,209 --> 02:11:46,570
[SPEAKER_21]: We reluctantly decided to move forward with the budget.

1384
02:11:47,131 --> 02:11:50,612
[SPEAKER_21]: Those necessities that we required didn't happen.

1385
02:11:51,613 --> 02:11:52,874
[SPEAKER_21]: We don't have a city solicitor.

1386
02:11:54,154 --> 02:12:04,380
[SPEAKER_21]: There are concerns that as we move forward with this, that this is our right and our responsibility to make sure that we get the information so we can move

1387
02:12:05,900 --> 02:12:26,024
[SPEAKER_21]: forward with a trustful feeling when it comes to the budgeting process that the residents that elected us for is one of probably the, maybe the most important, if not the only two things that we really are in charge of doing here as city councilors.

1388
02:12:26,644 --> 02:12:28,185
[SPEAKER_21]: So simply put,

1389
02:12:31,111 --> 02:12:46,698
[SPEAKER_21]: The request is the mayor has up to three months, she could finish in one month, but the mayor has the process for a 1-12 budget to work on the fiscal 2025 budget.

1390
02:12:46,918 --> 02:12:54,842
[SPEAKER_21]: That's without us cutting anything, moving forward business as usual until we get the information on a month to month basis.

1391
02:12:54,902 --> 02:12:57,123
[SPEAKER_21]: We meet again in July, then we meet again in August.

1392
02:12:57,919 --> 02:13:24,775
[SPEAKER_21]: Hopefully, after reading the resolution out loud and the FOIA request out loud, hopefully the administration now knows what we're looking for and we can get that information so we, as city councilors and stewards of the fiscal responsibility of this position, that we know that we're making the decision that was thoughtful and all the information was presented properly so we know where our city taxpayers' money is going.

1393
02:13:26,198 --> 02:13:41,743
[SPEAKER_21]: I would request that my colleagues follow, approve my request in this resolution that we move to a 112th budget, and I believe that's chapter 44, section 32.

1394
02:13:42,684 --> 02:13:55,048
[SPEAKER_21]: And that will allow the city administration at least a month or two, or it's up to three months possible to correct the issues that we have

1395
02:13:55,876 --> 02:14:06,880
[SPEAKER_21]: and making sure that we are voting on a budget that we can feel confident that our taxpayers' money are being spent correctly.

1396
02:14:07,501 --> 02:14:12,222
[SPEAKER_21]: So I hope my colleagues would vote in support with that resolution.

1397
02:14:12,262 --> 02:14:13,183
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you, Mr. President.

1398
02:14:15,083 --> 02:14:16,504
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councillor Scarpelli.

1399
02:14:17,244 --> 02:14:19,285
[SPEAKER_07]: Any comments by members of the Council?

1400
02:14:21,906 --> 02:14:22,366
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Sen.

1401
02:14:28,147 --> 02:14:30,990
[SPEAKER_09]: Councilor Scarpelli and I have spoken before about this.

1402
02:14:32,451 --> 02:14:50,267
[SPEAKER_09]: I think throughout the process of crafting a budget, moving to a one-twelfth budget is an important option to leave on the table to get the answers that we've been wanting, to get the requests that we have made to be fulfilled.

1403
02:14:53,348 --> 02:14:58,889
[SPEAKER_09]: I am hesitant to vote on this first before we discuss the budget itself.

1404
02:15:00,390 --> 02:15:14,233
[SPEAKER_09]: Because even though the budget isn't perfect and I think there are changes that we can make to it, I don't want us to lose the supplemental appropriations.

1405
02:15:15,698 --> 02:15:17,759
[SPEAKER_09]: that residents have been asking so long for.

1406
02:15:18,219 --> 02:15:21,700
[SPEAKER_09]: For example, increasing the pay for librarian staff.

1407
02:15:22,000 --> 02:15:29,943
[SPEAKER_09]: For example, the money for, sorry, my brain short-circuiting a little bit.

1408
02:15:31,843 --> 02:15:34,084
[SPEAKER_09]: I mean, I think the librarian staff is one example of that.

1409
02:15:34,864 --> 02:15:41,867
[SPEAKER_09]: The arts, the small increases to arts, even though it's not enough in my opinion, it's a little bit of a step forward.

1410
02:15:44,523 --> 02:15:50,287
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's better for the council to have a conversation about those things first before we vote on this.

1411
02:15:50,507 --> 02:15:57,351
[SPEAKER_09]: So I would respectfully just move to table until we do that.

1412
02:16:00,313 --> 02:16:06,197
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion of Councilor Scarpelli to table until the end of the meeting, seconded by Councilor Sang.

1413
02:16:06,237 --> 02:16:07,158
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

1414
02:16:12,601 --> 02:16:13,422
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan.

1415
02:16:15,148 --> 02:16:15,848
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming?

1416
02:16:16,669 --> 02:16:17,009
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1417
02:16:18,190 --> 02:16:18,670
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Malay?

1418
02:16:18,690 --> 02:16:18,750
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1419
02:16:20,011 --> 02:16:20,791
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scapelli?

1420
02:16:20,811 --> 02:16:20,891
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1421
02:16:21,691 --> 02:16:22,212
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Hussain?

1422
02:16:22,232 --> 02:16:22,292
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1423
02:16:23,172 --> 02:16:23,973
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

1424
02:16:23,993 --> 02:16:24,053
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1425
02:16:24,893 --> 02:16:25,433
[SPEAKER_19]: President Pierce?

1426
02:16:26,294 --> 02:16:26,534
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

1427
02:16:26,714 --> 02:16:29,235
[SPEAKER_07]: Having the affirmative, none the negative, that's tabled to the end of the meeting.

1428
02:16:29,255 --> 02:16:31,957
[SPEAKER_07]: We have a few items and then we'll come back to the budget.

1429
02:16:32,037 --> 02:16:33,117
[SPEAKER_07]: Communications from the Mayor.

1430
02:16:33,137 --> 02:16:36,699
[SPEAKER_07]: 26105, free cash appropriation for the Affordable Housing Trust.

1431
02:16:37,239 --> 02:16:42,222
[SPEAKER_07]: So this is the 250,000 for the Affordable Housing Trust that we originally heard two meetings ago.

1432
02:16:42,806 --> 02:16:48,669
[SPEAKER_07]: We said that we wanted to hear the full picture on free cash, and we did hear that earlier.

1433
02:16:49,129 --> 02:16:55,472
[SPEAKER_07]: So we do have the following two papers, which is the 250,000 for the Affordable Housing Trust, and then 100,000 for the MFN.

1434
02:16:56,332 --> 02:17:02,175
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there any further discussion by members of the Council on the Affordable Housing Trust piece now that we've heard the full picture on free cash?

1435
02:17:06,197 --> 02:17:07,217
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, is there a motion?

1436
02:17:08,118 --> 02:17:08,958
[SPEAKER_20]: Motion to approve.

1437
02:17:09,803 --> 02:17:11,965
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion approved by Councilor Lemming, seconded by?

1438
02:17:12,425 --> 02:17:13,787
[SPEAKER_07]: Seconded by Vice President Lazaro.

1439
02:17:13,827 --> 02:17:14,868
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

1440
02:17:17,190 --> 02:17:17,950
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan?

1441
02:17:19,291 --> 02:17:19,952
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming?

1442
02:17:21,473 --> 02:17:21,774
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1443
02:17:23,075 --> 02:17:23,575
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilman Layne?

1444
02:17:23,595 --> 02:17:23,655
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1445
02:17:26,017 --> 02:17:26,818
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scott Pelli?

1446
02:17:26,838 --> 02:17:26,918
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1447
02:17:28,139 --> 02:17:28,720
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Singh?

1448
02:17:28,740 --> 02:17:28,820
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1449
02:17:30,161 --> 02:17:30,882
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

1450
02:17:32,586 --> 02:17:33,386
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Behrs?

1451
02:17:33,486 --> 02:17:33,706
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

1452
02:17:33,726 --> 02:17:35,067
[SPEAKER_07]: I have the affirmative, none the negative.

1453
02:17:35,087 --> 02:17:35,967
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion passes.

1454
02:17:35,987 --> 02:17:40,588
[SPEAKER_07]: 26121, submitted by Mayor Brianna Lingo-Kern, free cash appropriation for Medford Family Network.

1455
02:17:41,109 --> 02:17:55,533
[SPEAKER_07]: Dear President Behrs and City Councillors, I respectfully request and recommend that your Honorable Body approves the appropriation of free cash in the amount of $100,000 for the Medford Family Network for a grant to bridge a funding gap that MFN has identified given the loss of funding from one of their major funders, the Children's Trust.

1456
02:17:56,254 --> 02:17:59,618
[SPEAKER_07]: MFN has identified a funding need of $240,000 for fiscal 27.

1457
02:18:00,179 --> 02:18:05,065
[SPEAKER_07]: Fortunately, through efforts by our state delegation, school committee members, and myself, Tufts University is donating $50,000.

1458
02:18:05,546 --> 02:18:09,110
[SPEAKER_07]: The Cummings Foundation is providing a $100,000 grant for a period of three years.

1459
02:18:09,571 --> 02:18:11,613
[SPEAKER_07]: And Senator Jalen has been working hard on a $100,000 budget amendment.

1460
02:18:13,315 --> 02:18:20,819
[SPEAKER_07]: This free cash appropriation together with other funding sources that haven't secured or currently being pursued will enable the city to begin developing a formal grant agreement this summer.

1461
02:18:20,980 --> 02:18:27,063
[SPEAKER_07]: In the meantime, MFN can rely on grant funds that is already received or expects to receive to support operations through at least the first quarter.

1462
02:18:27,483 --> 02:18:35,528
[SPEAKER_07]: If funding for MFN is not provided in the upcoming state budget, I will work with you all to increase the amount of funds available for the city's one-time grant to MFN to avoid any shortfalls.

1463
02:18:35,988 --> 02:18:43,296
[SPEAKER_07]: We want to be clear that negotiating and executing the grant agreement will take time and we are all working to ensure the process is completed thoughtfully and in accordance with all legal requirements.

1464
02:18:43,496 --> 02:18:50,903
[SPEAKER_07]: As of the submission of the request, the balance of free cash is $21,012,459, respectfully submitted, Brianna Lugo-Kern, Mayor.

1465
02:18:52,825 --> 02:18:59,412
[SPEAKER_07]: Chief of Staff Nazarian or Director Dickinson, is there anything you want to add to the Mayor's letter, your call?

1466
02:19:10,175 --> 02:19:11,016
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, President Behrs.

1467
02:19:11,096 --> 02:19:12,457
[SPEAKER_25]: No, I don't have anything further to add.

1468
02:19:12,617 --> 02:19:14,078
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm happy to answer any questions, however.

1469
02:19:14,098 --> 02:19:14,739
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

1470
02:19:15,479 --> 02:19:20,944
[SPEAKER_07]: Do we have any questions or comments from members of the City Council on the proposed free cash funding for the MFN?

1471
02:19:21,044 --> 02:19:22,004
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Moline.

1472
02:19:23,686 --> 02:19:25,487
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you for putting this together.

1473
02:19:25,587 --> 02:19:36,576
[SPEAKER_03]: I know that I think all of us on the City Council, I guess I should say for myself, have received a lot of feedback about how critical and important it is to provide this type of funding.

1474
02:19:38,277 --> 02:19:48,300
[SPEAKER_03]: Having worked in non-profit, I also know how difficult it is especially to get funding when it comes to staff support outside of just even programmatics and knowing this could go to it.

1475
02:19:48,820 --> 02:20:06,126
[SPEAKER_03]: I just definitely wanted to confirm because I see that there is that 100,000 budget amendment that we still are unsure of whether that is and that I just wanted to triple check that yes, if that doesn't come through, we'll be able to have another conversation to provide that bridge funding at least for this year.

1476
02:20:06,687 --> 02:20:10,650
[SPEAKER_03]: to ensure that they have everything they need in order to operate for the next fiscal year.

1477
02:20:13,793 --> 02:20:14,934
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, President Behrs.

1478
02:20:14,974 --> 02:20:28,225
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes, if Councilor Malauulu, if you're referring to the Cummings, sorry, if you're referring to the work that Senator Jalen is doing to get a budget amendment, yes, this appropriation would provide a bridge either way.

1479
02:20:28,245 --> 02:20:29,706
[SPEAKER_25]: Okay, great.

1480
02:20:29,846 --> 02:20:30,206
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

1481
02:20:33,269 --> 02:20:33,749
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1482
02:20:34,049 --> 02:20:34,630
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Sang.

1483
02:20:35,951 --> 02:20:36,412
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

1484
02:20:37,193 --> 02:20:47,581
[SPEAKER_09]: I know for me as a counselor, getting the MFN funded through the next fiscal year has been one of my top, if not the top priority of this budget.

1485
02:20:49,903 --> 02:20:58,591
[SPEAKER_09]: Given that it is such a resource for our community, for our families, for our children, I think we've waxed poetic about it many times in the past before.

1486
02:20:59,672 --> 02:21:02,414
[SPEAKER_09]: But especially in the time of rising cost of living,

1487
02:21:05,961 --> 02:21:19,824
[SPEAKER_09]: The MFN stands as a resource that is pivotal for families and pivotal for children to continue developing socially and in terms of education.

1488
02:21:19,844 --> 02:21:29,607
[SPEAKER_09]: I want to thank, I know various counselors have led on different fronts with regards to this, school committee members as well.

1489
02:21:30,327 --> 02:21:32,928
[SPEAKER_09]: And I want to make sure that everyone gets recognized for their work.

1490
02:21:34,271 --> 02:21:37,813
[SPEAKER_09]: work that oftentimes gets conveyed to residents in emails or in public.

1491
02:21:38,934 --> 02:21:42,736
[SPEAKER_09]: But between, I think we've all played different roles.

1492
02:21:43,597 --> 02:21:50,521
[SPEAKER_09]: Some of us in really getting this to the attention of the council and to the mayor, the public.

1493
02:21:50,921 --> 02:21:56,504
[SPEAKER_09]: Some of us have been involved directly in conversations between offices about getting this funded.

1494
02:21:58,229 --> 02:22:05,434
[SPEAKER_09]: I've been in contact with state legislators and for congressmen, our congresspeople about this as well.

1495
02:22:07,795 --> 02:22:10,337
[SPEAKER_09]: And it's taken a village.

1496
02:22:10,997 --> 02:22:16,041
[SPEAKER_09]: So I just want to say that and say that I am happy that something is getting done.

1497
02:22:16,741 --> 02:22:20,364
[SPEAKER_09]: I think Councilor Mullane and I have talked about this.

1498
02:22:20,484 --> 02:22:26,568
[SPEAKER_09]: It is important to ensure stability for the MFN going forward, the difficulties in terms

1499
02:22:27,467 --> 02:22:38,414
[SPEAKER_09]: staff support just by only having one year can be really difficult, especially when they may need more support for development for fundraising.

1500
02:22:40,035 --> 02:22:45,779
[SPEAKER_09]: But I think that's a conversation for us all to continue to have as well after this gets approved.

1501
02:22:46,199 --> 02:22:52,183
[SPEAKER_09]: I think my one question to the chief of staff through the chair is just for the, if the $100,000 doesn't work,

1502
02:22:55,207 --> 02:23:03,053
[SPEAKER_09]: just to follow up on the previous question, what's the plan of where we're drawing the funds from to cover that?

1503
02:23:04,494 --> 02:23:10,658
[SPEAKER_25]: Through you, President Behrs, I think the reality is we will address that, you know, if the reality comes to that point.

1504
02:23:11,839 --> 02:23:20,104
[SPEAKER_25]: But, you know, we are committed, the mayor is committed to working with this council on ensuring that, you know, we continue to support this

1505
02:23:21,185 --> 02:23:27,089
[SPEAKER_25]: obviously incredible program in Medford that I think, I don't know if it was Councilor Callahan that said it earlier.

1506
02:23:27,109 --> 02:23:28,550
[SPEAKER_25]: I believe it was you, Councilor.

1507
02:23:30,392 --> 02:23:33,254
[SPEAKER_25]: As a person with a small child, I agree wholeheartedly.

1508
02:23:34,254 --> 02:23:41,700
[SPEAKER_25]: You know, anyone in another community would be jealous of what resources this organization provides, the residents of Medford and its

1509
02:23:42,380 --> 02:23:44,822
[SPEAKER_25]: It's an incredible and special thing.

1510
02:23:45,342 --> 02:23:56,328
[SPEAKER_25]: I think that everyone here on this council, the mayor, and anyone who's interacted with MFN or, you know, had the opportunity and fortune to utilize the services of MFN see that.

1511
02:23:57,049 --> 02:23:58,469
[SPEAKER_25]: So, thank you.

1512
02:23:59,830 --> 02:24:06,834
[SPEAKER_09]: Just to clarify, yep, through the chair, are we looking, I mean, hopefully we get the $100,000.

1513
02:24:07,074 --> 02:24:09,115
[SPEAKER_09]: That would be really ideal.

1514
02:24:09,175 --> 02:24:10,596
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it'd be really necessary.

1515
02:24:12,767 --> 02:24:16,851
[SPEAKER_09]: mean that our city can do, can have that pressure off of us.

1516
02:24:18,233 --> 02:24:20,215
[SPEAKER_09]: We all know how tight budgets are generally.

1517
02:24:21,516 --> 02:24:23,097
[SPEAKER_09]: And so I really hope the state delivers on that.

1518
02:24:24,579 --> 02:24:27,162
[SPEAKER_09]: Are we looking at using stabilization funds for it or?

1519
02:24:29,221 --> 02:24:39,572
[SPEAKER_25]: President Behrs, through you, I would, we would want to probably try to avoid using stabilization funds on it because of the nature of the stabilization fund, that it's capital stabilization fund.

1520
02:24:40,533 --> 02:24:42,935
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we could evaluate alternatives.

1521
02:24:43,055 --> 02:24:52,725
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we would be good for enough of a period of time where, you know, MFN shouldn't have to bridge anything before we have free cash certified again.

1522
02:24:53,245 --> 02:24:58,590
[SPEAKER_25]: So, you know, hopefully we're in, I don't see a scenario where that's an issue.

1523
02:24:58,630 --> 02:25:05,257
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, if that scenario were to present itself, we would work very diligently to try to figure out options.

1524
02:25:05,877 --> 02:25:08,039
[SPEAKER_25]: Maybe that means a general stabilization.

1525
02:25:08,540 --> 02:25:08,960
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't know.

1526
02:25:09,481 --> 02:25:10,422
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not entirely sure.

1527
02:25:10,462 --> 02:25:16,788
[SPEAKER_25]: It really hasn't been contemplated at that level, but I don't think the timing is such that we're going to run into that question, but if we do,

1528
02:25:17,449 --> 02:25:23,920
[SPEAKER_25]: We'll have that dialogue with the various people we need to discuss with the state, with this council, and we'll figure it out.

1529
02:25:23,980 --> 02:25:25,243
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm confident on that.

1530
02:25:25,830 --> 02:25:26,230
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

1531
02:25:26,711 --> 02:25:38,178
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm, you know, just wanted to, you know, ask that question so that we have, we know that we're thinking about these things, thinking about the worst case scenario, thinking about plans for doing it.

1532
02:25:38,439 --> 02:25:40,860
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm glad to hear that the timing will likely work out.

1533
02:25:41,721 --> 02:25:46,224
[SPEAKER_09]: And I do want to thank, through you, the mayor for her work on this as well.

1534
02:25:47,485 --> 02:25:48,666
[SPEAKER_09]: It really has been a team effort.

1535
02:25:49,286 --> 02:25:49,526
[SPEAKER_25]: Agreed.

1536
02:25:49,746 --> 02:25:52,808
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1537
02:25:52,828 --> 02:25:53,569
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Sang.

1538
02:25:53,589 --> 02:25:55,070
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further questions on the MFN?

1539
02:25:59,330 --> 02:26:02,631
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, any questions or discussion from members of the public on the MFN?

1540
02:26:05,872 --> 02:26:06,792
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, is there a motion?

1541
02:26:08,832 --> 02:26:11,853
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion to approve, I, Vice President Lazaro, seconded by Councilor Mullane.

1542
02:26:12,573 --> 02:26:13,433
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

1543
02:26:16,514 --> 02:26:17,234
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan?

1544
02:26:17,254 --> 02:26:17,414
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1545
02:26:19,255 --> 02:26:19,975
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lennon?

1546
02:26:20,695 --> 02:26:21,015
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes.

1547
02:26:22,396 --> 02:26:22,916
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Mullane?

1548
02:26:22,936 --> 02:26:22,996
Yes.

1549
02:26:24,536 --> 02:26:25,336
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scapelli?

1550
02:26:25,356 --> 02:26:25,416
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1551
02:26:26,957 --> 02:26:27,557
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Singh?

1552
02:26:28,973 --> 02:26:31,936
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro, President Paris.

1553
02:26:32,216 --> 02:26:34,498
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, I have an affirmative, none in the negative, the motion passes.

1554
02:26:34,518 --> 02:26:40,143
[SPEAKER_07]: 26112 submitted by Mayor Brianna Lugo-Kern, request for food truck permits, Tandor, Curry and Revelry.

1555
02:26:40,644 --> 02:26:50,613
[SPEAKER_07]: I believe we approved the June one but we were coming back to look at the July and August dates for the Medford Square Fest Brews, Bites and Beats events.

1556
02:26:52,875 --> 02:26:53,696
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Scarpelli.

1557
02:26:55,266 --> 02:27:14,738
[SPEAKER_21]: After talking with the brick and mortar owners that had some questions and the response that they are fine with this process, not fine with it, but they're accepting it, I would just move approval.

1558
02:27:15,639 --> 02:27:16,699
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Scarpelli.

1559
02:27:16,879 --> 02:27:19,681
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion to approve by Councilor Scarpelli, seconded by Vice President Lazaro.

1560
02:27:19,701 --> 02:27:20,602
