02:42:29,484 --> 02:42:30,304
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

1759
02:42:30,324 --> 02:42:31,205
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1760
02:42:31,245 --> 02:42:31,965
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Pierce?

1761
02:42:33,306 --> 02:42:33,586
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

1762
02:42:34,066 --> 02:42:35,227
[SPEAKER_07]: Seven in the affirmative, none in the negative.

1763
02:42:35,247 --> 02:42:37,288
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion passes.

1764
02:42:37,308 --> 02:42:42,891
[SPEAKER_07]: 26124, submitted by Mayor Brianna Lungo-Kern, Personnel Ordinance Amendments, Director and Assistant Director of Health and Human Services.

1765
02:42:44,013 --> 02:43:01,277
[SPEAKER_07]: Dear President Behrs and City Councilors, I respectfully request and recommend that your Honorable Body approve the following amendments to the revised ordinances, Chapter 66, Entitled Personnel, Article 2, Entitled Reserve, City's Classification and Compensation Plan, formally included as Article 2, Sections 6631 to 6640, by adopting the following changes effective July 1, 2026.

1766
02:43:01,537 --> 02:43:06,458
[SPEAKER_07]: Amendment A, in the language of CAF 12, shall be amended to remove Prevention and Outreach Manager.

1767
02:43:06,538 --> 02:43:10,819
[SPEAKER_07]: In the language of CAF 13, shall be amended to include the following position, Assistant Health and Human Services Director.

1768
02:43:11,319 --> 02:43:17,666
[SPEAKER_07]: Amendment B, the language of CAF 19, shall be amended to remove Director of Public Health and replace it with the following position, Director of Health and Human Services.

1769
02:43:17,686 --> 02:43:20,529
[SPEAKER_07]: Director of Public Health, Marianne O'Connor, will be available to speak on this request.

1770
02:43:20,589 --> 02:43:22,751
[SPEAKER_07]: Respectfully submitted, Brianna Lungo-Kern, Mayor.

1771
02:43:23,312 --> 02:43:25,074
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'll recognize Director O'Connor.

1772
02:43:31,773 --> 02:43:48,197
[SPEAKER_27]: Hi, good evening President Beers and members of the city council basically here tonight as a continuation of the discussion we had during my budget hearing when we talked about how the current name of the department no longer really reflects the scope of service you currently provide.

1773
02:43:48,937 --> 02:43:54,598
[SPEAKER_27]: And also to acknowledge the work of the current prevention and outreach manager, Catherine Dinkler.

1774
02:43:55,538 --> 02:43:58,140
[SPEAKER_27]: She's integral to the expansion of these services.

1775
02:43:58,280 --> 02:44:14,751
[SPEAKER_27]: The federal $1.2 million grant we received has secured our programming for years to come, but it also increases her job responsibilities in managing that grant and the programs and the staff and the reporting requirements associated with it.

1776
02:44:15,532 --> 02:44:23,397
[SPEAKER_27]: Also, I'm happy to report tonight that we recently were notified that we did receive the $70,000 grant from the Gaming Commission.

1777
02:44:24,099 --> 02:44:30,701
[SPEAKER_27]: Which will continue our problem gambling prevention work, which will also be under Catherine's purview.

1778
02:44:31,481 --> 02:44:34,822
[SPEAKER_27]: So, therefore, I'm asking tonight that you approve the requests.

1779
02:44:35,922 --> 02:44:37,742
[SPEAKER_27]: To include the changes to.

1780
02:44:39,003 --> 02:44:44,724
[SPEAKER_27]: Catherine and adding assistant health and human services director for Catherine's position.

1781
02:44:45,577 --> 02:44:52,698
[SPEAKER_27]: and changing my current position title under CAF 19 to Director of Health and Human Services.

1782
02:44:53,438 --> 02:44:55,139
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm happy to take any questions.

1783
02:44:59,699 --> 02:45:00,100
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1784
02:45:00,120 --> 02:45:01,940
[SPEAKER_07]: Do we have any questions for Director O'Connor?

1785
02:45:07,701 --> 02:45:08,741
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, is there a motion?

1786
02:45:08,761 --> 02:45:14,222
[SPEAKER_07]: Motion approved by Councilor Scarbelli, seconded by Vice President Lazaro.

1787
02:45:15,439 --> 02:45:16,640
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

1788
02:45:17,761 --> 02:45:18,562
[SPEAKER_07]: Approve for first reading.

1789
02:45:25,648 --> 02:45:26,328
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan?

1790
02:45:26,348 --> 02:45:27,569
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1791
02:45:27,589 --> 02:45:28,230
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming?

1792
02:45:28,830 --> 02:45:29,151
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1793
02:45:30,672 --> 02:45:31,192
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Malauulu?

1794
02:45:31,213 --> 02:45:31,273
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1795
02:45:32,373 --> 02:45:33,134
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scarpelli?

1796
02:45:33,154 --> 02:45:33,234
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1797
02:45:34,095 --> 02:45:34,715
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Singh?

1798
02:45:34,876 --> 02:45:35,676
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes.

1799
02:45:35,696 --> 02:45:36,437
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

1800
02:45:36,457 --> 02:45:36,557
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1801
02:45:37,998 --> 02:45:38,759
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Pierce?

1802
02:45:39,019 --> 02:45:39,219
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

1803
02:45:39,239 --> 02:45:40,380
[SPEAKER_07]: I have the affirmative and the negative.

1804
02:45:40,400 --> 02:45:41,181
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion passes.

1805
02:45:41,761 --> 02:45:42,702
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Director O'Connor.

1806
02:45:43,103 --> 02:45:43,423
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you.

1807
02:45:49,235 --> 02:45:50,876
[SPEAKER_07]: We did 26-125.

1808
02:45:53,417 --> 02:45:56,138
[SPEAKER_07]: So that moves us to the budget items.

1809
02:45:56,978 --> 02:45:57,898
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Sang.

1810
02:45:58,878 --> 02:46:02,320
[SPEAKER_09]: To take the supplemental amendments out of order.

1811
02:46:03,000 --> 02:46:07,201
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion by Councilor Sang to take paper 26-126, seconded by.

1812
02:46:08,662 --> 02:46:09,962
[SPEAKER_07]: Seconded by Councilor Scarpelli.

1813
02:46:09,982 --> 02:46:11,043
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

1814
02:46:17,405 --> 02:46:18,065
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan.

1815
02:46:22,140 --> 02:46:22,781
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming?

1816
02:46:23,641 --> 02:46:23,942
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1817
02:46:25,143 --> 02:46:25,603
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Millan?

1818
02:46:25,623 --> 02:46:25,703
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1819
02:46:26,824 --> 02:46:27,545
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scapelli?

1820
02:46:27,565 --> 02:46:27,665
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1821
02:46:28,626 --> 02:46:29,206
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Hussain?

1822
02:46:29,266 --> 02:46:29,487
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1823
02:46:30,187 --> 02:46:30,908
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

1824
02:46:30,928 --> 02:46:30,988
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

1825
02:46:31,769 --> 02:46:32,469
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Beers?

1826
02:46:32,950 --> 02:46:33,250
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

1827
02:46:33,550 --> 02:46:35,632
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm in the affirmative, none in the negative, the motion passes.

1828
02:46:35,792 --> 02:46:37,334
[SPEAKER_07]: Dear President Beers and City Councilors,

1829
02:46:38,125 --> 02:46:51,931
[SPEAKER_07]: As you know, pursuant to Mass General Law, Chapter 44, Section 32, our specular request to recommend the honorable body approve the proposed fiscal year 2027 general fund budget public educational and governmental access special revenue fund and water sewer enterprise fund.

1830
02:46:52,946 --> 02:47:04,018
[SPEAKER_07]: As outlined in my letter dated June 4th, 2026, which appears in the council's June 9th, 2026 regular meeting packet, as part of city council and mayor budget negotiations, this offer is conditioned upon the council approving the budget as proposed without any reductions.

1831
02:47:04,038 --> 02:47:12,967
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm also requesting and recommending that the following supplemental appropriations, the fiscal year 2027 general fund budget, and the total supplemental appropriation is $112,929.

1832
02:47:16,588 --> 02:47:20,321
[SPEAKER_07]: Outlined in the following table, 25,000 legislative salaries, 15,000 executive salaries, 5,000 executive ordinary.

1833
02:47:23,990 --> 02:47:27,132
[SPEAKER_07]: Law, 22,230 salaries.

1834
02:47:27,772 --> 02:47:30,074
[SPEAKER_07]: Recreation, 25,000 salaries.

1835
02:47:30,354 --> 02:47:33,116
[SPEAKER_07]: And library, 20,696 salaries.

1836
02:47:33,636 --> 02:47:41,060
[SPEAKER_07]: And to meet these appropriations, the sum of $112,926.00 be appraised and appropriated from the fiscal year 2027 tax levy.

1837
02:47:41,541 --> 02:47:48,485
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you for your kind attention in this matter and for negotiating a solid fiscal 27 budget that includes a number of key priorities important to both the council and me.

1838
02:47:48,525 --> 02:47:50,406
[SPEAKER_07]: Sincerely, Brianna Lingo-Kern, Mayor.

1839
02:47:52,417 --> 02:48:07,324
[SPEAKER_07]: And I believe that those are for the council to hire the city messenger slash legislative assistant position, the arts liaison position, as well as increase in funding to the arts council is the executive budget for the law budget.

1840
02:48:07,384 --> 02:48:18,170
[SPEAKER_07]: That is an increase in the solicitor salary so that we can hopefully finally hire a solicitor for recreation does 25 in salary funding to allow for director Bailey

1841
02:48:18,690 --> 02:48:21,832
[SPEAKER_07]: to address some of the turnover and needs in that office.

1842
02:48:22,392 --> 02:48:32,218
[SPEAKER_07]: And the library, $20,696, was to increase from a $2 an hour raise to a $4 an hour raise for some of the part-time folks at the library.

1843
02:48:35,220 --> 02:48:35,840
[SPEAKER_07]: Any discussion?

1844
02:48:35,940 --> 02:48:37,081
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Scarpelli.

1845
02:48:37,521 --> 02:48:39,602
[SPEAKER_21]: Just some clarity, Mr. President, if you can.

1846
02:48:40,743 --> 02:48:47,827
[SPEAKER_21]: The voting of this supplemental budget would allow us to accept what the mayor has offered

1847
02:48:48,741 --> 02:48:56,743
[SPEAKER_21]: and then leave the option open for a vote of the total budget.

1848
02:48:57,083 --> 02:48:57,643
[SPEAKER_21]: Is that correct?

1849
02:48:57,723 --> 02:49:09,986
[SPEAKER_21]: I don't want to, like I said, I think that my resolution speaks for itself as we move forward, but I would hate to not vote something in without understanding it before I move forward.

1850
02:49:10,026 --> 02:49:11,707
[SPEAKER_21]: Because again, these are the,

1851
02:49:13,441 --> 02:49:28,260
[SPEAKER_21]: These are the pieces that the mayor had requested that she's appropriated to the budget as part of the negotiation that we then do not cut certain other lines.

1852
02:49:29,562 --> 02:49:31,685
[SPEAKER_21]: But again, until we get that information,

1853
02:49:32,321 --> 02:49:56,446
[SPEAKER_21]: that we need, I think, would be prudent for us to make sure that we make the right decision on what's being asked right here, Mr. President, because if this is to move this along, and then if we go to the next step, which is a supplemental or a 112th budget, and we get the information that we want in one month, that this would allow everything to be implemented into the budget.

1854
02:49:56,646 --> 02:49:57,267
[SPEAKER_21]: I support it 1,000%.

1855
02:49:57,307 --> 02:49:57,967
[SPEAKER_21]: That's not my intent.

1856
02:49:59,671 --> 02:50:07,597
[SPEAKER_21]: My intent is to make sure that we get the information, and the only way to get that information is slow the process down until we get what we want.

1857
02:50:09,758 --> 02:50:15,482
[SPEAKER_21]: So if anybody can help answer that, that'd be helpful, Mr. President.

1858
02:50:15,963 --> 02:50:16,903
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Scrivelly.

1859
02:50:17,424 --> 02:50:22,667
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll just say for myself, and I do see a number of other councilors, I support these five items being funded.

1860
02:50:23,688 --> 02:50:29,232
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't accept the kind of whatever you want to call it,

1861
02:50:29,932 --> 02:50:37,276
[SPEAKER_07]: In my opinion, quid pro quo, we didn't really have a public negotiation.

1862
02:50:37,296 --> 02:50:41,018
[SPEAKER_07]: The mayor just said, if you don't cut anything, I'll fund these five things.

1863
02:50:41,118 --> 02:50:41,938
[SPEAKER_07]: The paper's before us.

1864
02:50:42,099 --> 02:50:43,239
[SPEAKER_07]: I support the five things.

1865
02:50:43,960 --> 02:50:48,222
[SPEAKER_07]: I personally don't believe that we should.

1866
02:50:49,760 --> 02:50:53,703
[SPEAKER_07]: give up the power to make targeted cuts in the next vote that we take.

1867
02:50:54,844 --> 02:50:57,445
[SPEAKER_07]: And so I would support these appropriations.

1868
02:50:58,886 --> 02:51:05,631
[SPEAKER_07]: And I would also probably support some proposals to make adjustments or cuts to the budget.

1869
02:51:06,372 --> 02:51:14,778
[SPEAKER_07]: And if the mayor chooses to decide that we don't fund the Arts Council or we don't fund the librarian raises or anything else, that's her choice.

1870
02:51:14,918 --> 02:51:16,379
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's my opinion on the matter.

1871
02:51:16,419 --> 02:51:18,160
[SPEAKER_07]: But that's just my singular opinion.

1872
02:51:19,117 --> 02:51:20,998
[SPEAKER_07]: And we do have the supplemental before us tonight.

1873
02:51:21,438 --> 02:51:21,778
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you.

1874
02:51:22,399 --> 02:51:24,299
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Sang and then Councilor Callahan.

1875
02:51:24,780 --> 02:51:25,180
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

1876
02:51:26,200 --> 02:51:38,886
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm going to vote yes on the supplemental and I want to say why because it's important for residents to see this as a statement of what our council has spent the last few months fighting for.

1877
02:51:41,207 --> 02:51:44,508
[SPEAKER_09]: I think we all remember that meeting when the librarians showed up.

1878
02:51:45,318 --> 02:51:53,565
[SPEAKER_09]: And not only did they show up in the city council chambers, they show up every day for our families here in Medford.

1879
02:51:54,886 --> 02:51:56,767
[SPEAKER_09]: Shelving books, they run programs.

1880
02:51:57,548 --> 02:51:59,890
[SPEAKER_09]: I think a lot of folks were at the fairytale ball.

1881
02:52:00,991 --> 02:52:03,232
[SPEAKER_09]: They answer questions in multiple languages.

1882
02:52:04,453 --> 02:52:12,820
[SPEAKER_09]: Yet at the same time, they make wages that don't reflect what that work is worth and what the city owes to people who do that work.

1883
02:52:15,383 --> 02:52:17,124
[SPEAKER_09]: And tonight, that starts to change.

1884
02:52:18,025 --> 02:52:23,449
[SPEAKER_09]: It's imperfect, but $4 an hour is better than the $2 an hour offer.

1885
02:52:24,910 --> 02:52:28,632
[SPEAKER_09]: And that is a win for the city council as well.

1886
02:52:28,973 --> 02:52:30,454
[SPEAKER_09]: It's a win for all residents of the city.

1887
02:52:31,394 --> 02:52:43,583
[SPEAKER_09]: Across the legislative, the executive recreation library budgets, I think these amendments reflect real investments in the people who run the city and the residents who depend on it.

1888
02:52:44,334 --> 02:52:55,977
[SPEAKER_09]: It would improve constituent services, improve investment in arts, create more accessibility and equity in recreation, among other changes.

1889
02:52:56,438 --> 02:53:02,339
[SPEAKER_09]: And it's easy to look at what we were presented with and see it as lines.

1890
02:53:02,459 --> 02:53:05,320
[SPEAKER_09]: But again, as I always say, these aren't line items.

1891
02:53:08,669 --> 02:53:10,410
[SPEAKER_09]: It's what a city government should be doing.

1892
02:53:10,650 --> 02:53:26,076
[SPEAKER_09]: It's the responsibilities of a city government that says it's going to do something and turns that plan into a budget, and the budget then in turn becomes the thing that exists in people's lives.

1893
02:53:28,553 --> 02:53:32,516
[SPEAKER_09]: Even though it's, you know, five items, it might not be as much as we wanted.

1894
02:53:32,976 --> 02:53:34,577
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not a small thing.

1895
02:53:34,637 --> 02:53:35,718
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's our job.

1896
02:53:35,918 --> 02:53:39,080
[SPEAKER_09]: It's the whole part of the reason why we're here as a council.

1897
02:53:40,121 --> 02:53:43,683
[SPEAKER_09]: But I do want to name something very plainly.

1898
02:53:45,745 --> 02:53:52,570
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's evident through the quote unquote negotiations that the funds for this existed before tonight.

1899
02:53:53,910 --> 02:53:57,053
[SPEAKER_09]: The money for the library wages, for constituent services, for arts,

1900
02:53:57,980 --> 02:54:01,141
[SPEAKER_09]: It was there, and it is there.

1901
02:54:03,261 --> 02:54:11,682
[SPEAKER_09]: What changed, I think, between the proposed budget and this offer wasn't the city's finances, it's that we started asking questions as a council.

1902
02:54:12,482 --> 02:54:21,324
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think too often the responses to those questions were, stop asking, we'll fund the things you care about in the future.

1903
02:54:22,764 --> 02:54:26,945
[SPEAKER_09]: And here's the hook, here's the kind of the quiproquo.

1904
02:54:27,738 --> 02:54:29,599
[SPEAKER_09]: keep asking questions and we won't fund it.

1905
02:54:30,880 --> 02:54:36,022
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think it's important to put on the record that that's not really a fiscal offer.

1906
02:54:36,583 --> 02:54:37,763
[SPEAKER_09]: It's a political transaction.

1907
02:54:38,383 --> 02:54:51,630
[SPEAKER_09]: It's one that asks our council to purchase services that Medford workers and families have already earned with a promise of silence about how our city spends our legal budget.

1908
02:54:54,578 --> 02:55:01,004
[SPEAKER_09]: I agree with the council president that that condition is unenforceable.

1909
02:55:02,805 --> 02:55:11,893
[SPEAKER_09]: Legally speaking, the condition that was contained in this transmittal letter is, I think, a political statement.

1910
02:55:12,073 --> 02:55:13,054
[SPEAKER_09]: It's a statement of policy.

1911
02:55:13,675 --> 02:55:15,957
[SPEAKER_09]: But it's not a legally binding statement.

1912
02:55:16,897 --> 02:55:19,420
[SPEAKER_09]: A transmittal letter, it's not an ordinance.

1913
02:55:19,620 --> 02:55:21,281
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not a money paper.

1914
02:55:22,967 --> 02:55:27,757
[SPEAKER_09]: what's, you know, the funds that we approve are, are, but that statement itself isn't.

1915
02:55:29,060 --> 02:55:31,265
[SPEAKER_09]: And furthermore, I think that statement itself.

1916
02:55:33,291 --> 02:55:35,712
[SPEAKER_09]: would be unenforceable because it being unconstitutional.

1917
02:55:35,812 --> 02:55:38,132
[SPEAKER_09]: It goes against the separation of powers in this city.

1918
02:55:38,172 --> 02:55:47,674
[SPEAKER_09]: It would go against Massachusetts state law, which allows us the power to make adjustments down from the, to reduce line items in the city budget.

1919
02:55:48,795 --> 02:55:55,236
[SPEAKER_09]: And it would reduce our oversight over that process and our ability to make those changes.

1920
02:55:57,436 --> 02:55:59,557
[SPEAKER_09]: Budgets are relatively simple in terms of

1921
02:56:00,553 --> 02:56:02,054
[SPEAKER_09]: the approval part of city council.

1922
02:56:02,114 --> 02:56:04,014
[SPEAKER_09]: You either approve, reject, or reduce.

1923
02:56:04,694 --> 02:56:08,756
[SPEAKER_09]: And adding conditions isn't contained in those options offered by state law.

1924
02:56:10,816 --> 02:56:12,717
[SPEAKER_09]: So I just wanna put that out there.

1925
02:56:13,057 --> 02:56:15,118
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm sure I have more to say about it later.

1926
02:56:16,478 --> 02:56:22,200
[SPEAKER_09]: But what's important to know again is the money exists.

1927
02:56:24,681 --> 02:56:26,221
[SPEAKER_09]: I would hope that this council approves it.

1928
02:56:28,569 --> 02:56:35,874
[SPEAKER_09]: If it's approved and we make changes to the budget, it's up to the mayor to see if she wants to try to enforce that condition.

1929
02:56:36,415 --> 02:56:46,822
[SPEAKER_09]: But these are real services that hardworking taxpayers, hardworking families have paid into, that workers are working for to keep running.

1930
02:56:47,242 --> 02:56:54,888
[SPEAKER_09]: And it becomes a political choice whether or not that exists or doesn't in a few weeks.

1931
02:56:59,452 --> 02:57:02,833
[SPEAKER_07]: I think Councillor Sang, Councillor Callahan.

1932
02:57:05,054 --> 02:57:05,294
[SPEAKER_14]: Thanks.

1933
02:57:05,414 --> 02:57:06,835
[SPEAKER_14]: So a couple of things.

1934
02:57:07,255 --> 02:57:12,597
[SPEAKER_14]: First, I did have a phone conversation with the mayor.

1935
02:57:12,637 --> 02:57:19,080
[SPEAKER_14]: This was way back, must have been around August timeframe when we were discussing zoning.

1936
02:57:19,580 --> 02:57:23,902
[SPEAKER_14]: And there was another sort of ultimatum that like,

1937
02:57:25,122 --> 02:57:34,268
[SPEAKER_14]: she would only allow zoning to move forward if we agreed to the exact things that she wanted on this particular zoning corner.

1938
02:57:34,289 --> 02:57:50,560
[SPEAKER_14]: And during that conversation, and it was a good conversation, I was quite clear that as a personality type, I do not appreciate being told do this or else.

1939
02:57:52,375 --> 02:57:53,680
[SPEAKER_14]: there will be some sort of punishment.

1940
02:57:53,760 --> 02:57:57,754
[SPEAKER_14]: And the punishment doesn't punish me, it punishes the whole city.

1941
02:58:00,277 --> 02:58:02,518
[SPEAKER_14]: that I will not react well to that.

1942
02:58:03,078 --> 02:58:04,838
[SPEAKER_14]: So I was quite clear.

1943
02:58:04,858 --> 02:58:08,179
[SPEAKER_14]: I see this in the same way.

1944
02:58:08,319 --> 02:58:24,782
[SPEAKER_14]: And in addition to sort of my own real resistance to this kind of, I would not call it negotiations, I think that is the term that is being used,

1945
02:58:26,269 --> 02:58:27,710
[SPEAKER_14]: You know, I would not call it that.

1946
02:58:27,870 --> 02:58:29,691
[SPEAKER_14]: I think this kind of ultimatum.

1947
02:58:31,392 --> 02:58:42,860
[SPEAKER_14]: In addition to that, I also want to point out that, you know, I think people often get frustrated with government, with people who they're, you know, folks who

1948
02:58:44,240 --> 02:58:49,124
[SPEAKER_14]: really hard for stuff, and then there are folks who will just beg for crumbs, right?

1949
02:58:49,144 --> 02:58:51,825
[SPEAKER_14]: That's like a phrase, people doing things for crumbs.

1950
02:58:51,985 --> 02:58:57,069
[SPEAKER_14]: And I want to point out that what this piece of paper is, is crumbs.

1951
02:58:58,430 --> 02:59:00,951
[SPEAKER_14]: So this is $113,000 out of a $200 million budget, and that is 0.05% of the budget.

1952
02:59:10,807 --> 02:59:14,492
[SPEAKER_14]: $25,000 of which is for a position, a paid position, and I want you to think about $25,000.

1953
02:59:14,532 --> 02:59:16,715
[SPEAKER_14]: $25,000 is for a paid position mandated by our new charter.

1954
02:59:16,735 --> 02:59:17,015
[SPEAKER_14]: In my opinion,

1955
02:59:28,885 --> 02:59:32,107
[SPEAKER_14]: $25,000 does not cover a paid position mandated by the charter.

1956
02:59:32,587 --> 02:59:40,250
[SPEAKER_14]: But we as a city council, we're willing to put this forward because we understand that we are not a city that has a ton of money.

1957
02:59:41,031 --> 02:59:45,333
[SPEAKER_14]: So we were willing to ask for crumbs.

1958
02:59:46,553 --> 02:59:47,994
[SPEAKER_14]: We were willing to accept that.

1959
02:59:48,734 --> 02:59:53,897
[SPEAKER_14]: I almost regret that we were willing to do that, that we bent over backwards to

1960
02:59:55,426 --> 03:00:04,254
[SPEAKER_14]: accept a $25,000 for a role that is mandated by the Charter and that we need in order to do the business of the City Council.

1961
03:00:05,015 --> 03:00:14,084
[SPEAKER_14]: The $20,000 for the library is because we are the only city around that pays their non-union part-time staff

1962
03:00:15,685 --> 03:00:21,626
[SPEAKER_14]: far far below what they pay their union staff and far below what any other city surrounding city pays.

1963
03:00:23,007 --> 03:00:27,128
[SPEAKER_14]: It is disgraceful what we pay the part time library employees.

1964
03:00:31,489 --> 03:00:44,892
[SPEAKER_14]: I am genuinely as you can tell I'm a little worked up about how we are being told that

1965
03:00:45,788 --> 03:01:02,554
[SPEAKER_14]: The only way that the mayor will punish the librarians and go against the city charter, as well as not funding other, you know, the arts, like $5,000 for the arts.

1966
03:01:03,534 --> 03:01:07,416
[SPEAKER_14]: Wow, that's the smallest crumb on this page.

1967
03:01:08,976 --> 03:01:10,917
[SPEAKER_14]: That these people will be punished.

1968
03:01:11,891 --> 03:01:20,217
[SPEAKER_14]: because we have the audacity to ask for information about where the money for lawsuits is going in this city.

1969
03:01:22,616 --> 03:01:34,602
[SPEAKER_14]: So I will definitely not vote for this if it includes the phrase which I read for you right now, this offer, offer, this is an offer.

1970
03:01:35,322 --> 03:01:41,125
[SPEAKER_14]: This offer is conditioned upon the council approving the budget as proposed without any reductions.

1971
03:01:42,105 --> 03:01:51,407
[SPEAKER_14]: Reductions is, by law, the only thing that any city council in Massachusetts is allowed to do to a budget.

1972
03:01:52,007 --> 03:01:53,848
[SPEAKER_14]: It is the only statement we can make.

1973
03:01:54,968 --> 03:01:55,768
[SPEAKER_14]: The only one.

1974
03:01:57,488 --> 03:01:59,849
[SPEAKER_14]: So we are supposed to accept 0.05%

1975
03:02:05,242 --> 03:02:23,730
[SPEAKER_14]: of the budget that already existed, that includes something mandated by the city charter, we are supposed to accept that and agree to not do our jobs, to not do our duty, to give up that right for this city.

1976
03:02:25,707 --> 03:02:37,974
[SPEAKER_14]: And I will not do that, but I will vote in favor of this with the amendment that it removes the phrase this offer is conditioned upon the council approving the budget as proposed without any reductions.

1977
03:02:40,476 --> 03:02:41,256
[SPEAKER_07]: I can do you one better.

1978
03:02:42,237 --> 03:02:43,777
[SPEAKER_07]: We can vote to approve this paper.

1979
03:02:43,877 --> 03:02:51,702
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think we can amend the mayor's papers, but we can vote to approve this paper and then if people want to make reductions, we can make reductions and we can just like not get blackmailed.

1980
03:02:56,546 --> 03:02:57,848
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you, Mr. President.

1981
03:03:01,253 --> 03:03:05,199
[SPEAKER_21]: Technically, would we be cutting if we go to a 112th budget?

1982
03:03:06,903 --> 03:03:08,024
[SPEAKER_21]: All that would be is delaying.

1983
03:03:08,464 --> 03:03:09,164
[SPEAKER_21]: It wouldn't be cutting.

1984
03:03:10,005 --> 03:03:11,746
[SPEAKER_21]: So that would still leave this in place.

1985
03:03:11,806 --> 03:03:16,448
[SPEAKER_21]: I can't believe we're even talking about it, because my colleagues are right.

1986
03:03:17,348 --> 03:03:27,254
[SPEAKER_21]: Imagine cutting something that we feel that is a necessity, but then the mayor saying, well, I'm going to cut the $25,000 for inclusionary programming for recreation.

1987
03:03:27,514 --> 03:03:27,854
[SPEAKER_21]: Good luck.

1988
03:03:30,455 --> 03:03:30,775
[SPEAKER_21]: Good luck.

1989
03:03:31,876 --> 03:03:33,497
[SPEAKER_21]: So I don't know, Mr. President.

1990
03:03:34,583 --> 03:03:39,124
[SPEAKER_21]: I just want to make sure that we vote in the supplemental budget through.

1991
03:03:39,164 --> 03:03:40,745
[SPEAKER_21]: We all agree this is in place.

1992
03:03:41,465 --> 03:03:58,609
[SPEAKER_21]: Whatever we decide on the regular budget, whether we cut, whether we do a 112 budget, I think that, I don't want to use Councilor Callahan's crumb statement, but minimal, at least we

1993
03:04:00,931 --> 03:04:01,912
[SPEAKER_21]: make a few people happy.

1994
03:04:01,932 --> 03:04:05,014
[SPEAKER_21]: And it's sad because we all see the emails, right?

1995
03:04:05,535 --> 03:04:10,299
[SPEAKER_21]: From the librarians and the art community, please help.

1996
03:04:10,359 --> 03:04:15,583
[SPEAKER_21]: It's like, it shouldn't be that way, but I guess that's where we are.

1997
03:04:15,823 --> 03:04:16,844
[SPEAKER_21]: So thank you, Mr. President.

1998
03:04:18,745 --> 03:04:19,406
[SPEAKER_21]: Move forward then.

1999
03:04:20,126 --> 03:04:20,507
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

2000
03:04:20,527 --> 03:04:25,911
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, I mean, before us, there's a $112,926 appropriation.

2001
03:04:31,673 --> 03:04:32,773
[SPEAKER_07]: Then we'll take a vote on the budget.

2002
03:04:33,413 --> 03:04:36,234
[SPEAKER_07]: If there's reductions to the budget, we've approved this appropriation.

2003
03:04:36,294 --> 03:04:46,878
[SPEAKER_07]: If the mayor doesn't want to spend it and the people who have interest in these funds being expended, we can direct them to, you know, we approved it.

2004
03:04:47,718 --> 03:04:48,419
[SPEAKER_07]: That's all I'm saying here.

2005
03:04:50,439 --> 03:04:52,660
[SPEAKER_07]: On a motion to approve by Councilor Scarpelli, seconded by?

2006
03:04:53,440 --> 03:04:54,961
[SPEAKER_07]: Seconded by Vice President Lazaro.

2007
03:04:56,381 --> 03:04:57,722
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further discussion by members of the council?

2008
03:04:58,953 --> 03:05:01,094
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, I do see a member of the public.

2009
03:05:01,715 --> 03:05:05,938
[SPEAKER_07]: If you could provide your name and city for the record and you'll have three minutes.

2010
03:05:07,399 --> 03:05:08,980
[SPEAKER_05]: Simon Elsendorf, Medford.

2011
03:05:09,800 --> 03:05:17,826
[SPEAKER_05]: I just want to come up here again because once again, it seems as if this mayoral administration is attempting to make quid pro quos.

2012
03:05:18,386 --> 03:05:22,909
[SPEAKER_05]: In this case, they are not only like we're again going back to the thing of

2013
03:05:23,733 --> 03:05:32,840
[SPEAKER_05]: the mayoral administration trying to go against what our elected body is attempting to do in order to get what she wants.

2014
03:05:32,940 --> 03:05:34,601
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, let me put it this way.

2015
03:05:34,641 --> 03:05:39,064
[SPEAKER_05]: A quid pro quo should not be three words that I'm hearing in a city council meeting in the year of our Lord 2026.

2016
03:05:39,345 --> 03:05:41,326
[SPEAKER_05]: This is not the 70s.

2017
03:05:41,646 --> 03:05:43,167
[SPEAKER_05]: We are not being run by the mafia.

2018
03:05:44,008 --> 03:05:46,330
[SPEAKER_05]: Act like it, okay?

2019
03:05:47,745 --> 03:05:53,048
[SPEAKER_05]: I, like, this is, just, excuse my language, this is fucking insane, just as a baseline.

2020
03:05:53,068 --> 03:05:54,309
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, we can't say that.

2021
03:05:54,489 --> 03:05:55,490
[SPEAKER_07]: Can't say that on the meeting.

2022
03:05:55,510 --> 03:05:56,690
[SPEAKER_07]: I said excuse my language.

2023
03:05:56,750 --> 03:05:58,532
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, you still can't say it.

2024
03:05:58,792 --> 03:06:00,513
[SPEAKER_07]: There's like a lot of other words that we can say.

2025
03:06:01,073 --> 03:06:07,537
[SPEAKER_05]: But, just straight up, this is not something that we should be doing.

2026
03:06:07,817 --> 03:06:14,621
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm just here to very strongly condemn the fact that the mayor is currently trying to offer quid pro quos to the council.

2027
03:06:14,961 --> 03:06:15,662
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much.

2028
03:06:17,278 --> 03:06:17,878
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

2029
03:06:18,138 --> 03:06:19,839
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing no hands on Zoom, we'll stay at the podium.

2030
03:06:20,580 --> 03:06:22,361
[SPEAKER_07]: Name and address for the record, and you'll have three minutes.

2031
03:06:22,761 --> 03:06:24,121
[SPEAKER_04]: Michael Gessman, 499 Main Street.

2032
03:06:25,082 --> 03:06:27,723
[SPEAKER_04]: I actually encourage you to vote against this.

2033
03:06:30,465 --> 03:06:37,468
[SPEAKER_04]: As has been stated already, none of these line items make any difference.

2034
03:06:38,549 --> 03:06:44,852
[SPEAKER_04]: This is not gonna affect anything, and all it's gonna do is feed into this

2035
03:06:45,682 --> 03:06:59,196
[SPEAKER_04]: wild, absolutely unprofessional, petty, pathetic, and childish view of the office that the mayor holds that it is a transactional process.

2036
03:06:59,836 --> 03:07:01,378
[SPEAKER_04]: You are not negotiating.

2037
03:07:02,688 --> 03:07:06,009
[SPEAKER_04]: Like this is not, you don't negotiate our city budget.

2038
03:07:06,309 --> 03:07:11,051
[SPEAKER_04]: You don't negotiate the services that we have, that we provide to residents.

2039
03:07:11,691 --> 03:07:15,872
[SPEAKER_04]: You determine what the needs are and you fill them and you fund them.

2040
03:07:16,392 --> 03:07:17,732
[SPEAKER_04]: Like that's not a negotiation.

2041
03:07:18,113 --> 03:07:19,933
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not a transaction.

2042
03:07:20,293 --> 03:07:21,534
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not adversarial.

2043
03:07:22,114 --> 03:07:26,035
[SPEAKER_04]: It is a collaborative process to serve your community.

2044
03:07:27,553 --> 03:07:29,894
[SPEAKER_04]: And I mean, that goes as much for you guys as it does for the mayor.

2045
03:07:29,994 --> 03:07:32,334
[SPEAKER_04]: But like, it's just like, this is just crazy.

2046
03:07:33,275 --> 03:07:34,915
[SPEAKER_04]: The idea of like, I offer you this.

2047
03:07:35,735 --> 03:07:37,136
[SPEAKER_04]: Who is this being offered to?

2048
03:07:37,836 --> 03:07:38,976
[SPEAKER_04]: Because you're not getting the money.

2049
03:07:39,596 --> 03:07:41,697
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not being offered to you as counselors.

2050
03:07:41,737 --> 03:07:43,258
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not going into your bank accounts.

2051
03:07:44,038 --> 03:07:51,620
[SPEAKER_04]: Is she offering the city of Medford to fund the services that she agrees that we need and deserve and should be funded?

2052
03:07:52,360 --> 03:07:54,002
[SPEAKER_04]: What the hell is she talking about?

2053
03:07:54,482 --> 03:07:55,343
[SPEAKER_04]: This is crazy.

2054
03:07:55,783 --> 03:07:58,005
[SPEAKER_04]: So I don't think you should feed into this nonsense.

2055
03:07:58,125 --> 03:08:02,528
[SPEAKER_04]: It's complete garbage and I don't think that these line items are gonna make any difference anyway.

2056
03:08:03,028 --> 03:08:04,449
[SPEAKER_04]: So why put up with it?

2057
03:08:04,750 --> 03:08:09,253
[SPEAKER_04]: Say no, and we're still gonna do what we can do to the budget because that's the job.

2058
03:08:09,813 --> 03:08:10,894
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not a negotiation.

2059
03:08:11,895 --> 03:08:15,237
[SPEAKER_04]: Like if you wanted to do negotiations, go back into private practice.

2060
03:08:15,538 --> 03:08:16,819
[SPEAKER_04]: Go back to real estate law.

2061
03:08:17,119 --> 03:08:18,340
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm sure you'd be great at it.

2062
03:08:20,830 --> 03:08:23,292
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, seeing no hands on Zoom, we'll stay at the podium.

2063
03:08:24,513 --> 03:08:26,114
[SPEAKER_07]: Name and city for the record, you have three minutes.

2064
03:08:27,035 --> 03:08:28,916
[SPEAKER_01]: Barry Ingber, 9 Draper Street.

2065
03:08:31,598 --> 03:08:36,882
[SPEAKER_01]: Mr. President, I'd like to agree with the previous two speakers and with Councilor Callahan.

2066
03:08:37,683 --> 03:08:45,889
[SPEAKER_01]: I actually think that you should table this resolution rather than voting it either up or down.

2067
03:08:46,470 --> 03:08:49,272
[SPEAKER_01]: Just table it until you actually vote on the budget.

2068
03:08:50,907 --> 03:09:00,213
[SPEAKER_01]: What the mayor is saying here is that she has the money to fund these programs, because she's offering it to you to fund.

2069
03:09:02,015 --> 03:09:07,378
[SPEAKER_01]: If you cut the budget, you have even more money to fund these programs, but she's not going to fund the programs.

2070
03:09:08,259 --> 03:09:08,879
[SPEAKER_01]: I dare her.

2071
03:09:10,440 --> 03:09:15,223
[SPEAKER_01]: I dare her to say, I can afford these programs, but I am not going to fund them.

2072
03:09:16,105 --> 03:09:21,708
[SPEAKER_01]: It's bold coercion, and it's an attempt to take away the only power that this council really has.

2073
03:09:21,728 --> 03:09:24,949
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

2074
03:09:29,491 --> 03:09:30,292
[SPEAKER_07]: Vice President Lazaro.

2075
03:09:32,052 --> 03:09:32,513
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

2076
03:09:33,253 --> 03:09:36,554
[SPEAKER_13]: Respectfully, this is funding programs.

2077
03:09:36,594 --> 03:09:39,096
[SPEAKER_13]: We've already done the work of getting these

2078
03:09:40,202 --> 03:09:41,083
[SPEAKER_13]: on the agenda.

2079
03:09:42,184 --> 03:09:44,426
[SPEAKER_13]: Of course it's not the way we would have wanted to.

2080
03:09:44,786 --> 03:09:46,027
[SPEAKER_13]: And of course it's not enough.

2081
03:09:47,849 --> 03:09:57,197
[SPEAKER_13]: My biggest concern this term was to pay the library employees a competitive wage.

2082
03:09:58,078 --> 03:10:05,004
[SPEAKER_13]: We haven't achieved that but we've at least gotten to the minimum amount that the library staff requested.

2083
03:10:07,844 --> 03:10:15,993
[SPEAKER_13]: And that is something that the trustees of the library were very excited to hear about when I told them that that was a possibility.

2084
03:10:16,413 --> 03:10:28,486
[SPEAKER_13]: Now if we said no, it's the principle, so we're going to take the thing that we achieved after months and months of these late meetings, and we said actually,

2085
03:10:29,251 --> 03:10:31,413
[SPEAKER_13]: on principle, we're not going to do it.

2086
03:10:31,793 --> 03:10:32,513
[SPEAKER_13]: That's not going to work.

2087
03:10:33,134 --> 03:10:34,755
[SPEAKER_13]: Why did we, no, we're not going to do that.

2088
03:10:35,075 --> 03:10:37,077
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm not going to do that, respectfully.

2089
03:10:37,197 --> 03:10:43,841
[SPEAKER_13]: So I think that we should vote this through and move on to the next item.

2090
03:10:44,002 --> 03:10:46,804
[SPEAKER_13]: But also I am very tired.

2091
03:10:47,064 --> 03:10:54,469
[SPEAKER_13]: So after this paper, I am going to go home and I will finish this meeting on Zoom because otherwise I might die.

2092
03:10:55,150 --> 03:10:55,450
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

2093
03:10:56,984 --> 03:11:00,068
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm just going to say very quickly that I actually don't think any of us are in disagreement.

2094
03:11:00,189 --> 03:11:10,163
[SPEAKER_07]: What I'm saying is we can approve this supplemental appropriation because the only thing that's on the agenda is a supplemental appropriation, and then we can vote the budget down, we can vote the budget up, we can cut the budget.

2095
03:11:12,357 --> 03:11:14,077
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm just not accepting the coercion.

2096
03:11:14,958 --> 03:11:16,398
[SPEAKER_07]: Like, just deny the coercion.

2097
03:11:16,778 --> 03:11:18,278
[SPEAKER_07]: There's an appropriation before us.

2098
03:11:19,139 --> 03:11:21,039
[SPEAKER_07]: I support the items being appropriated.

2099
03:11:21,059 --> 03:11:24,860
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't support those being, like, traded for something else.

2100
03:11:25,500 --> 03:11:27,000
[SPEAKER_07]: So we don't make a trade.

2101
03:11:27,361 --> 03:11:30,981
[SPEAKER_07]: And then if they don't get funded, we approve them.

2102
03:11:31,221 --> 03:11:32,382
[SPEAKER_07]: That's just all I'm saying.

2103
03:11:34,844 --> 03:11:35,324
[SPEAKER_03]: I agree.

2104
03:11:35,344 --> 03:11:47,833
[SPEAKER_03]: President Behrs and Vice President Lozaro, I mean, it's $112,000 that we're talking about, and these are critical pieces that we've had these conversations with.

2105
03:11:47,973 --> 03:11:54,218
[SPEAKER_03]: I am not going to vote down, especially when I've spoken to various members of the library around

2106
03:11:54,738 --> 03:11:56,319
[SPEAKER_03]: this increase for their funding.

2107
03:11:56,399 --> 03:12:09,863
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm hopeful, maybe naive, but hopeful that because we've gone through all of this process and we have said yes to these things, that this can be still approved regardless of what happens next.

2108
03:12:09,943 --> 03:12:19,727
[SPEAKER_03]: But for, again, $112,000 that we're having, I'm really hopeful that we're able to approve this and get this money funded.

2109
03:12:21,387 --> 03:12:21,707
[SPEAKER_07]: That's it.

2110
03:12:22,127 --> 03:12:22,968
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilman Layton.

2111
03:12:24,417 --> 03:12:25,197
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there a motion?

2112
03:12:25,217 --> 03:12:28,439
[SPEAKER_07]: Who's it by?

2113
03:12:33,520 --> 03:12:34,761
[SPEAKER_07]: Make motions at the end, please.

2114
03:12:34,841 --> 03:12:35,341
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't remember.

2115
03:12:39,062 --> 03:12:42,364
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion to approve by Councilor Scarpelli, seconded by Vice President Lazaro.

2116
03:12:42,464 --> 03:12:43,464
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

2117
03:12:45,605 --> 03:12:46,305
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan?

2118
03:12:46,325 --> 03:12:46,385
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2119
03:12:48,126 --> 03:12:48,786
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming?

2120
03:12:49,346 --> 03:12:49,666
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2121
03:12:51,367 --> 03:12:51,907
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Malay?

2122
03:12:51,927 --> 03:12:52,007
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2123
03:12:53,208 --> 03:12:54,088
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scarpelli?

2124
03:12:55,595 --> 03:12:56,215
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Singh?

2125
03:12:56,295 --> 03:12:56,475
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2126
03:12:57,616 --> 03:12:58,376
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

2127
03:12:58,396 --> 03:12:58,456
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2128
03:12:59,437 --> 03:13:00,037
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Beers?

2129
03:13:00,197 --> 03:13:00,477
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

2130
03:13:00,537 --> 03:13:01,538
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm in the affirmative, none the negative.

2131
03:13:01,558 --> 03:13:03,339
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion passes.

2132
03:13:03,359 --> 03:13:07,801
[SPEAKER_07]: 26061 submitted by Mayor Brianna Lugo-Curran, fiscal year 2027, budget submission revised.

2133
03:13:08,861 --> 03:13:15,945
[SPEAKER_07]: Dear President Beers and City Councilors, pursuant to Chiles and $904.68, thank you for your kind attention to this matter.

2134
03:13:16,425 --> 03:13:17,886
[SPEAKER_07]: Sincerely, Brianna Lugo-Curran, Mayor.

2135
03:13:18,446 --> 03:13:22,668
[SPEAKER_07]: I do believe this contained some, I believe,

2136
03:13:23,425 --> 03:13:26,846
[SPEAKER_07]: just like technical edits to some of the figures within the table.

2137
03:13:26,906 --> 03:13:37,208
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know if Director Dickinson or Chief of Staff Nazarian, you want to speak to any of them, but I also believe that the total amount for all of the funds has remained the same.

2138
03:13:37,228 --> 03:13:43,970
[SPEAKER_07]: And then I do see questions from members of the council.

2139
03:13:52,475 --> 03:13:53,275
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, President Behrs.

2140
03:13:53,896 --> 03:14:03,102
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes, in brief, the changes to the paper are effectively, you know, not material.

2141
03:14:03,842 --> 03:14:08,445
[SPEAKER_25]: They were a scrivener's error and a minor adjustment that got overlooked.

2142
03:14:09,986 --> 03:14:10,266
[SPEAKER_07]: Great.

2143
03:14:10,926 --> 03:14:11,367
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

2144
03:14:11,387 --> 03:14:14,128
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

2145
03:14:14,229 --> 03:14:17,190
[SPEAKER_07]: I will go to Councilor Scarpelli and then Councilor Sank.

2146
03:14:17,210 --> 03:14:17,931
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Scarpelli.

2147
03:14:18,271 --> 03:14:19,272
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you, Mr. President.

2148
03:14:20,338 --> 03:14:36,086
[SPEAKER_21]: I think this is time we can look at the budget in totality and look to see what budget cuts we would like and then at the same time also vote on a 112th budget.

2149
03:14:36,506 --> 03:14:47,792
[SPEAKER_21]: I think that to sit here tonight and hear the administration tell us to our faces that they cannot provide the information that we need.

2150
03:14:48,553 --> 03:14:51,834
[SPEAKER_21]: But we can look at the papers that were sent to us today, everyone.

2151
03:14:53,435 --> 03:14:58,818
[SPEAKER_21]: We can look at a snow and ice deficit in an appropriation of $1,355,311.55 to the cent, right?

2152
03:14:58,858 --> 03:15:05,761
[SPEAKER_21]: You can give us the breakdown for all of the contracted services and all the fees and all of the extras that we needed for snow removal.

2153
03:15:18,516 --> 03:15:28,941
[SPEAKER_21]: We can find that to the penny to replenish our capital stabilization fund of 7447658.04.

2154
03:15:29,461 --> 03:15:30,822
[SPEAKER_21]: We can do that to the penny.

2155
03:15:32,042 --> 03:15:47,109
[SPEAKER_21]: But the administration can sit here in front of everybody and say, we don't have an avenue to get a breakdown of what our taxpayers are paying in legal lawsuits.

2156
03:15:49,276 --> 03:16:14,730
[SPEAKER_21]: I think that this council should really take notice that the only leverage we have to get this information is to vote the 1-12 budget, make the cuts that you see fit, but vote the 1-12 budget so nobody gets, no one's hurt, everybody still gets paid from the same schedule of our FY25 budget

2157
03:16:17,839 --> 03:16:28,307
[SPEAKER_21]: for up to three months or as long as it takes to find these numbers that are hiding somewhere, that can't be found.

2158
03:16:30,990 --> 03:16:46,542
[SPEAKER_21]: Because I will tell you publicly, if we don't do that, and we don't do a 112th budget, we will not get the answers that we need that taxpayers have now come forth to us since this has been put forth.

2159
03:16:48,555 --> 03:16:50,696
[SPEAKER_21]: Now, politically, put it all aside.

2160
03:16:52,757 --> 03:16:55,938
[SPEAKER_21]: The average person is seeing and hearing what's happening, and they want answers.

2161
03:16:57,319 --> 03:17:06,863
[SPEAKER_21]: We heard tonight from our administration and our financial team that it's impossible to get a breakdown of our legal fees.

2162
03:17:06,923 --> 03:17:07,443
[SPEAKER_21]: Impossible.

2163
03:17:11,805 --> 03:17:17,948
[SPEAKER_21]: I think that is enough information this council needs to say our jobs and our duties

2164
03:17:18,933 --> 03:17:30,484
[SPEAKER_21]: are to call for a 112 budget, chapter 44, section 32, move forward with at least three months to get that information.

2165
03:17:31,425 --> 03:17:35,049
[SPEAKER_21]: So then we can move forward with what we have been working so hard for.

2166
03:17:37,572 --> 03:17:52,120
[SPEAKER_21]: So, Mr. President, I would put this as a B paper or as a motion and move forward with any other options that the council wishes.

2167
03:17:52,220 --> 03:17:56,602
[SPEAKER_21]: But I think we're in a very unique situation.

2168
03:17:57,083 --> 03:17:57,983
[SPEAKER_21]: This hasn't happened.

2169
03:17:59,604 --> 03:18:04,927
[SPEAKER_21]: But how do we wake up tomorrow morning if this passes?

2170
03:18:06,080 --> 03:18:11,321
[SPEAKER_21]: and say that we have faith in our administration to get us these numbers if this budget is passed.

2171
03:18:13,462 --> 03:18:16,402
[SPEAKER_21]: So I respect all of you.

2172
03:18:16,462 --> 03:18:28,164
[SPEAKER_21]: I think we've gone a long way, but I think this is something that we've seen in the past, and we've been asking.

2173
03:18:28,705 --> 03:18:29,185
[SPEAKER_21]: This isn't $15,000.

2174
03:18:30,465 --> 03:18:32,645
[SPEAKER_21]: This isn't $112,000 that we're questioning.

2175
03:18:37,159 --> 03:18:38,180
[SPEAKER_21]: This is a lot of money.

2176
03:18:38,800 --> 03:18:43,123
[SPEAKER_21]: So thank you for listening, Mr. President.

2177
03:18:43,503 --> 03:18:51,728
[SPEAKER_21]: I know that I'm being redundant, but I think we need to move as a council with some authority and some strength.

2178
03:18:52,188 --> 03:18:52,688
[SPEAKER_21]: So thank you.

2179
03:18:53,509 --> 03:18:54,770
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Scarpelli.

2180
03:18:57,611 --> 03:19:04,276
[SPEAKER_07]: So we have a B paper to move to a 112th budget.

2181
03:19:07,922 --> 03:19:11,764
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know if you guys want to speak to that before I recognize Councilor Sang.

2182
03:19:16,067 --> 03:19:21,350
[SPEAKER_25]: I mean, I would say it's my hope that the council wouldn't vote a 112th budget this evening.

2183
03:19:21,931 --> 03:19:24,152
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm sure that doesn't come to you as a surprise.

2184
03:19:24,232 --> 03:19:28,495
[SPEAKER_25]: There would be a significant amount of resources drawn on the city.

2185
03:19:29,275 --> 03:19:36,500
[SPEAKER_25]: I'd prefer to put those resources toward responding further to public records requests in general that we have.

2186
03:19:37,160 --> 03:19:39,622
[SPEAKER_25]: to work that the finance department wants to do.

2187
03:19:39,642 --> 03:19:45,706
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not saying that, let me back up, and I'm not saying that that excludes the records that the council has requested.

2188
03:19:45,726 --> 03:19:51,190
[SPEAKER_25]: I think there has been some characterizations that have been made here tonight.

2189
03:19:51,230 --> 03:19:57,294
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not gonna correct them at this stage because I'm hopeful that we can proceed forward, but I

2190
03:19:57,794 --> 03:20:02,115
[SPEAKER_25]: to continue on what I was about to say, that would draw away from resources in all of our departments.

2191
03:20:02,735 --> 03:20:07,436
[SPEAKER_25]: It would significantly draw on resources in our finance department, and our finance director can speak to that.

2192
03:20:08,576 --> 03:20:20,939
[SPEAKER_25]: It would draw attention and resources away from our ability to take the lengthy and arduous journey of transitioning to a new financial software.

2193
03:20:21,079 --> 03:20:23,360
[SPEAKER_25]: As you all know, that's going to take several years.

2194
03:20:25,040 --> 03:20:29,384
[SPEAKER_25]: So that's all I have to say at this stage.

2195
03:20:31,306 --> 03:20:35,330
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't want to go down a path I don't hopefully have to.

2196
03:20:35,350 --> 03:20:39,293
[SPEAKER_25]: I respect the feelings of this council.

2197
03:20:39,353 --> 03:20:41,876
[SPEAKER_25]: I respect the sentiment of the council.

2198
03:20:46,910 --> 03:20:53,053
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't have any issues and I don't think the mayor has any issues providing information to this council.

2199
03:20:53,093 --> 03:20:55,534
[SPEAKER_25]: We have been trying to do that in good faith.

2200
03:20:56,095 --> 03:21:02,318
[SPEAKER_25]: The mayor feels she's negotiated in good faith for several weeks to adhere to the council's priorities.

2201
03:21:03,158 --> 03:21:06,200
[SPEAKER_25]: I'll pause there and I defer to...

2202
03:21:11,223 --> 03:21:16,145
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there anything, can I just, Director Dickinson and then I'll recognize you, George, Bob.

2203
03:21:16,646 --> 03:21:24,229
[SPEAKER_18]: Just operationally to, I've never been in a situation where I did not have a budget.

2204
03:21:24,569 --> 03:21:36,315
[SPEAKER_18]: So to do a 112th budget means that, I mean, for my, for example, my department it's not very difficult to do a monthly budget because you're basically talking our salaries.

2205
03:21:37,055 --> 03:21:40,537
[SPEAKER_18]: When you're talking the DPW facilities,

2206
03:21:42,930 --> 03:21:45,372
[SPEAKER_18]: making sure we have enough money for each month.

2207
03:21:46,232 --> 03:21:50,015
[SPEAKER_18]: I mean, for instance, Treasury has to pay debt service.

2208
03:21:50,035 --> 03:21:55,098
[SPEAKER_18]: I've got to issue $25 million worth of bonds in August.

2209
03:21:57,039 --> 03:22:06,004
[SPEAKER_18]: I have to make sure that I have the resources available to do that, so that needs to be calculated for every month for every department.

2210
03:22:06,144 --> 03:22:07,425
[SPEAKER_18]: It's just an awful lot of work.

2211
03:22:08,417 --> 03:22:19,286
[SPEAKER_18]: I'd have to really look at exactly what we have to do and how to quarterback this, you know.

2212
03:22:20,267 --> 03:22:31,456
[SPEAKER_18]: So I'd really appreciate it if we could work on the council's needs some other way than to basically, you know,

2213
03:22:34,046 --> 03:22:35,787
[SPEAKER_18]: grind things to a halt at the city.

2214
03:22:35,847 --> 03:22:37,508
[SPEAKER_18]: We need to do things.

2215
03:22:37,888 --> 03:22:42,069
[SPEAKER_18]: We need to, you know, we need to close the fiscal year.

2216
03:22:42,109 --> 03:22:48,952
[SPEAKER_18]: We need to have lifeguards at the pools.

2217
03:22:49,052 --> 03:22:51,514
[SPEAKER_18]: We need the recreation department to have its money.

2218
03:22:52,294 --> 03:22:52,954
[SPEAKER_18]: It can be done.

2219
03:22:53,054 --> 03:22:56,115
[SPEAKER_18]: It's just an awful lot of extra work, so.

2220
03:22:57,836 --> 03:22:58,176
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

2221
03:22:58,336 --> 03:22:59,797
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Scarpelli, then Councillor Singh.

2222
03:23:00,137 --> 03:23:01,758
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you, Mr. President.

2223
03:23:03,608 --> 03:23:08,229
[SPEAKER_21]: I just share the information that we heard over and over again.

2224
03:23:08,249 --> 03:23:09,289
[SPEAKER_21]: I read.

2225
03:23:09,309 --> 03:23:12,510
[SPEAKER_21]: I read our.

2226
03:23:14,630 --> 03:23:14,990
[SPEAKER_21]: For you.

2227
03:23:15,870 --> 03:23:17,551
[SPEAKER_21]: It was very clear back in February.

2228
03:23:18,531 --> 03:23:20,171
[SPEAKER_21]: And what was told to us at that podium?

2229
03:23:20,591 --> 03:23:21,592
[SPEAKER_21]: We don't have time.

2230
03:23:23,652 --> 03:23:23,812
[SPEAKER_21]: But.

2231
03:23:24,692 --> 03:23:26,613
[SPEAKER_21]: We have time to look at the emails.

2232
03:23:26,653 --> 03:23:27,873
[SPEAKER_21]: Go back to the emails, everybody.

2233
03:23:28,713 --> 03:23:31,994
[SPEAKER_21]: Go back to the emails from the chief of staff sent us a breakdown of.

2234
03:23:33,521 --> 03:23:37,845
[SPEAKER_21]: what each department is using legal services for.

2235
03:23:37,865 --> 03:23:38,966
[SPEAKER_21]: They spent time for that.

2236
03:23:39,386 --> 03:23:40,847
[SPEAKER_21]: Didn't spend time on what we asked.

2237
03:23:41,728 --> 03:23:50,536
[SPEAKER_21]: Look at what was shared and what was presented just in an email recently with the FIIA Department of Professional Services line.

2238
03:23:56,301 --> 03:23:57,102
[SPEAKER_21]: We didn't ask for that.

2239
03:23:59,762 --> 03:24:03,364
[SPEAKER_21]: Look at what was asked for legal costs when it talks about the breakdown.

2240
03:24:03,765 --> 03:24:04,865
[SPEAKER_21]: That's not what we asked for.

2241
03:24:05,866 --> 03:24:06,807
[SPEAKER_21]: That all took time.

2242
03:24:07,827 --> 03:24:16,713
[SPEAKER_21]: So the fact that we're sitting at the podium tonight and saying that this is going to take resources away, that's not on this council.

2243
03:24:17,254 --> 03:24:22,157
[SPEAKER_21]: That's on this administration and the department heads, because we were very clear what we asked for.

2244
03:24:24,539 --> 03:24:27,841
[SPEAKER_21]: And there's a process that you know, as a financial director,

2245
03:24:29,509 --> 03:24:34,952
[SPEAKER_21]: that you move the process through as a 112 budget using last year's numbers.

2246
03:24:35,072 --> 03:24:35,392
[SPEAKER_21]: That's it.

2247
03:24:37,113 --> 03:24:37,893
[SPEAKER_21]: Is it going to be work?

2248
03:24:37,933 --> 03:24:38,573
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm sure it is.

2249
03:24:38,874 --> 03:24:39,834
[SPEAKER_21]: But you know what work is?

2250
03:24:40,734 --> 03:24:45,877
[SPEAKER_21]: Answering to constituents that want to know where our money is being spent in this community.

2251
03:24:48,078 --> 03:24:57,763
[SPEAKER_21]: And when the chief of staff and the director of finance sit at our podium and look at us and tell us it's impossible to get us

2252
03:24:58,864 --> 03:25:05,206
[SPEAKER_21]: information from what I read to you is totally disingenuous.

2253
03:25:06,806 --> 03:25:08,867
[SPEAKER_21]: So, Mr President, this isn't shocking.

2254
03:25:09,327 --> 03:25:16,429
[SPEAKER_21]: This isn't something that should go out to the community like, Wow, look at Council Scott Pelley's asking for out of nowhere.

2255
03:25:18,289 --> 03:25:26,312
[SPEAKER_21]: The process started in February, February, February, March, April, May, June.

2256
03:25:26,392 --> 03:25:27,232
[SPEAKER_21]: Here we are in June.

2257
03:25:27,917 --> 03:25:29,278
[SPEAKER_21]: It's five months we've asked.

2258
03:25:30,359 --> 03:25:31,559
[SPEAKER_21]: Five months for a breakdown.

2259
03:25:31,579 --> 03:25:39,525
[SPEAKER_21]: And to sit there and look us in the eye and say, it's impossible for us to get you that information.

2260
03:25:41,066 --> 03:25:45,508
[SPEAKER_21]: But then you want to say, let's vote this budget through like we want.

2261
03:25:46,769 --> 03:25:51,152
[SPEAKER_21]: And let us then put all of our energy into getting you what you want in this FOIA.

2262
03:25:53,193 --> 03:25:54,014
[SPEAKER_21]: I don't trust you.

2263
03:25:57,462 --> 03:26:03,005
[SPEAKER_21]: The residents have voted us to ask these questions and get these answers, these questions answered.

2264
03:26:05,226 --> 03:26:10,569
[SPEAKER_21]: So again, Mr. President, we know the timeline.

2265
03:26:10,749 --> 03:26:12,610
[SPEAKER_21]: We know the history.

2266
03:26:14,090 --> 03:26:15,151
[SPEAKER_21]: This is our duty.

2267
03:26:15,931 --> 03:26:16,832
[SPEAKER_21]: This isn't a game.

2268
03:26:16,852 --> 03:26:20,093
[SPEAKER_21]: This is our duty to get the information that we need.

2269
03:26:20,814 --> 03:26:23,475
[SPEAKER_21]: So we're protecting the fiscal responsibilities of this community.

2270
03:26:28,478 --> 03:26:28,838
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

2271
03:26:30,439 --> 03:26:30,799
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

2272
03:26:30,899 --> 03:26:31,540
[SPEAKER_08]: Councillor Sang.

2273
03:26:32,880 --> 03:26:33,761
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm going to go to Councillor Sang.

2274
03:26:35,161 --> 03:26:35,582
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

2275
03:26:36,962 --> 03:26:41,905
[SPEAKER_09]: Like all the folks behind the rail, I've been knocking on doors in this city for years now.

2276
03:26:42,685 --> 03:26:46,667
[SPEAKER_09]: And there's a feeling I encounter more and more.

2277
03:26:48,528 --> 03:26:49,369
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not anger.

2278
03:26:50,009 --> 03:26:51,129
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not apathy.

2279
03:26:51,269 --> 03:26:55,332
[SPEAKER_09]: But it's something that is quiet and it's hard to name.

2280
03:26:56,032 --> 03:26:58,073
[SPEAKER_09]: And the feeling is one that

2281
03:26:58,773 --> 03:27:01,494
[SPEAKER_09]: showing up doesn't change anything.

2282
03:27:01,574 --> 03:27:11,439
[SPEAKER_09]: That you can come before the city council, you can give testimony, you can organize your neighbors, you can send the email, sign the petition, wait for your name to be called.

2283
03:27:12,119 --> 03:27:20,343
[SPEAKER_09]: And two years later, you're back at the same podium making the same case and someone is thanking you for your patience, for coming here.

2284
03:27:21,684 --> 03:27:28,327
[SPEAKER_09]: And at the same time, it's equally heartbreaking for us as counselors to not be able to say yes, we're gonna do that.

2285
03:27:29,130 --> 03:27:34,813
[SPEAKER_09]: Instead, I think way too often we have to say, yes, we agree with you, but we can't do that.

2286
03:27:37,194 --> 03:27:41,156
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think that feeling deserves an honest answer.

2287
03:27:42,196 --> 03:27:44,237
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not cynicism, right?

2288
03:27:44,678 --> 03:27:46,238
[SPEAKER_09]: That feeling is a sense of memory.

2289
03:27:46,559 --> 03:27:54,362
[SPEAKER_09]: It's a sense of accumulated weight of being told year after year, we hear you, we share your priorities, we just don't have the money this year.

2290
03:27:54,823 --> 03:27:55,563
[SPEAKER_09]: Come back next year.

2291
03:27:57,267 --> 03:28:01,289
[SPEAKER_09]: Residents have been asking for a more organized grant manager.

2292
03:28:03,330 --> 03:28:05,951
[SPEAKER_09]: Assessing staff for the residential exemption.

2293
03:28:07,872 --> 03:28:14,274
[SPEAKER_09]: For a program that, you know, taxpayers are looking for, are in counting on for real relief.

2294
03:28:15,055 --> 03:28:22,138
[SPEAKER_09]: They've been asking for a fire dive team, an urban forest, come back next year, come back next year, come back next year.

2295
03:28:23,017 --> 03:28:29,060
[SPEAKER_09]: And over time, I think that memory isn't just bitterness.

2296
03:28:29,100 --> 03:28:30,021
[SPEAKER_09]: It becomes evidence.

2297
03:28:30,841 --> 03:28:39,966
[SPEAKER_09]: It's evidence of the gap between what this city commissions in our budgets and what this city funds.

2298
03:28:40,847 --> 03:28:44,048
[SPEAKER_09]: But that gap isn't a fiscal inevitability.

2299
03:28:44,108 --> 03:28:47,490
[SPEAKER_09]: It's a political choice made quietly, made year after year.

2300
03:28:49,725 --> 03:28:54,969
[SPEAKER_09]: When I think about our job as a city council, it's to make that choice harder to make without consequence.

2301
03:28:55,650 --> 03:29:11,543
[SPEAKER_09]: To demand the plans, to build the city that our residents deserve, to develop a revenue plan that stops budget season from becoming a battle of attrition between branches of government and makes it into a win-win where our residents get more than just crumbs.

2302
03:29:13,865 --> 03:29:15,366
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think that's what tonight,

2303
03:29:16,768 --> 03:29:20,190
[SPEAKER_09]: I wish tonight was, and I think it's what tonight could be.

2304
03:29:22,031 --> 03:29:25,654
[SPEAKER_09]: There's an elephant in the room, the law department budget.

2305
03:29:28,575 --> 03:29:30,797
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm not calling to eliminate it.

2306
03:29:30,817 --> 03:29:35,700
[SPEAKER_09]: I think the city has active legal obligations and council needs to be paid.

2307
03:29:35,720 --> 03:29:37,801
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm not here to manufacture a crisis.

2308
03:29:39,704 --> 03:29:43,687
[SPEAKER_09]: I also can't fully fund a line that I cannot see.

2309
03:29:44,407 --> 03:29:47,309
[SPEAKER_09]: And that's the information that we've been missing.

2310
03:29:48,370 --> 03:30:01,740
[SPEAKER_09]: In February, this council passed Resolution 26-043, I believe, requesting a full accounting of the city's, of Medford's litigation history, its legal costs, its settlement agreements since 2020.

2311
03:30:03,021 --> 03:30:07,103
[SPEAKER_09]: In April, every member of this body signed a public records request making the same demand.

2312
03:30:07,824 --> 03:30:09,185
[SPEAKER_09]: The statutory deadline passed.

2313
03:30:09,628 --> 03:30:12,511
[SPEAKER_09]: An extension was granted, that deadline passed too.

2314
03:30:13,172 --> 03:30:21,300
[SPEAKER_09]: And now we're in June being asked to appropriate funds for outside legal costs that run three to four times what it seems like.

2315
03:30:22,581 --> 03:30:31,991
[SPEAKER_09]: It seems reasonable in other cities' budgets, but we can't even know that because we do our line items differently and it seems like we're spreading it across different budgets.

2316
03:30:34,012 --> 03:30:40,333
[SPEAKER_09]: We don't know, we don't have full knowledge about what exactly we are defending, how many cases that we're defending.

2317
03:30:42,474 --> 03:30:50,176
[SPEAKER_09]: We don't really know clearly what we've paid firm by firm without knowing what we've settled, why, and for how much.

2318
03:30:51,956 --> 03:30:54,157
[SPEAKER_09]: I think in short, we're being asked to trust.

2319
03:30:55,497 --> 03:31:01,758
[SPEAKER_09]: But I think the governance of a city can't run on trust alone.

2320
03:31:02,139 --> 03:31:03,739
[SPEAKER_09]: We can trust, but we have to verify.

2321
03:31:04,866 --> 03:31:12,750
[SPEAKER_09]: And with verification, we need information on the ability of residents and their representatives to see what's being done in their name and to correct it when necessary.

2322
03:31:13,731 --> 03:31:17,873
[SPEAKER_09]: We hear from residents that they want more transparency.

2323
03:31:18,133 --> 03:31:21,635
[SPEAKER_09]: We hear it from city employees that they want more accountability.

2324
03:31:22,276 --> 03:31:24,417
[SPEAKER_09]: And year after year, those two words

2325
03:31:25,822 --> 03:31:27,804
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not about, it's not a complaint about tone.

2326
03:31:28,204 --> 03:31:35,390
[SPEAKER_09]: It's a description of a distance between the decisions that are being made and the people those decisions are being made about.

2327
03:31:36,090 --> 03:31:37,411
[SPEAKER_09]: And that distance is a choice.

2328
03:31:38,312 --> 03:31:40,994
[SPEAKER_09]: And we can work hard to close that.

2329
03:31:42,635 --> 03:31:45,418
[SPEAKER_09]: This council has very few tools to close it.

2330
03:31:45,558 --> 03:31:49,881
[SPEAKER_09]: I think, you know, we've talked time and time again about how limited we are in our powers.

2331
03:31:50,382 --> 03:31:51,863
[SPEAKER_09]: But tonight we do actually have one.

2332
03:31:56,031 --> 03:32:08,105
[SPEAKER_09]: I think I also want to note that, you know, the administration's position is that any cuts are impermissible if we want the supplemental appropriations.

2333
03:32:08,165 --> 03:32:12,971
[SPEAKER_09]: But that appropriation authority doesn't come from the mayor's position of permission.

2334
03:32:13,291 --> 03:32:15,293
[SPEAKER_09]: It comes from Article 6 of our city charter.

2335
03:32:16,434 --> 03:32:31,729
[SPEAKER_09]: Section 6-4 gives this council the power to reduce or decrease, to reject or decrease any appropriation except expenditures required by law without qualification, without an exception carved out for transmittal letter conditions.

2336
03:32:32,770 --> 03:32:36,093
[SPEAKER_09]: And as I said earlier tonight, a transmittal letter isn't a contract.

2337
03:32:36,213 --> 03:32:37,014
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not an ordinance.

2338
03:32:37,394 --> 03:32:37,935
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not law.

2339
03:32:39,464 --> 03:32:46,608
[SPEAKER_09]: And the mayor still has a remedy to what I'm going to propose, section 3.7, a veto.

2340
03:32:48,149 --> 03:32:52,352
[SPEAKER_09]: So, you know, she can return the budget with written objections.

2341
03:32:52,372 --> 03:32:53,213
[SPEAKER_09]: We can reconsider.

2342
03:32:53,853 --> 03:32:57,815
[SPEAKER_09]: And if we choose to override, the budget, you know, the budget we pass takes effect.

2343
03:32:57,956 --> 03:32:58,756
[SPEAKER_09]: That's the process.

2344
03:32:59,737 --> 03:33:01,057
[SPEAKER_09]: That's what the charter lays out.

2345
03:33:01,538 --> 03:33:05,840
[SPEAKER_09]: That's, the separation of powers isn't just a technicality.

2346
03:33:06,061 --> 03:33:08,042
[SPEAKER_09]: It's an architecture of accountable government.

2347
03:33:09,275 --> 03:33:12,437
[SPEAKER_09]: So there actually is a path to full funding.

2348
03:33:13,317 --> 03:33:14,398
[SPEAKER_09]: That path's direct.

2349
03:33:15,578 --> 03:33:16,459
[SPEAKER_09]: Produce the records.

2350
03:33:20,341 --> 03:33:33,828
[SPEAKER_09]: That path's open tonight, but, you know, and if we choose to cut the funding, as I'll move, then if we get the records,

2351
03:33:36,977 --> 03:33:39,580
[SPEAKER_09]: The mayor can transmit a supplemental appropriation.

2352
03:33:40,501 --> 03:33:42,783
[SPEAKER_09]: This council can and should vote.

2353
03:33:44,024 --> 03:33:45,666
[SPEAKER_09]: And hopefully the funds will flow.

2354
03:33:46,767 --> 03:33:51,772
[SPEAKER_09]: And whether the mayor walks, I think it's entirely her decision.

2355
03:33:53,614 --> 03:33:59,360
[SPEAKER_09]: So let me talk about what I'm gonna propose.

2356
03:34:00,383 --> 03:34:10,605
[SPEAKER_09]: Earlier tonight, I moved to table with Councilor Scarpelli's resolution that would have rejected this budget entirely and sent the budget into a one, one-twelfth budget for the coming year.

2357
03:34:12,285 --> 03:34:24,288
[SPEAKER_09]: That would mean month to month appropriations across every department, and my fear is that, that provides no stability, no certainty for the workers and residents who depend on city services.

2358
03:34:25,028 --> 03:34:28,149
[SPEAKER_09]: That option, but I want to say, that option was available.

2359
03:34:28,369 --> 03:34:29,129
[SPEAKER_09]: It's one I considered.

2360
03:34:31,148 --> 03:34:34,492
[SPEAKER_09]: And it's an option I chose, I'm choosing not to use.

2361
03:34:35,453 --> 03:34:40,918
[SPEAKER_09]: Because I believe that the council's job isn't to maximize pressure, it's also to govern.

2362
03:34:41,839 --> 03:34:49,808
[SPEAKER_09]: What I'm moving instead is a targeted reduction to a single department for a defined period with a defined path to restoration.

2363
03:34:51,924 --> 03:34:57,328
[SPEAKER_09]: One that preserves stability across the rest of City Hall and places on the administration a choice.

2364
03:34:57,989 --> 03:35:00,310
[SPEAKER_09]: It's been deferring since February.

2365
03:35:01,411 --> 03:35:03,873
[SPEAKER_09]: Produce the records or explain to the public why you won't.

2366
03:35:05,571 --> 03:35:21,835
[SPEAKER_09]: So with that, I moved to cut the law department by 83% or ten-twelfths to leave two months of funding and allow the administration to come back to the council with the requested information on legal expenses alongside a request to fund the department for the remaining 12 months of the fiscal year.

2367
03:35:22,815 --> 03:35:27,336
[SPEAKER_09]: More specifically, I moved to cut the following amounts from these specific line items.

2368
03:35:28,176 --> 03:35:30,137
[SPEAKER_09]: From 010-151-5110, permanent employees, to cut

2369
03:35:35,883 --> 03:35:36,904
[SPEAKER_09]: $182,576.33.

2370
03:35:35,903 --> 03:35:36,904
[SPEAKER_09]: From 010-151-5302, professional services legal to cut $130,000.

2371
03:35:36,984 --> 03:35:37,784
[SPEAKER_09]: From 010-151-5761, claims under $2,500 to cut $41,666.67.

2372
03:36:04,385 --> 03:36:05,245
[SPEAKER_09]: from 010-151-5762 claims over $2,500,000 to cut $62,500.

2373
03:36:06,085 --> 03:36:07,466
[SPEAKER_09]: And finally, 010-151-5763 claims to cut $8,333.33.

2374
03:36:07,506 --> 03:36:10,027
[SPEAKER_09]: I think this gives us enough time to get some more answers.

2375
03:36:34,270 --> 03:36:46,175
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, it sounds hefty, but I think with two months, maybe we can get the answers and hopefully we'll be able to pass the rest of the year's worth of a budget.

2376
03:36:46,315 --> 03:36:51,458
[SPEAKER_09]: And it gives us the time to find out the answers so that we can go back to our constituents with real answers.

2377
03:36:54,759 --> 03:36:58,681
[SPEAKER_09]: I think that's the big news of the day, but look,

2378
03:37:03,604 --> 03:37:10,149
[SPEAKER_09]: There are things that this budget doesn't do, and I think I've enumerated that.

2379
03:37:11,831 --> 03:37:23,800
[SPEAKER_09]: With that motion, if this council accepts it, I'd also be comfortable voting yes on the rest of it, because I think the vast majority of this city's workers and departments have done nothing to earn instability.

2380
03:37:24,814 --> 03:37:33,479
[SPEAKER_09]: The men and women in public works and recreation and our health departments in the library, they submitted their budgets, they made their case, they're ready to do their jobs.

2381
03:37:34,699 --> 03:37:38,482
[SPEAKER_09]: A 112th budget doesn't punish the administration for its choices.

2382
03:37:38,862 --> 03:37:41,363
[SPEAKER_09]: It punishes them for ours.

2383
03:37:41,563 --> 03:37:43,464
[SPEAKER_09]: It punishes the workers for our choices.

2384
03:37:44,225 --> 03:37:49,408
[SPEAKER_09]: It denies every department an operating budget calibrated to the actual costs of fiscal year 27.

2385
03:37:51,070 --> 03:37:56,372
[SPEAKER_09]: Not the cost of a year ago, not a rolling average, but what it actually takes to run the city in a fiscal year.

2386
03:37:57,193 --> 03:38:02,495
[SPEAKER_09]: And I'm afraid that that leans more towards show than accountability.

2387
03:38:03,095 --> 03:38:05,376
[SPEAKER_09]: That becomes somewhat like collateral damage.

2388
03:38:06,617 --> 03:38:20,163
[SPEAKER_09]: And so a yes vote with the amendments I proposed, in my opinion, is a decision to protect the people and departments that have earned a real budget, hold the line on one that has an answer for itself, and to leave the remaining choice.

2389
03:38:20,974 --> 03:38:23,776
[SPEAKER_09]: transparency or obstruction exactly where it belongs.

2390
03:38:26,498 --> 03:38:29,961
[SPEAKER_09]: We need to move past being a city that manages scarcity.

2391
03:38:32,463 --> 03:38:43,171
[SPEAKER_09]: The plans we've commissioned, the promises we've made, the things that we said we valued but didn't become real, I think these are all justified feelings from residents.

2392
03:38:45,415 --> 03:38:49,538
[SPEAKER_09]: And we need to create the conditions by which we can build trust again with residents.

2393
03:38:49,818 --> 03:38:59,825
[SPEAKER_09]: That we can give them all the information that we have and to really have an accurate picture going forward of how we're gonna fund the big projects that our city demands and deserves.

2394
03:39:01,527 --> 03:39:05,309
[SPEAKER_09]: So I put that motion out there for this council to debate.

2395
03:39:05,750 --> 03:39:11,614
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm looking forward to hearing different viewpoints about what folks think of it.

2396
03:39:15,008 --> 03:39:16,349
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councilor Sang.

2397
03:39:16,369 --> 03:39:19,933
[SPEAKER_07]: On a motion of Councilor Sang to cut, seconded by.

2398
03:39:20,814 --> 03:39:22,216
[SPEAKER_20]: Second.

2399
03:39:22,356 --> 03:39:23,397
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Callahan.

2400
03:39:26,225 --> 03:39:35,191
[SPEAKER_14]: I mostly wanted to really thank Councilor Sang for having done a lot of homework before tonight.

2401
03:39:35,612 --> 03:39:38,314
[SPEAKER_14]: It's a really difficult position that we're in.

2402
03:39:39,675 --> 03:39:54,747
[SPEAKER_14]: And I very much also appreciate Councilor Serapelli for having a solution, which I think is kind of the textbook solution that one 12th budget is what is described as like, this is what has to happen when a city council and a mayor cannot agree on a budget as you go to one 12th.

2403
03:39:55,887 --> 03:40:01,788
[SPEAKER_14]: the way that it is dealt with in Massachusetts, sort of on a textbook perspective.

2404
03:40:02,748 --> 03:40:15,511
[SPEAKER_14]: But I also appreciate what our finance director is saying, that moving to a 112 budget is actually extremely cumbersome to say the least, and will require a ton of extra work and effort.

2405
03:40:17,131 --> 03:40:21,432
[SPEAKER_14]: And I also very much appreciate the basic

2406
03:40:22,712 --> 03:40:30,854
[SPEAKER_14]: that like instability is not healthy for anyone in our city and moving to a one 12th budget would just be very unstable.

2407
03:40:32,395 --> 03:40:39,677
[SPEAKER_14]: So I just very much appreciate this as what I think is a incredibly well thought out option for us that we can approve.

2408
03:40:40,898 --> 03:40:47,241
[SPEAKER_14]: You know, the rest of the budget leave not just one month, but two months of law budget available.

2409
03:40:48,522 --> 03:40:58,568
[SPEAKER_14]: And then, you know, the ability upon the production of the information and documents that we have requested to move forward on the rest of the 10 months.

2410
03:40:58,788 --> 03:41:00,649
[SPEAKER_14]: I feel like it's an excellent compromise.

2411
03:41:00,729 --> 03:41:02,851
[SPEAKER_14]: So I really appreciate that.

2412
03:41:02,971 --> 03:41:05,032
[SPEAKER_14]: And that's my thinking so far.

2413
03:41:05,112 --> 03:41:08,074
[SPEAKER_14]: I also look forward to hearing the rest of the councilor's opinions.

2414
03:41:09,113 --> 03:41:09,473
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

2415
03:41:09,573 --> 03:41:11,616
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Scarpelli, then Councilor Malauulu.

2416
03:41:12,156 --> 03:41:13,157
[SPEAKER_21]: I yield to Councilor Malauulu.

2417
03:41:13,217 --> 03:41:14,138
[SPEAKER_21]: She hasn't spoken yet.

2418
03:41:14,298 --> 03:41:16,440
[SPEAKER_21]: Councilor Malauulu.

2419
03:41:16,801 --> 03:41:23,567
[SPEAKER_03]: First, I appreciate both Councilor Scarpelli and Councilor Sang for bringing up these two different options.

2420
03:41:24,108 --> 03:41:29,013
[SPEAKER_03]: We've been having this conversation for so long about trying to find information around the law budget.

2421
03:41:29,904 --> 03:41:50,399
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, I, I, I think what makes me the most nervous is that I don't want to leave departments, um, feeling unstable, but also I get where, uh, Councilor Scarpelli is coming from on the 112th budget, and at some point, um,

2422
03:41:51,300 --> 03:41:57,505
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, at what point do we finally say, I don't know, enough is enough, and get these types of answers?

2423
03:41:58,085 --> 03:42:13,857
[SPEAKER_03]: I guess my question would be, if, if Councilor Singh's amendments to this go through and the two months, you know, pass by and we still don't have that information, what's, what does the council do then?

2424
03:42:13,917 --> 03:42:14,798
[SPEAKER_03]: What does that look like?

2425
03:42:14,818 --> 03:42:19,181
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm, again, being kind of new to this process, I'm not quite sure how you handle that.

2426
03:42:19,687 --> 03:42:24,088
[SPEAKER_03]: Is it then it jumps into, do we look back to the 112th?

2427
03:42:24,148 --> 03:42:31,949
[SPEAKER_03]: I just don't know what the end result is one way or the other and would appreciate any feedback or thoughts that people could share on it.

2428
03:42:34,089 --> 03:42:40,731
[SPEAKER_07]: At that point, you know, the administration would have to put forward a supplemental appropriation for the law department budget.

2429
03:42:42,391 --> 03:42:45,611
[SPEAKER_07]: So, the money would run out at the end of August for the law department.

2430
03:42:45,991 --> 03:42:47,552
[SPEAKER_07]: So, KP Law Retainer.

2431
03:42:49,578 --> 03:42:55,263
[SPEAKER_07]: City Solicitor, nominally Office Manager Spencer, which is one person I don't think we want to harm at all.

2432
03:42:56,724 --> 03:43:03,769
[SPEAKER_07]: But yeah, so that's what would happen if the information requesting wasn't provided.

2433
03:43:05,290 --> 03:43:10,715
[SPEAKER_07]: There's like some wiggle room in there from what I read of Councilor Sang's motion.

2434
03:43:10,935 --> 03:43:14,217
[SPEAKER_07]: He proposed to cut, I think, the five big line items in the law department.

2435
03:43:14,257 --> 03:43:15,598
[SPEAKER_07]: There's some small ones.

2436
03:43:15,638 --> 03:43:16,859
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know how many weeks that gets.

2437
03:43:18,725 --> 03:43:23,187
[SPEAKER_07]: past August 31st, depending on what the administration chooses to fund in the department.

2438
03:43:23,367 --> 03:43:43,760
[SPEAKER_07]: But yeah, in terms of what would happen, it would just be within the law department budget after today if the cuts were made to the law department budget and then information wasn't provided that the council felt was sufficient to approve further funding.

2439
03:43:44,991 --> 03:43:48,294
[SPEAKER_07]: You could also approve, take the law department month to month after two months.

2440
03:43:48,334 --> 03:43:52,537
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, there's a lot of things you could do within there, but in terms of what happened, I mean, this is not really precedented.

2441
03:43:52,817 --> 03:44:04,966
[SPEAKER_07]: So your lack of understanding what happens next is not really, this has come up a couple of times in the last six, seven budgets, the budgets I've been around for.

2442
03:44:07,348 --> 03:44:09,210
[SPEAKER_07]: To be honest, it's 1105, that's an early night.

2443
03:44:09,530 --> 03:44:13,253
[SPEAKER_07]: I remember, I think it was fiscal 23, we were here till two in the morning.

2444
03:44:14,785 --> 03:44:15,686
[SPEAKER_07]: The mayor was actually here.

2445
03:44:17,866 --> 03:44:21,588
[SPEAKER_07]: That was a... Yeah.

2446
03:44:22,128 --> 03:44:26,689
[SPEAKER_07]: Bob looks back wistfully and fondly with a smile at the 1.35 a.m.

2447
03:44:26,709 --> 03:44:27,329
[SPEAKER_07]: budget agreement.

2448
03:44:33,975 --> 03:44:37,176
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, I mean, we haven't done a 1-12 before in my time on the council.

2449
03:44:37,896 --> 03:44:46,759
[SPEAKER_07]: So, and certainly if we go the route of approving essentially most of the budget except for the law department budget, then future discussions would be constrained to the law department budget.

2450
03:44:48,320 --> 03:44:49,100
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Scarpelli.

2451
03:44:49,820 --> 03:44:50,760
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you, Mr. President.

2452
03:44:50,780 --> 03:44:53,801
[SPEAKER_21]: I appreciate Councilor Sang's thoughtful approach.

2453
03:44:53,861 --> 03:44:58,743
[SPEAKER_21]: But again, to be clear, this, it's not compatible from one council.

2454
03:44:58,803 --> 03:45:01,824
[SPEAKER_21]: This is the process that we have as an option.

2455
03:45:02,644 --> 03:45:12,211
[SPEAKER_21]: and the 112th budget doesn't, the fear that our employees and recreation and our lifeguards won't get paid is not true.

2456
03:45:13,051 --> 03:45:13,872
[SPEAKER_21]: It's the process.

2457
03:45:14,553 --> 03:45:15,133
[SPEAKER_21]: No, they did.

2458
03:45:15,233 --> 03:45:15,914
[SPEAKER_21]: No, no, no.

2459
03:45:16,334 --> 03:45:23,259
[SPEAKER_21]: That's what Council, Mr. Dickerson said, that that's the fear that it's going to be so cumbersome for the staff.

2460
03:45:23,799 --> 03:45:29,223
[SPEAKER_21]: Well, what guarantees that, why are we here?

2461
03:45:29,937 --> 03:45:32,919
[SPEAKER_21]: We're here because we're questioning the law line.

2462
03:45:33,940 --> 03:45:41,826
[SPEAKER_21]: The mayor has come up here with the chief of staff and our finance director and said, see, we are following the rules with the law line.

2463
03:45:42,726 --> 03:45:43,507
[SPEAKER_21]: And they weren't lying.

2464
03:45:43,567 --> 03:45:53,314
[SPEAKER_21]: The truth, they're right, because they're funding the law issues and concerns through other avenues, which we don't know.

2465
03:45:53,354 --> 03:45:54,175
[SPEAKER_21]: That's why we're here.

2466
03:45:55,376 --> 03:45:58,258
[SPEAKER_21]: So I know it sounds good, but understand,

2467
03:45:59,092 --> 03:46:09,254
[SPEAKER_21]: even if we fund it for two months, they'll find a way to fund the legal line and other options.

2468
03:46:09,754 --> 03:46:14,635
[SPEAKER_21]: We just don't know how because we've asked legally, but they're not telling us.

2469
03:46:15,895 --> 03:46:28,417
[SPEAKER_21]: So although it's a thoughtful process and a very well put forth process, this administration has shown already that all that they'll do

2470
03:46:29,528 --> 03:46:33,230
[SPEAKER_21]: They say thank you, move on, maybe cut the supplemental, maybe not.

2471
03:46:34,390 --> 03:46:42,253
[SPEAKER_21]: But they'll just move on and fund the line the way they're doing it for the last five years.

2472
03:46:43,834 --> 03:46:45,775
[SPEAKER_21]: That's my concern.

2473
03:46:46,335 --> 03:46:47,075
[SPEAKER_21]: It's not anger.

2474
03:46:47,776 --> 03:46:49,416
[SPEAKER_21]: It's not bitterness.

2475
03:46:51,017 --> 03:46:55,279
[SPEAKER_21]: It's the tool that we have as city councils in our toolbox to say,

2476
03:46:56,282 --> 03:47:00,544
[SPEAKER_21]: How do we get the answers that we require for our residents?

2477
03:47:02,145 --> 03:47:14,770
[SPEAKER_21]: So I would hope that we at least put the 112B paper through a motion and it voted up or down, that's fine.

2478
03:47:15,431 --> 03:47:24,835
[SPEAKER_21]: And then that'll give us an opportunity for the second option, which would put it out there.

2479
03:47:26,127 --> 03:47:33,369
[SPEAKER_21]: I do have a motion on the floor, Mr. President, that I'm hoping that my council colleagues understand the reason why.

2480
03:47:33,489 --> 03:47:40,791
[SPEAKER_21]: So it's not to hurt any other department or make any department feel like it's not stable.

2481
03:47:41,831 --> 03:47:43,191
[SPEAKER_21]: All it is is a continuation.

2482
03:47:43,211 --> 03:47:45,532
[SPEAKER_21]: It's like having a 13th and 14th month of the year.

2483
03:47:46,232 --> 03:47:47,392
[SPEAKER_21]: It's using the numbers of 2025.

2484
03:47:47,632 --> 03:47:52,354
[SPEAKER_21]: That's what the intent of this rule is, this law is.

2485
03:47:55,810 --> 03:48:04,336
[SPEAKER_21]: It's the only thing that we have because, again, to sit in front of us tonight and look at all of us in the eye and say, there's no way I can get you that information.

2486
03:48:05,016 --> 03:48:05,697
[SPEAKER_21]: It's impossible.

2487
03:48:08,659 --> 03:48:10,340
[SPEAKER_21]: What makes you think it's going to change in a month?

2488
03:48:11,641 --> 03:48:12,441
[SPEAKER_21]: But thank you.

2489
03:48:14,562 --> 03:48:15,863
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councillor Scarapelli.

2490
03:48:15,883 --> 03:48:16,624
[SPEAKER_07]: Councillor Callahan.

2491
03:48:18,818 --> 03:48:27,024
[SPEAKER_14]: I do appreciate what councillor Scarpelli is saying I Think that for me

2492
03:48:29,972 --> 03:48:32,834
[SPEAKER_14]: The, the law budget that is being requested is $529,000.

2493
03:48:32,874 --> 03:48:40,018
[SPEAKER_14]: And I know how tight the budget of the city of Medford is.

2494
03:48:40,919 --> 03:48:46,822
[SPEAKER_14]: I think that, I do believe that cutting that by 80 to 83% is enough to get the information, I do.

2495
03:48:55,537 --> 03:49:01,381
[SPEAKER_14]: I see the value of both of these perspectives, and I do agree that a one-twelfth budget is, that is a thing.

2496
03:49:01,642 --> 03:49:03,243
[SPEAKER_14]: We're not, it's not invented, right?

2497
03:49:03,703 --> 03:49:10,308
[SPEAKER_14]: This is what happens in Massachusetts when city councils and mayors cannot agree on a budget.

2498
03:49:10,808 --> 03:49:23,018
[SPEAKER_14]: So it is, you know, a standard thing, but I also think that we will, I believe we'll get what we want through this,

2499
03:49:25,507 --> 03:49:29,089
[SPEAKER_14]: drastic cut of the law budget because of its size.

2500
03:49:30,089 --> 03:49:34,972
[SPEAKER_14]: So I think that's why I'm leaning toward Councilor Sang's proposal.

2501
03:49:36,092 --> 03:49:38,253
[SPEAKER_14]: But I, you know, I could be wrong.

2502
03:49:38,613 --> 03:49:42,215
[SPEAKER_14]: If I'm wrong, next time, George, we're going for it.

2503
03:49:42,715 --> 03:49:50,179
[SPEAKER_17]: All right.

2504
03:49:52,340 --> 03:49:52,840
[SPEAKER_07]: Just a second.

2505
03:49:52,860 --> 03:49:54,401
[SPEAKER_07]: I want to list the motions that we have.

2506
03:49:55,386 --> 03:50:02,668
[SPEAKER_07]: We have a B paper from Councilor Scarpelli, a motion to cut the law department budget specific line items.

2507
03:50:02,708 --> 03:50:04,429
[SPEAKER_07]: I think I got them down by Councilor Sang.

2508
03:50:05,429 --> 03:50:07,390
[SPEAKER_07]: And then we would take a vote on the final paper.

2509
03:50:08,090 --> 03:50:09,370
[SPEAKER_07]: So those are the motions.

2510
03:50:10,771 --> 03:50:13,572
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll come back for seconds after we hear from the administration.

2511
03:50:15,532 --> 03:50:16,313
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you, President Behrs.

2512
03:50:17,513 --> 03:50:22,695
[SPEAKER_25]: I feel it's important to set the record straight at this point from our perspective.

2513
03:50:25,590 --> 03:50:41,816
[SPEAKER_25]: You know, it was stated at some point during the various discussions, the prior paper, this paper, that something about, I don't honestly recall which counselor it was, but something about audacity to ask for information where money is going for legal costs.

2514
03:50:42,756 --> 03:50:47,118
[SPEAKER_25]: Nobody's saying that that characterization is simply false.

2515
03:50:48,639 --> 03:50:49,559
[SPEAKER_25]: The reality is,

2516
03:50:51,425 --> 03:51:03,946
[SPEAKER_25]: The nature and specificity of the council's request itself has been a major barrier to our ability to fulfill the records request.

2517
03:51:06,473 --> 03:51:25,668
[SPEAKER_25]: As I believe was stated on the petition to the Secretary of State's office, and I can pull it up, there's about 30,000 records that we discovered would need to be reviewed for item A alone of that public records request that Counselor Scarpelli read all the way to letter K.

2518
03:51:31,915 --> 03:51:40,280
[SPEAKER_25]: I think it needs to be stated by me that it's a lot more cumbersome and a lot more complex.

2519
03:51:40,880 --> 03:51:48,825
[SPEAKER_25]: I mean, I think the language of the FOIA request itself speaks volumes as to the complexity of it.

2520
03:51:49,005 --> 03:51:56,910
[SPEAKER_25]: But in case, you know, any member of this council has any, you know,

2521
03:52:01,828 --> 03:52:16,384
[SPEAKER_25]: has any unawareness of the complexity and amount of resources and time that it's going to take from the city to comply with that records request, which we have begun working on, by the way.

2522
03:52:18,387 --> 03:52:20,068
[SPEAKER_25]: Our law department has begun working on it.

2523
03:52:22,962 --> 03:52:30,587
[SPEAKER_25]: And we have, in good faith, sent records that are compliant with the resolution and with the public records request.

2524
03:52:31,387 --> 03:52:39,812
[SPEAKER_25]: So, Councillor Scarapelli, President Behrs, through you, had stated that we have been providing information that wasn't requested.

2525
03:52:39,852 --> 03:52:45,196
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, that's just purely false, because we have provided information that was specifically requested.

2526
03:52:45,756 --> 03:52:46,997
[SPEAKER_25]: That included settlement agreements.

2527
03:52:47,417 --> 03:52:48,418
[SPEAKER_25]: That's, that's fact.

2528
03:52:48,978 --> 03:52:52,745
[SPEAKER_25]: that included a breakdown of the fire department line item.

2529
03:52:54,268 --> 03:52:54,909
[SPEAKER_25]: There's a motion.

2530
03:52:55,290 --> 03:52:58,456
[SPEAKER_25]: It occurred at the meeting of...

2531
03:53:01,997 --> 03:53:02,657
[SPEAKER_25]: Sounds right.

2532
03:53:03,898 --> 03:53:05,598
[SPEAKER_25]: It occurred at the meeting of June 2nd.

2533
03:53:05,618 --> 03:53:11,380
[SPEAKER_25]: I, I, I actually believe it was May 27th, but we can agree to disagree on that, no big deal.

2534
03:53:11,941 --> 03:53:19,143
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not, we're not quibbling on that one, but the fact of the matter is that we have made as much attempts as we can.

2535
03:53:19,483 --> 03:53:23,465
[SPEAKER_25]: The reality is, as I stated to the council, is that we have

2536
03:53:26,046 --> 03:53:29,649
[SPEAKER_25]: We had a very complex budget preparation process before us this year.

2537
03:53:31,710 --> 03:53:38,595
[SPEAKER_25]: We are fortunate to have onboarded a new assistant finance director and budget manager.

2538
03:53:39,155 --> 03:53:40,997
[SPEAKER_25]: That position and that person has

2539
03:53:41,717 --> 03:53:55,725
[SPEAKER_25]: done a good job coming up to speed where they can, but there has been a lot of work that has been put into the process that others ordinarily wouldn't have to do because of that onboarding, myself included.

2540
03:53:56,526 --> 03:54:03,210
[SPEAKER_25]: And this has been a challenging year at best, but we, with the councils, and I won't discount the councils,

2541
03:54:05,751 --> 03:54:21,642
[SPEAKER_25]: flexibility here on this, but with the council's flexibility, we have delivered, I believe, a comprehensive and solid budget that was well thought out by the mayor, all department heads, dialogue with this council,

2542
03:54:22,342 --> 03:54:37,443
[SPEAKER_25]: including but not limited to a 15-page memorandum from this council to which the mayor personally reviewed and responded to with the support of department heads over the course of several weeks upon receiving that communication.

2543
03:54:37,923 --> 03:54:49,586
[SPEAKER_25]: The mayor has communicated with this council the work that she has done and has negotiated with this council to provide for the things that this council felt were dire and important.

2544
03:54:50,366 --> 03:54:59,728
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not going to drill down into those at this point, but one thing that's worth noting, which is an incredible, incredible change in this process, is that

2545
03:55:01,188 --> 03:55:02,048
[SPEAKER_25]: We're not talking about $112,000.

2546
03:55:02,589 --> 03:55:13,514
[SPEAKER_25]: We're really talking about $1.4 million on order of magnitude because we're talking about an additional $1.25 million that was allocated to the school department.

2547
03:55:14,034 --> 03:55:17,696
[SPEAKER_25]: So while I don't agree with the characterization as to

2548
03:55:19,517 --> 03:55:23,882
[SPEAKER_25]: You know, small potatoes, I know that those weren't the words that were used, but I'll, I'll just say that.

2549
03:55:24,883 --> 03:55:32,250
[SPEAKER_25]: Because I think we're really talking about significant changes to meet the city's needs, to meet the school department needs, to meet the priorities of this council.

2550
03:55:32,731 --> 03:55:39,097
[SPEAKER_25]: One of the specific things outlined in the city council's 15 page memo was

2551
03:55:40,098 --> 03:55:43,620
[SPEAKER_25]: the request to increase the funding for the school department.

2552
03:55:44,360 --> 03:55:54,585
[SPEAKER_25]: And that is unequivocally provided for in a $1.25 million adjustment to the allocation that would have otherwise went to the school department.

2553
03:55:59,982 --> 03:56:03,145
[SPEAKER_25]: I said this before, but the mayor has negotiated in good faith for weeks.

2554
03:56:03,865 --> 03:56:17,015
[SPEAKER_25]: She indicated that she'd be available for discussions with councilors to discuss both the records request and any other council matters with regard to this budget.

2555
03:56:17,575 --> 03:56:28,040
[SPEAKER_25]: in her email on June 3rd, and I know that she received three communications that effectively thanked her for the clear and concise communication from this council.

2556
03:56:30,181 --> 03:56:36,363
[SPEAKER_25]: So, I also never said it was impossible to provide certain information.

2557
03:56:36,403 --> 03:56:46,988
[SPEAKER_25]: I never said it was impossible, but what is incredibly challenging and darn near impossible is

2558
03:56:48,922 --> 03:56:52,091
[SPEAKER_25]: the length and complexity of the public records request that has been placed before us.

2559
03:57:06,928 --> 03:57:21,482
[SPEAKER_25]: I think it was already stated here, but cutting the law department budget by the amounts that were proposed could affect a union employee located in the law department, the office manager, Janice Spencer.

2560
03:57:22,362 --> 03:57:27,367
[SPEAKER_25]: I think that is really unfortunate that this council would venture that direction.

2561
03:57:31,351 --> 03:57:31,611
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

2562
03:57:36,972 --> 03:57:37,832
[SPEAKER_07]: say we all take a breath.

2563
03:57:41,613 --> 03:57:44,673
[SPEAKER_07]: We would happily entertain a supplemental appropriation to fund Janice's position.

2564
03:57:47,314 --> 03:57:53,155
[SPEAKER_07]: If, you know, the threats, it's the threats that really are just like unbelievable.

2565
03:57:53,975 --> 03:57:57,015
[SPEAKER_07]: We're not going to do $5,000 for the arts if you don't cut anything.

2566
03:57:57,256 --> 03:57:59,736
[SPEAKER_07]: If you cut anything, we're taking it out on Janice.

2567
03:57:59,956 --> 03:58:05,537
[SPEAKER_07]: Like, I just don't, I want to say

2568
03:58:06,159 --> 03:58:07,559
[SPEAKER_07]: Go ahead, George, and then I'll go.

2569
03:58:08,219 --> 03:58:22,542
[SPEAKER_21]: Mr. President, because the chief of staff has come up here time after time and spewed these different poor me attitude, like this is important, that I didn't say that, or let me defend this, let me defend that.

2570
03:58:23,262 --> 03:58:25,523
[SPEAKER_21]: We were very clear five months ago what we were looking for.

2571
03:58:26,403 --> 03:58:28,083
[SPEAKER_21]: Let me even be clearer than that.

2572
03:58:29,223 --> 03:58:31,804
[SPEAKER_21]: Four years ago, I was very clear when I said,

2573
03:58:32,813 --> 03:58:37,697
[SPEAKER_21]: All I wanted to see is what we're paying people out in the legal line.

2574
03:58:38,357 --> 03:58:39,999
[SPEAKER_21]: That's what I've asked for for years.

2575
03:58:41,760 --> 03:58:46,424
[SPEAKER_21]: In the pushing this down can down the road, pushing it down the road has come to this.

2576
03:58:47,705 --> 03:58:50,607
[SPEAKER_21]: It's come to a legal document that says this is what we need.

2577
03:58:51,888 --> 03:58:52,769
[SPEAKER_21]: But we don't have this.

2578
03:58:52,829 --> 03:58:53,429
[SPEAKER_21]: We don't have time.

2579
03:58:53,449 --> 03:58:53,829
[SPEAKER_21]: We have this.

2580
03:58:54,170 --> 03:58:55,871
[SPEAKER_21]: This is the emails that we received.

2581
03:58:57,252 --> 03:58:58,253
[SPEAKER_21]: Legal expenses.

2582
03:58:59,731 --> 03:59:09,898
[SPEAKER_21]: Dear President, expressing what the Chief of Staff has sent to us back in the day, expressing, sharing with us what neighboring communities have spent.

2583
03:59:12,640 --> 03:59:13,480
[SPEAKER_21]: That's not what we asked.

2584
03:59:13,520 --> 03:59:14,481
[SPEAKER_21]: We never asked that.

2585
03:59:14,761 --> 03:59:18,423
[SPEAKER_21]: But you're going to spend time going through that to prove what point?

2586
03:59:18,744 --> 03:59:19,484
[SPEAKER_21]: The gotcha game?

2587
03:59:20,245 --> 03:59:23,827
[SPEAKER_21]: So she can say that we're doing our due diligence?

2588
03:59:24,607 --> 03:59:27,269
[SPEAKER_21]: It only looks shady.

2589
03:59:27,409 --> 03:59:28,350
[SPEAKER_21]: It doesn't look right.

2590
03:59:29,805 --> 03:59:33,706
[SPEAKER_21]: We can go back to her other emails that she's told us that she's done.

2591
03:59:34,086 --> 03:59:36,627
[SPEAKER_21]: And let's all be prepared.

2592
03:59:36,667 --> 03:59:47,430
[SPEAKER_21]: In a minute, in a minute, our chief of staff might come back to the podium and say that my aggression has put her in a bad way.

2593
03:59:48,310 --> 03:59:50,631
[SPEAKER_21]: So I want us to be prepared for that, because my lawyer is.

2594
03:59:52,291 --> 03:59:58,753
[SPEAKER_21]: Fire department, professional services line, this is what she said we asked for on June 3.

2595
04:00:00,787 --> 04:00:04,791
[SPEAKER_21]: American Arbitration Association $3,400 Harvey $1,000 New England ladder testing $3,000 KP Law $157,000 nets $2,600.

2596
04:00:04,831 --> 04:00:05,731
[SPEAKER_21]: But that's it.

2597
04:00:05,792 --> 04:00:07,053
[SPEAKER_21]: It doesn't break down what we asked for.

2598
04:00:07,113 --> 04:00:09,895
[SPEAKER_21]: We asked for a detail of what the law lines are, what we spent them on.

2599
04:00:29,495 --> 04:00:31,797
[SPEAKER_21]: And geez, why is Counselor Scott Pelley saying that?

2600
04:00:33,097 --> 04:00:43,224
[SPEAKER_21]: The fire department just settled a lawsuit with a firefighter that they chased all over his hometown with a private investigator who they fired.

2601
04:00:45,505 --> 04:00:46,406
[SPEAKER_21]: We went to court.

2602
04:00:46,846 --> 04:00:47,787
[SPEAKER_21]: They figured it out.

2603
04:00:48,627 --> 04:00:49,268
[SPEAKER_21]: We lost.

2604
04:00:49,648 --> 04:00:51,790
[SPEAKER_21]: He's getting his job back with back pay.

2605
04:00:54,191 --> 04:00:55,432
[SPEAKER_21]: Who's paying his attorney?

2606
04:00:57,376 --> 04:00:59,238
[SPEAKER_21]: Where are we paying the money to back pay him?

2607
04:01:00,899 --> 04:01:04,242
[SPEAKER_21]: If it's through insurance, how far have we gone over the retainer?

2608
04:01:04,302 --> 04:01:07,725
[SPEAKER_21]: These are the questions we're asked every day, Bob, every day.

2609
04:01:07,765 --> 04:01:09,546
[SPEAKER_21]: These are the questions that residents are asking us.

2610
04:01:10,087 --> 04:01:11,068
[SPEAKER_21]: That's one case.

2611
04:01:12,829 --> 04:01:14,170
[SPEAKER_21]: But then they talk about truths.

2612
04:01:15,451 --> 04:01:25,400
[SPEAKER_21]: The mayor sat in front of us weeks ago and said, we'd never negotiate and implement a non-disclosure, never.

2613
04:01:26,657 --> 04:01:32,321
[SPEAKER_21]: And what did we get the other day in the first two documents that were sent by the Chief of Staff and legal litigations?

2614
04:01:33,702 --> 04:01:34,642
[SPEAKER_21]: What did it say?

2615
04:01:35,303 --> 04:01:39,585
[SPEAKER_21]: It said, this is in place.

2616
04:01:42,487 --> 04:01:51,213
[SPEAKER_21]: So to sit at the podium and present a fact that, geez, this is way too much and this is something new, this isn't.

2617
04:01:52,450 --> 04:01:56,474
[SPEAKER_21]: This is something we've asked for that, forget the five months, this has been asked for for years.

2618
04:01:56,874 --> 04:01:58,555
[SPEAKER_21]: So let me make it as simple as possible.

2619
04:01:58,595 --> 04:02:00,097
[SPEAKER_21]: Maybe you can bring it back to your team, Bob.

2620
04:02:02,599 --> 04:02:19,794
[SPEAKER_21]: At minimum, share with us every single penny we spent for legal lines, for arbitrations, for settlements, for any outside fees incurred through that, which means private investigators,

2621
04:02:21,090 --> 04:02:25,331
[SPEAKER_21]: and then give us a breakdown of what our insurance looks like now.

2622
04:02:26,251 --> 04:02:29,912
[SPEAKER_21]: Because if we have a $100,000 retainer, did we go over it?

2623
04:02:30,472 --> 04:02:31,332
[SPEAKER_21]: That's what we need to know.

2624
04:02:31,672 --> 04:02:42,055
[SPEAKER_21]: At minimum, if the administration came back with that, maybe my counselors are telling me I'm wrong, if they at least came back with that, that's at least a semblance of what we asked for in the FOIA.

2625
04:02:42,475 --> 04:02:42,915
[SPEAKER_21]: At least.

2626
04:02:44,288 --> 04:02:47,749
[SPEAKER_21]: Correct me if I'm wrong, but if at least we got that, then we could say, you know what?

2627
04:02:48,329 --> 04:02:55,791
[SPEAKER_21]: That's good faith, and it's showing us for one department, for one law group, KP Law, $150,000 this year.

2628
04:02:56,751 --> 04:02:57,231
[SPEAKER_21]: That's one.

2629
04:02:58,652 --> 04:03:00,092
[SPEAKER_21]: Now, we know there's other law firms.

2630
04:03:01,773 --> 04:03:06,534
[SPEAKER_21]: We know there's other law firms that we're using for the fire.

2631
04:03:08,094 --> 04:03:08,875
[SPEAKER_21]: And that's just fire.

2632
04:03:09,775 --> 04:03:10,255
[SPEAKER_21]: You just heard

2633
04:03:11,357 --> 04:03:18,501
[SPEAKER_21]: You just heard the team's treasurer come up and talk about all of these lawsuits that have just been settled, and what's still in front of us, and how much of that is paid.

2634
04:03:20,222 --> 04:03:21,583
[SPEAKER_21]: So there are so many more things.

2635
04:03:22,163 --> 04:03:28,607
[SPEAKER_21]: The fighting with the 40B projects, how that went down, who paid the attorneys there.

2636
04:03:29,267 --> 04:03:29,867
[SPEAKER_21]: We lost.

2637
04:03:30,688 --> 04:03:32,289
[SPEAKER_21]: We fought it in appeals.

2638
04:03:34,630 --> 04:03:37,551
[SPEAKER_21]: Even if you get, I just ring off 10 things that are very easy.

2639
04:03:38,152 --> 04:03:39,933
[SPEAKER_21]: Come back in a month with that.

2640
04:03:40,962 --> 04:03:42,123
[SPEAKER_21]: Maybe that might move the needle.

2641
04:03:42,703 --> 04:03:51,627
[SPEAKER_21]: But don't come back with old emails from 2022 with Councilor Morrell showing us that we're on par with any other community when it comes to legal fees.

2642
04:03:51,868 --> 04:03:52,828
[SPEAKER_21]: That's disingenuine.

2643
04:03:55,489 --> 04:04:00,612
[SPEAKER_21]: So if feelings are hurt, this is the arena.

2644
04:04:02,273 --> 04:04:07,796
[SPEAKER_21]: My job as an elected official is to ask the questions that the residents that voted me in

2645
04:04:08,677 --> 04:04:09,497
[SPEAKER_21]: need me to ask.

2646
04:04:09,917 --> 04:04:15,038
[SPEAKER_21]: And if people are offended or hurt, maybe we'll find another line of work.

2647
04:04:16,579 --> 04:04:16,959
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

2648
04:04:19,459 --> 04:04:20,520
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you, Councillor Scarpelli.

2649
04:04:20,680 --> 04:04:22,820
[SPEAKER_07]: Any other Councillors have comments at this time?

2650
04:04:25,221 --> 04:04:31,662
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm just going to be pretty brief.

2651
04:04:32,582 --> 04:04:35,303
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think you end up with an agreement until there's a vote.

2652
04:04:36,023 --> 04:04:36,543
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think

2653
04:04:37,280 --> 04:04:42,064
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, hearing from three counselors over email or phone is a negotiation.

2654
04:04:44,006 --> 04:04:45,827
[SPEAKER_07]: This is the place where the discussions happen.

2655
04:04:45,927 --> 04:04:48,930
[SPEAKER_07]: In the past, this is the place where the discussions have happened.

2656
04:04:49,651 --> 04:04:52,173
[SPEAKER_07]: Clearly, we're at a point tonight where there's not an agreement.

2657
04:04:54,855 --> 04:05:00,080
[SPEAKER_07]: I do want to say I think we got pretty close on many of the items other than the law department budget.

2658
04:05:00,480 --> 04:05:01,441
[SPEAKER_07]: I have concerns with

2659
04:05:02,373 --> 04:05:09,637
[SPEAKER_07]: spending, you know, saying that there's a firefighter who costs a dollar and certain other kind of tips and tricks that were used.

2660
04:05:10,917 --> 04:05:17,101
[SPEAKER_07]: But by and large, my concern is with the law budget and I think that we've been very consistent for months about that and I don't think it's a surprise.

2661
04:05:18,601 --> 04:05:29,627
[SPEAKER_07]: And it kind of sounds to me like we actually got to the core of the issue tonight which is there isn't a document in this building that is a record of

2662
04:05:32,577 --> 04:05:35,760
[SPEAKER_07]: The legal expenses and the legal cases against the city, it just doesn't exist.

2663
04:05:36,301 --> 04:05:41,205
[SPEAKER_07]: There's not a list of here are all the legal cases, here are the arbitrations, here are the grievances.

2664
04:05:41,806 --> 04:05:42,887
[SPEAKER_07]: There's not a document that.

2665
04:05:44,160 --> 04:05:47,561
[SPEAKER_07]: Here's a list of all of the proceedings.

2666
04:05:49,521 --> 04:05:53,042
[SPEAKER_07]: And then because that doesn't exist, there's not a column that says this is how much this cost us.

2667
04:05:53,062 --> 04:05:54,042
[SPEAKER_07]: This is the status of it.

2668
04:05:54,642 --> 04:05:57,043
[SPEAKER_07]: And here's a link to the folder where all the relevant documents are.

2669
04:05:58,423 --> 04:06:07,065
[SPEAKER_07]: If that existed, then the public records request wouldn't be nearly as hard to put together as is being said.

2670
04:06:08,413 --> 04:06:13,078
[SPEAKER_07]: Maybe the public records request wouldn't have happened because it would have been easy to answer the February resolution.

2671
04:06:17,342 --> 04:06:25,690
[SPEAKER_07]: Beyond any of that, you know, I did try to get this down to a pretty specific distillation.

2672
04:06:28,250 --> 04:06:39,981
[SPEAKER_07]: About a week ago, this is last Wednesday around noon, in an email I sent, I said, hi mayor, I think one of the major outstanding questions from both of the council's resolutions this year and the budget discussions are legal expenses across the budget.

2673
04:06:40,542 --> 04:06:51,372
[SPEAKER_07]: For example, we had asked for a breakdown of the fire department professional services line item, both what it was spent on in fiscal 26 and the components that were used to decide the number for fiscal 27, but we haven't gotten that.

2674
04:06:51,940 --> 04:06:52,140
[SPEAKER_07]: Yet.

2675
04:06:52,440 --> 04:07:00,905
[SPEAKER_07]: Would it be possible to get a vendor export from admins of the city's financial software for fiscal 26 expenses for KP law and any other legal services vendors?

2676
04:07:00,985 --> 04:07:11,791
[SPEAKER_07]: And would it be possible for us to get an explanation of any line items where legal expenses appear or are expended, expected in the department budgets other than the law department, for example, in professional services line items?

2677
04:07:12,592 --> 04:07:20,116
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that's a pretty clear set of things asking for specific reports, specific information, specific data.

2678
04:07:21,687 --> 04:07:24,888
[SPEAKER_07]: We did receive the breakdown of the fire department professional services line item.

2679
04:07:25,988 --> 04:07:33,250
[SPEAKER_07]: Half of what we requested, we received the what it was spent on in fiscal 26, but not what the components were that where it's gonna be spent in fiscal 27.

2680
04:07:34,530 --> 04:07:44,673
[SPEAKER_07]: And that said that we spent $150,000 on KP law from that line item, which is essentially double what the professional services legal line item is in the law department budget.

2681
04:07:45,754 --> 04:07:59,940
[SPEAKER_07]: So that answer shows that law expenses are spread and legal expenses are spread across the budget in a way where it's not clear what the actual cost is to the city, and therefore we don't have the information to do effective oversight.

2682
04:08:01,460 --> 04:08:03,141
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that's the story here.

2683
04:08:03,761 --> 04:08:11,924
[SPEAKER_07]: There seems to be differing levels of trust in what solutions are required to get the answers that we're seeking.

2684
04:08:13,808 --> 04:08:16,249
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, one is the whole budget's got to go one twelfth.

2685
04:08:16,429 --> 04:08:23,412
[SPEAKER_07]: One is a significant reduction in the law department budget and the request to come back with information and a supplemental appropriation.

2686
04:08:26,734 --> 04:08:32,856
[SPEAKER_07]: But it sounds like we all agree on the substance of this, which is we've been asking the same questions for six months.

2687
04:08:34,377 --> 04:08:41,060
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't disagree that work has been done to provide responses and that those responses contain some information that we didn't have before.

2688
04:08:41,770 --> 04:08:51,998
[SPEAKER_07]: But I don't think that those responses actually have enough information for us to answer the question, which is, how much are we spending on legal expenses across the city budget?

2689
04:08:54,640 --> 04:09:02,566
[SPEAKER_07]: And then back to where we were three hours ago, Councilor Seng's point of, is that the best way that we should be doing this as a city?

2690
04:09:03,146 --> 04:09:05,688
[SPEAKER_07]: And I do think that our job is, that's part of our job.

2691
04:09:05,948 --> 04:09:08,470
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's where we are.

2692
04:09:08,490 --> 04:09:10,352
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think we're gonna,

2693
04:09:12,640 --> 04:09:13,700
[SPEAKER_07]: come to an agreement tonight.

2694
04:09:13,740 --> 04:09:18,622
[SPEAKER_07]: There's obviously significant disagreement between the council and the administration.

2695
04:09:19,903 --> 04:09:24,944
[SPEAKER_07]: And there are essentially three votes left, although I actually do have one more thing I'd like to do after this.

2696
04:09:25,004 --> 04:09:25,685
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry, everybody.

2697
04:09:28,025 --> 04:09:38,549
[SPEAKER_07]: But we have the B paper from Councillor Scarpelli to move to a 112th budget.

2698
04:09:39,849 --> 04:09:41,510
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there a second on that B paper?

2699
04:09:45,860 --> 04:09:55,326
[SPEAKER_07]: I will second it and then we'll take the cut and then we will go to the final vote on the whole budget.

2700
04:09:58,028 --> 04:10:05,773
[SPEAKER_07]: So we have a B paper from Councilor Scarpelli, seconded by me to move to a 112th budget.

2701
04:10:06,153 --> 04:10:08,095
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further discussion by members of the council?

2702
04:10:10,476 --> 04:10:13,358
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, we'll go to the floor, members of the public.

2703
04:10:13,812 --> 04:10:16,614
[SPEAKER_07]: If you could provide your name and city for the record, and you'll have three minutes.

2704
04:10:18,074 --> 04:10:21,776
[SPEAKER_05]: All right, Simon Alcindor, 44 Tainter Street.

2705
04:10:22,337 --> 04:10:27,980
[SPEAKER_05]: So I feel like I'm getting a lot of echoes from a couple of fights I've already been in this year related to politics.

2706
04:10:29,621 --> 04:10:31,502
[SPEAKER_05]: And it really comes down to questions.

2707
04:10:31,722 --> 04:10:35,344
[SPEAKER_05]: The first one is, where the hell is my audit?

2708
04:10:35,724 --> 04:10:37,945
[SPEAKER_05]: As you may know from state legislature.

2709
04:10:38,586 --> 04:10:41,167
[SPEAKER_05]: The second one is, are you going to fund us or fail us?

2710
04:10:44,812 --> 04:11:01,645
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that it's very interesting just looking at this, because I think this also requires a separate, this again, like as Councilor Behrs was referring to, this requires again a question.

2711
04:11:02,245 --> 04:11:11,332
[SPEAKER_05]: How much are we going to trust this group that has continued to use mafia-like tactics to attempt to get what they want out of us?

2712
04:11:14,191 --> 04:11:20,472
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, I would say that I would presume that the answer is that we're not going to trust that group for the most part.

2713
04:11:22,933 --> 04:11:29,474
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think when it comes down to it, really the best way of expressing that is through the 112th's budget.

2714
04:11:29,534 --> 04:11:43,077
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, the other reason why I support the 112th's budget is that, simply put, I'm somebody who evaluates policy a lot just like, literally as a job in some cases, as a policy debate judge.

2715
04:11:44,247 --> 04:12:03,859
[SPEAKER_05]: And one of the things I'm looking at here is I'm really struggling to see, because what I'm seeing here is a lot of what Mr. Scarpelli is talking about, where essentially the 112th budget functions as a continuation of what the current year's budget is.

2716
04:12:04,540 --> 04:12:09,703
[SPEAKER_05]: While it might be unfortunate that some raises might not come as quickly as we might hope,

2717
04:12:10,555 --> 04:12:16,257
[SPEAKER_05]: in the end, if we are really able to actually pressure this administration to making change, I think that is what's needed.

2718
04:12:16,637 --> 04:12:33,041
[SPEAKER_05]: Instead of having, instead of giving them this out of, that we're not really holding any real pressure to the administration, while there might be some fears of a poor lack of stability, I think that in terms of actual concrete evidence, I think that

2719
04:12:34,915 --> 04:12:52,936
[SPEAKER_05]: There has been a lot more for me that really makes me feel as if a 112th budget will actually be able to apply pressure just generally because it makes sure that there is actually some motive for the administration to come back.

2720
04:12:55,501 --> 04:12:56,401
[SPEAKER_05]: actually do stuff.

2721
04:12:56,501 --> 04:13:02,184
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't think that, considering the fact that, like, it's not like there isn't any time for us to go over this again.

2722
04:13:02,304 --> 04:13:06,245
[SPEAKER_05]: I mean, like, it might be inconvenient, but that's sort of what happens.

2723
04:13:08,606 --> 04:13:10,327
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

2724
04:13:10,547 --> 04:13:19,871
[SPEAKER_05]: And finally, I just want to say that the chief of staff tried to say that we're suddenly caring about union employees is a bit rich, but, you know, that's besides the point.

2725
04:13:20,611 --> 04:13:20,891
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

2726
04:13:23,397 --> 04:13:24,277
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

2727
04:13:24,637 --> 04:13:28,678
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing no hands on Zoom, state the podium, name and address, name and city for the record, please.

2728
04:13:28,698 --> 04:13:29,519
[SPEAKER_07]: You'll have three minutes.

2729
04:13:29,919 --> 04:13:32,059
[SPEAKER_07]: I guess I'm in 499 Main Street, Medford.

2730
04:13:33,059 --> 04:13:51,284
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that what might be helpful moving this forward to resolution is if the administration could identify with specificity what the actual blocker is and what's preventing them from getting this information.

2731
04:13:51,962 --> 04:13:54,063
[SPEAKER_04]: Not just say, we can't get it, it's hard.

2732
04:13:54,483 --> 04:13:55,984
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's say, what's hard about it?

2733
04:13:56,524 --> 04:14:00,887
[SPEAKER_04]: This is what I use when I'm mentoring people that might get fired.

2734
04:14:01,647 --> 04:14:10,351
[SPEAKER_04]: So what is the specific thing that is preventing this goal from being accomplished?

2735
04:14:11,052 --> 04:14:13,253
[SPEAKER_04]: And then figure out a way to get over that.

2736
04:14:14,028 --> 04:14:15,490
[SPEAKER_04]: This is not an insurmountable task.

2737
04:14:16,130 --> 04:14:30,986
[SPEAKER_04]: Honestly, it shouldn't be super challenging, so there must be some sort of thing that the administration is accidentally overlooking, giving them the benefit of the doubt, because literally, you know what law firms you have hired.

2738
04:14:31,847 --> 04:14:32,447
[SPEAKER_04]: You know that.

2739
04:14:33,663 --> 04:14:38,008
[SPEAKER_04]: Even if you don't know specifically what you've used them for, you know what firms you've used.

2740
04:14:38,669 --> 04:14:45,657
[SPEAKER_04]: And then just go and backtrack to the firms what they have charged you and you have paid them.

2741
04:14:46,478 --> 04:14:47,680
[SPEAKER_04]: They will have those records.

2742
04:14:48,220 --> 04:14:50,683
[SPEAKER_04]: If they don't, they're committing malpractice.

2743
04:14:51,615 --> 04:14:53,576
[SPEAKER_04]: So, you can do this.

2744
04:14:54,097 --> 04:14:55,838
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, it's not hard, actually.

2745
04:14:55,938 --> 04:14:58,039
[SPEAKER_04]: It's actually pretty straightforward.

2746
04:14:58,159 --> 04:15:10,807
[SPEAKER_04]: Even if you, for some unfathomable reason, don't maintain a record of your own legal matters in the City Hall, also start doing that.

2747
04:15:11,547 --> 04:15:11,948
[SPEAKER_04]: Please.

2748
04:15:14,469 --> 04:15:14,889
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, what?

2749
04:15:15,650 --> 04:15:19,512
[SPEAKER_04]: So, I think that you could, like, this is the way forward.

2750
04:15:19,532 --> 04:15:20,773
[SPEAKER_04]: Like, this is not super difficult.

2751
04:15:21,463 --> 04:15:28,048
[SPEAKER_04]: challenging I think like, you know, can hold hands and take the leap and make it happen.

2752
04:15:28,849 --> 04:15:31,111
[SPEAKER_04]: Please, we're just asking for competence.

2753
04:15:31,992 --> 04:15:32,292
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

2754
04:15:37,556 --> 04:15:38,117
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

2755
04:15:38,357 --> 04:15:39,938
[SPEAKER_07]: Any further public comments?

2756
04:15:44,462 --> 04:15:50,346
[SPEAKER_07]: Seeing none, on the motion of Councilor Scarpelli, seconded by myself.

2757
04:15:51,851 --> 04:15:57,012
[SPEAKER_07]: as a rule of necessity since there was no other second and I was willing to second it.

2758
04:16:01,913 --> 04:16:02,813
[SPEAKER_07]: That would be preferable.

2759
04:16:07,454 --> 04:16:08,734
[SPEAKER_07]: Seconded by Councilor Sang.

2760
04:16:14,115 --> 04:16:15,155
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

2761
04:16:22,646 --> 04:16:23,346
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lennon?

2762
04:16:24,447 --> 04:16:24,687
[SPEAKER_20]: No.

2763
04:16:27,849 --> 04:16:28,389
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Malay?

2764
04:16:28,409 --> 04:16:28,469
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2765
04:16:31,470 --> 04:16:32,351
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scarpelli?

2766
04:16:32,791 --> 04:16:32,971
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2767
04:16:34,352 --> 04:16:35,052
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Singh?

2768
04:16:35,232 --> 04:16:35,372
[SPEAKER_19]: No.

2769
04:16:37,213 --> 04:16:38,374
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

2770
04:16:39,074 --> 04:16:39,274
[SPEAKER_19]: No.

2771
04:16:41,315 --> 04:16:42,176
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Beers?

2772
04:16:43,096 --> 04:16:43,436
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

2773
04:16:43,636 --> 04:16:45,137
[SPEAKER_07]: Three in the affirmative, four in the negative.

2774
04:16:45,157 --> 04:16:46,558
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion fails.

2775
04:16:52,188 --> 04:16:54,870
[SPEAKER_07]: on the motion of Councillor Seng.

2776
04:16:55,010 --> 04:16:58,793
[SPEAKER_07]: And Councillor Seng, could you send that in writing?

2777
04:17:06,499 --> 04:17:12,243
[SPEAKER_07]: We have the motion of Councillor Seng on the main paper to cut the law department budget by 83%, 010-151-5110 by 182,000.

2778
04:17:18,668 --> 04:17:20,690
[SPEAKER_07]: $576.33, 0101515302, $130,000, 0101515761, $41,666.67, 0101515762, $62,500, 0101515763, $8,333.33.

2779
04:17:18,988 --> 04:17:20,690
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'll invite the administration to come back to the council.

2780
04:17:47,012 --> 04:17:52,957
[SPEAKER_07]: with the requested info on legal expenses alongside a request to fund the department for the remaining 10 months of the fiscal year.

2781
04:17:54,158 --> 04:17:56,761
[SPEAKER_07]: Motion by Councilor Sang, seconded by Councilor Callahan.

2782
04:17:56,801 --> 04:17:59,483
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there any further discussion on that motion by members of the council?

2783
04:17:59,503 --> 04:18:03,947
[SPEAKER_13]: I move the question.

2784
04:18:06,149 --> 04:18:12,935
[SPEAKER_07]: On the motion of Councilor Lazaro to move the question, move the previous question, which is,

2785
04:18:14,584 --> 04:18:17,766
[SPEAKER_07]: seconded by councilor saying that requires a two-thirds majority.

2786
04:18:17,806 --> 04:18:21,668
[SPEAKER_07]: So we're going to take two votes on this one motion, but this is Robert's Rules.

2787
04:18:21,708 --> 04:18:27,692
[SPEAKER_07]: When you move the previous question, a two-thirds majority ends debate and then there'll be a vote on the motion.

2788
04:18:27,832 --> 04:18:30,434
[SPEAKER_07]: So we're taking two votes on this one.

2789
04:18:36,418 --> 04:18:40,060
[SPEAKER_07]: So this is on the motion essentially to move the previous question to end debate.

2790
04:18:40,660 --> 04:18:43,162
[SPEAKER_07]: Then we'll take a vote on the actual cut and then

2791
04:18:44,247 --> 04:18:47,488
[SPEAKER_07]: There can be a motion to approve the budget with the reductions.

2792
04:19:04,893 --> 04:19:05,313
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, sorry.

2793
04:19:05,553 --> 04:19:06,574
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

2794
04:19:07,734 --> 04:19:08,994
[SPEAKER_07]: This is to move the question.

2795
04:19:09,014 --> 04:19:09,955
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah.

2796
04:19:09,995 --> 04:19:10,715
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan.

2797
04:19:14,785 --> 04:19:15,465
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming?

2798
04:19:16,085 --> 04:19:16,425
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2799
04:19:18,066 --> 04:19:18,646
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Malay?

2800
04:19:18,686 --> 04:19:18,746
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2801
04:19:21,166 --> 04:19:22,027
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scarpelli?

2802
04:19:22,047 --> 04:19:22,147
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2803
04:19:23,647 --> 04:19:24,387
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Sang?

2804
04:19:24,407 --> 04:19:25,748
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2805
04:19:25,768 --> 04:19:26,988
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro?

2806
04:19:27,368 --> 04:19:27,668
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes.

2807
04:19:29,288 --> 04:19:29,989
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Pierce?

2808
04:19:30,209 --> 04:19:30,549
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

2809
04:19:31,269 --> 04:19:31,969
[SPEAKER_07]: That motion passes.

2810
04:19:32,009 --> 04:19:39,191
[SPEAKER_07]: Debate has ended on the motion by Councilor Sang, seconded by Councilor Callahan as read to make cuts to the law department budget.

2811
04:19:39,231 --> 04:19:40,351
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

2812
04:19:45,382 --> 04:19:46,082
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan.

2813
04:19:46,102 --> 04:19:46,162
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2814
04:19:48,223 --> 04:19:48,983
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Lemming.

2815
04:19:49,623 --> 04:19:49,943
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes.

2816
04:19:51,804 --> 04:19:52,604
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Malayne.

2817
04:19:52,624 --> 04:19:53,104
Yes.

2818
04:19:54,124 --> 04:19:55,205
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Scarpelli.

2819
04:19:55,545 --> 04:19:55,665
Yes.

2820
04:19:56,685 --> 04:19:57,485
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Sang.

2821
04:19:57,505 --> 04:19:58,606
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes.

2822
04:19:58,626 --> 04:19:59,846
[SPEAKER_19]: Vice President Lazaro.

2823
04:20:00,366 --> 04:20:00,666
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

2824
04:20:02,087 --> 04:20:02,907
[SPEAKER_19]: And President Peers.

2825
04:20:03,547 --> 04:20:03,827
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

2826
04:20:03,987 --> 04:20:05,308
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean the affirmative, none of the negative.

2827
04:20:05,348 --> 04:20:06,408
[SPEAKER_07]: The motion passes.

2828
04:20:07,288 --> 04:20:12,250
[SPEAKER_07]: On the main budget, is there a motion to approve as reduced?

2829
04:20:12,970 --> 04:20:13,930
[SPEAKER_13]: Motion to approve as reduced.

2830
04:20:15,139 --> 04:20:21,823
[SPEAKER_07]: on the motion of Councilor Seng to approve the budget as reduced, seconded by.

2831
04:20:22,164 --> 04:20:22,564
[SPEAKER_13]: Second.

2832
04:20:22,624 --> 04:20:23,905
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilor Callahan.

2833
04:20:25,686 --> 04:20:26,827
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

2834
04:20:31,610 --> 04:20:32,370
[SPEAKER_19]: Councilor Callahan.

2835
